{"title_page": "Thom Bray", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American actor and writer}}\n{{For|the saloon-keeper and criminal|Tom Bray}}\n{{other people|Thomas Bray}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Thom Bray\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Thomas Edward Bray\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1954|4|30}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lawrenceville, New Jersey|Lawrenceville]], New Jersey, U.S.<ref name=\"8q\">{{cite web|url=http://www.retroist.com/2007/01/17/8-questions-with-thom-bray/|work=Retroist|title=8 Questions with Thom Bray|date=January 17, 2007|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Actor\n| yearsactive        = 1980\u20132019\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Edward \"Thom\" Bray'''  (born April 30, 1954) is an American actor and writer perhaps best known for his role as Murray \"Boz\" Bozinsky in the detective TV series ''[[Riptide (American TV series)|Riptide]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opb.org/television/programs/artbeat/segment/thom-bray-actor-and-educator/|work=Oregon Public Broadcasting (OPB)|title=Thom Bray, actor and educator|date=December 16, 2008|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref> He made his film debut in the [[slasher film]] ''[[The Prowler (1981 film)|The Prowler]]'' (1981) and later appeared in [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[Prince of Darkness (film)|Prince of Darkness]]'' (1987), and ''[[The Horror Show]]'' (1989). His work has been primarily in television, and his most recent credit was in 2012 on an episode of the [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] series ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''. \n\nBray was a drama teacher and also taught [[television studies]].\n\n==Life and career==\nBray was born and raised in the [[Lawrenceville, New Jersey|Lawrenceville]] section of [[Lawrence Township, Mercer County, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"8q\"/> His first television role was in the short-lived TV series ''[[Breaking Away (TV series)|Breaking Away]]'' as Cyril. Later on in the 1980s, he would star in the TV series ''[[Harry (U.S. TV series)|Harry]]'' with future Academy Award-winning actor [[Alan Arkin]]. In 1990, he did the voice of Wilbur Finletter in the cartoon series ''[[Attack of the Killer Tomatoes: The Animated Series]]'' and voices in various other animated works.\n\nHis first feature film was in the 1981 film ''[[The Prowler (1981 film)|The Prowler]]''. He has appeared in other films like the comedy ''[[Burglar (film)|Burglar]]'' as a [[shoplifter]], director [[John Carpenter]]'s  ''[[Prince of Darkness (film)|Prince of Darkness]]'' (both 1987), and in the horror genre, ''[[DeepStar Six]]'' and ''[[The Horror Show]]'', both in 1989. Thom appeared in the 1988 made-for-TV-movie ''Lady Mobster''.\n\nBray would later become a writer and producer for television, including the shows: ''[[Designing Women]]''. ''[[Now and Again]]'', ''[[Fired Up (TV series)|Fired Up]]'' and ''[[Nash Bridges]]''.\n\nHe has many stage credits in regional and stock theatres throughout the country.{{citation needed|date=July 2007}}\n\nHe was a drama teacher at Five Oaks and Rachel Carson Middle School, and also taught [[television Studies]] at [[Portland State University]]. He is the father to three children.\n\nBray retired from his teaching career in 2019, after 13 years.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[The Prowler (1981 film)|The Prowler]]'' || Ben || \n|-\n| 1983 || ''Prime Times'' || Various || Television film\n|-\n| 1983 || ''An Uncommon Love'' || Molson || Television film\n|-\n| 1984 || ''Last of the Great Survivors '' || Eddie || Television film\n|-\n| 1984 || ''Anatomy of an Illness'' || Intern || Television film\n|-\n| 1984 || ''Concrete Beat'' || || Television film\n|-\n| 1987 || ''[[Burglar (film)|Burglar]]'' || Shoplifter in Bookstore || \n|-\n| 1987 || ''[[Prince of Darkness (film)|Prince of Darkness]]'' || Etchison || \n|-\n| 1988||''Lady Mobster'' || Paul Castle || Television film\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[DeepStar Six]]'' || Johnny Hodges ||\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[The Horror Show]]'' || Peter Campbell ||\n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[Child in the Night]]'' || || Television film\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Stripperland'' || Dr. Logan || \n|-\n|}\n\n;Television\n*''[[Breaking Away (TV series)|Breaking Away]]'' (1980\u201381) \u2013 Cyril (8 episodes)\n*''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]'' (1981) \u2013 Len Holland (1 episode)\n* ''[[Remington Steele]]'' (1982) \u2013 Sheldon Quarry (1 episode)\n* ''[[One Day at a Time (1975 TV series)|One Day at a Time]]'' (1982) \u2013 Hal (4 episodes)\n*''[[Quincy, M.E.]]'' (1983) \u2013 Joby Kenyon (1 episode)\n*''[[The Love Boat]]'' (1986) \u2013 Lowell Mandell (1 episode)\n* ''[[Riptide (American TV series)|Riptide]]'' (1984\u201386) \u2013 Murray 'Boz' Bozinsky (56 episodes)\n* ''[[Harry (U.S. TV series)|Harry]]'' (1987) \u2013 Lawrence Pendleton (7 episodes)\n* ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'' (1987) \u2013 Dorian Beecher (Saison 3 episode 11)\n*''[[New Kids on the Block (TV series)|New Kids on the Block]]'' (1990) \u2013 Voice (14 episodes)\n*''[[Mancuso, F.B.I.]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (1987 TV series)|Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]]'' (1990) \u2013 Howie Hardy (2 episodes)\n* ''[[The Adventures of Don Coyote and Sancho Panda]]'' \u2013 Voices \n*''[[Attack of the Killer Tomatoes (TV series)|Attack of the Killer Tomatoes]]'' (1990\u201391) \u2013 Wilbur Finletter / Floyd Bridgework / Tomato Wilbur (21 episodes)\n*''[[The Legend of Prince Valiant]]'' (1992) \u2013 Voice (1 episode)\n* ''[[Hearts Afire]]'' (1993) \u2013 Jerry/Norman Bates (1 episode)\n*''[[The District]]'' (2002) \u2013 EPA Agent (1 episode)\n*''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]'' (2012) \u2013 Bartholomew (1 episode)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0106257|name=Thom Bray}}\n*[http://www.thom-bray.com Official Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bray, Thom}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Lawrence Township, Mercer County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Portland, Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American actor and writer}}\n{{For|the saloon-keeper and criminal|Tom Bray}}\n{{other people|Thomas Bray}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Thom Bray\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Thomas Edward Bray\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1954|4|30}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lawrenceville, New Jersey|Lawrenceville]], New Jersey, U.S.<ref name=\"8q\">{{cite web|url=http://www.retroist.com/2007/01/17/8-questions-with-thom-bray/|work=Retroist|title=8 Questions with Thom Bray|date=January 17, 2007|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Actor\n| yearsactive        = 1980\u20132019\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Edward \"Thom\" Bray'''  (born April 30, 1954) is an American actor and writer perhaps best known for his role as Murray \"Boz\" Bozinsky in the detective TV series ''[[Riptide (American TV series)|Riptide]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opb.org/television/programs/artbeat/segment/thom-bray-actor-and-educator/|work=Oregon Public Broadcasting (OPB)|title=Thom Bray, actor and educator|date=December 16, 2008|accessdate=October 25, 2015}}</ref> He made his film debut in the [[slasher film]] ''[[The Prowler (1981 film)|The Prowler]]'' (1981) and later appeared in [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[Prince of Darkness (film)|Prince of Darkness]]'' (1987), and ''[[The Horror Show]]'' (1989). His work has been primarily in television, and his most recent credit was in 2012 on an episode of the [[TNT Network|TNT]] series ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''. \n\nBray was a drama teacher and also taught [[television studies]].\n\n==Life and career==\nBray was born and raised in the [[Lawrenceville, New Jersey|Lawrenceville]] section of [[Lawrence Township, Mercer County, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"8q\"/> His first television role was in the short-lived TV series ''[[Breaking Away (TV series)|Breaking Away]]'' as Cyril. Later on in the 1980s, he would star in the TV series ''[[Harry (U.S. TV series)|Harry]]'' with future Academy Award-winning actor [[Alan Arkin]]. In 1990, he did the voice of Wilbur Finletter in the cartoon series ''[[Attack of the Killer Tomatoes: The Animated Series]]'' and voices in various other animated works.\n\nHis first feature film was in the 1981 film ''[[The Prowler (1981 film)|The Prowler]]''. He has appeared in other films like the comedy ''[[Burglar (film)|Burglar]]'' as a [[shoplifter]], director [[John Carpenter]]'s  ''[[Prince of Darkness (film)|Prince of Darkness]]'' (both 1987), and in the horror genre, ''[[DeepStar Six]]'' and ''[[The Horror Show]]'', both in 1989. Thom appeared in the 1988 made-for-TV-movie ''Lady Mobster''.\n\nBray would later become a writer and producer for television, including the shows: ''[[Designing Women]]''. ''[[Now and Again]]'', ''[[Fired Up (TV series)|Fired Up]]'' and ''[[Nash Bridges]]''.\n\nHe has many stage credits in regional and stock theatres throughout the country.{{citation needed|date=July 2007}}\n\nHe was a drama teacher at Five Oaks and Rachel Carson Middle School, and also taught [[television Studies]] at [[Portland State University]]. He is the father to three children.\n\nBray retired from his teaching career in 2019, after 13 years.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[The Prowler (1981 film)|The Prowler]]'' || Ben || \n|-\n| 1983 || ''Prime Times'' || Various || Television film\n|-\n| 1983 || ''An Uncommon Love'' || Molson || Television film\n|-\n| 1984 || ''Last of the Great Survivors '' || Eddie || Television film\n|-\