{"title_page": "Glenn Fredly", "text_new": "{{short description|Indonesian singer-songwriter}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image            = Glenn Fredly.jpg\n| name             = Glenn Fredly\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Glenn Fredly Deviano Latuihamallo\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1975|09|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Jakarta]], Indonesia\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2020|04|08|1975|09|30|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = Jakarta, Indonesia\n| origin           = [[Ambon Island|Ambon]]\n| occupation       = Singer-songwriter-producer-actor\n| genre            = {{flat list|\n*[[Jazz]]\n*[[Pop music|pop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n}}\n| instrument       = Vocals, Guitar, Bass Guitar, Piano\n| years_active     = 1995\u20132020\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = [https://www.glennfredly.com glennfredly.com]\n}}\n\n'''Glenn Fredly Deviano Latuihamallo''' (30 September 1975 \u2013 8 April 2020), known professionally as '''Glenn Fredly''', was an [[Indonesia]]n [[R&B]] singer and songwriter as well as producer and actor. Entering the music industry after winning a singing contest in 1995, he released more than 10 albums. He produced new talented artists like female vocalist [[Yura (Indonesian singer)|Yura]] and male soloist Gilbert Pohan. He also produced ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]''. In 2013, he served as a coach for ''[[The Voice Indonesia]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nFredly was born on 30 September 1975 to Hengky and Linda Latuihamallo. He was the first of five children.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} Fredly was of [[Moluccas|Molucca]]n descent.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | last = Yudo\n  | first = Aji\n  | title = Glenn Fredly Menjadi Produser Album Maluku Hip-Hop Community\n  | publisher = [[Rolling Stone (magazine)|RollingStone]] Indonesia\n  | date = 11 June 2011\n  | url = http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/05/11/125927/1637229/1093/glenn-fredly-menjadi-produser-album-maluku-hip-hop-community\n  | access-date = 7 September 2011\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110517214210/http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/05/11/125927/1637229/1093/glenn-fredly-menjadi-produser-album-maluku-hip-hop-community\n  | archive-date = 17 May 2011\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1995, he won the [[Cipta Pesona Bintang]] singing contest.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} That same year, he joined the rock band Funk Section.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} The following year, he was a finalist in the [[Asia Song Festival]].{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} In 1998, Fredly left Funk Section to be a solo R&B singer, feeling that it suited his vocal style better. He released his first album, ''GLENN'', that year. It was relatively well received, selling 50 thousand copies; R&B was generally not popular in Indonesia at the time.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}}\n\nIn 2000, Fredly released his second solo album, ''Kembali'' (''Return''), with the single \"Kasih Putih\" (\"White Love\") receiving much airplay.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} In 2001, he placed third in the Russian Asia Dauzy International Song Festival.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}\n\nHe married singer [[Dewi Sandra]] in [[Uluwatu]], [[Bali]] on 3 April 2006. Glenn filed for divorce in 2009.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-25, Glenn files}}\n\nIn March 2009, Fredly was one of the main performers in a tribute concert to deceased Indonesian singer [[Chrisye]] during the [[Java Jazz Festival]].{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}} That same year, he performed tribute concerts to [[Michael Jackson]] in five cities throughout Indonesia, covering Jackson's hit songs.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}\n\nIn 2011, he joined with Tompi and [[Sandhy Sondoro]] to perform a set of concerts under the name Trio Lestari (The Eternal Trio).{{sfn|Fawilia 2011-06-26, An evening}}\n\nFredly celebrated his 17th anniversary in the music business with a sold-out concert in front of 7,500 people at [[Istora Gelora Bung Karno]] on 2 September 2012.\n\nIn 2014, he entered film producing with the film ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]'', which received the best movie award from the [[Indonesian Film Festival]].\n\n==Death==\nFredly died on 8 April 2020 at the age of 44 in Jakarta. It was reported that his cause of death was [[meningitis]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Glenn Fredly Meninggal karena Sakit Meningitis|url=https://kumparan.com/kumparanhits/glenn-fredly-meninggal-karena-sakit-meningitis-1tBV6Z3yxZD|language=id|website=Kumparan.com|date=8 April 2020}}</ref> He is survived by his wife for 7.5 months (married on 19 August 2019), the 25-year-old Mutia Ayu, and their 40-day-old daughter, who was born on 28 February 2020.\n\n==Influences==\nFredly credited [[Michael Jackson]] as being one of his influences, saying that Jackson inspired him \"through his music, his style, his dancing, everything\". He also credited Jackson's humanitarian work for inspiring his own charitable work.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} He also admired [[Marvin Gaye]] and [[Quincy Jones]],{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} and was a fan of [[Chrisye]].{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}}\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:G.Fredly.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Fredly during performance in the Netherlands in 2011.]]\n===Music===\n*''GLENN'' (1998)\n*''Kembali'' (''Return'', 2000)\n*''Selamat Pagi, Dunia'' (''Good Morning, World'', 2003)\n*''Selamat Pagi, Dunia Repackaged'' (2004)\n*DVD & CD Selamat Pagi,Dunia Repackaged (2004)\n*''OST Cinta Silver'' (2005)\n*''Aku dan Wanita'' (''Women and I'', 2006)\n*''Terang'' (''Clear'',  2006)\n*''Happy Sunday (2007)\n*''Private Collection (2008)\n*''DVD Tribute to Chrisye (2009)\n*''Lovevolution'' (2010)\n*DVD Lovevolution Live in Esplanade  (2010)\n*''Luka, Cinta & Merdeka'' (2012)\n*''DVD Glenn Fredly & The Bakuucakar live at Lokananta'' (2012)\n\n===Movies===\n* ''[[Tanda Tanya]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]'' (2014)\n*Filosofi Kopi (2015)\n*Surat dari Praha (2016)\n*Pretty Boys (2019) \n** \n** \n** \n** \n** \n\n==References==\n;Footnotes\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/06/26/an-evening-with-trio-lestari.html|last=Fawilia|first=Aliendheasja |title=An evening with Trio Lestari |date=26 June 2011 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|Fawilia 2011-06-26, An evening}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/03/25/glenn-files-divorce.html|title=Glenn files for divorce|date=25 March 2009|work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-25, Glenn files}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://selebriti.indonesiaselebriti.com/selebriti/bio/283212744214/Glenn-Fredly|title=Glenn Fredly|date=|work=IndonesiaSelebriti.com|ref={{harvid|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}}|language=Indonesian|accessdate=29 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316153631/http://selebriti.indonesiaselebriti.com/selebriti/bio/283212744214/Glenn-Fredly|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/03/07/glenn-sing-chrisye-java-jazz.html|title=Glenn to sing for Chrisye in Java Jazz|date=7 March 2009 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/08/09/glenn-fredly-get-ready-welcome-new-glenn039.html|last=Kurniasari|first=Titik |title=Glenn Fredly: Get ready to welcome the `new Glenn' |date=9 August 2009 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.glennfredly.com/v4/ }}\n\n{{The Voice Indonesia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fredly, Glenn}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Moluccan people]]\n[[Category:Indonesian Christians]]\n[[Category:Indonesian male singers]]\n[[Category:Anugerah Musik Indonesia winners]]\n[[Category:People from Ambon]]\n[[Category:Deaths from meningitis]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indonesian singer-songwriter}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image            = Glenn Fredly.jpg\n| name             = Glenn Fredly\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Glenn Fredly Deviano Latuihamallo\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1975|09|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Jakarta]], Indonesia\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2020|04|08|1975|09|30|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = Jakarta, Indonesia\n| origin           = [[Ambon Island|Ambon]]\n| occupation       = Singer-songwriter-producer-actor\n| genre            = {{flat list|\n*[[Jazz]]\n*[[Pop music|pop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n}}\n| instrument       = Vocals, Guitar, Bass Guitar, Piano\n| years_active     = 1995\u20132020\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = [https://www.glennfredly.com glennfredly.com]\n}}\n\n'''Glenn Fredly Deviano Latuihamallo''' (30 September 1975 \u2013 8 April 2020), known professionally as '''Glenn Fredly''', was an [[Indonesia]]n [[R&B]] singer and songwriter as well as producer and actor. Entering the music industry after winning a singing contest in 1995, he released more than 10 albums. He produced new talented artists like female vocalist [[Yura (Indonesian singer)|Yura]] and male soloist Gilbert Pohan. He also produced ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]''. In 2013, he served as a coach for ''[[The Voice Indonesia]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nFredly was born on 30 September 1975 to Hengky and Linda Latuihamallo. He was the first of five children.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} Fredly was of [[Moluccas|Molucca]]n descent.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | last = Yudo\n  | first = Aji\n  | title = Glenn Fredly Menjadi Produser Album Maluku Hip-Hop Community\n  | publisher = [[Rolling Stone (magazine)|RollingStone]] Indonesia\n  | date = 11 June 2011\n  | url = http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/05/11/125927/1637229/1093/glenn-fredly-menjadi-produser-album-maluku-hip-hop-community\n  | access-date = 7 September 2011\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110517214210/http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/05/11/125927/1637229/1093/glenn-fredly-menjadi-produser-album-maluku-hip-hop-community\n  | archive-date = 17 May 2011\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1995, he won the [[Cipta Pesona Bintang]] singing contest.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} That same year, he joined the rock band Funk Section.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} The following year, he was a finalist in the [[Asia Song Festival]].{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} In 1998, Fredly left Funk Section to be a solo R&B singer, feeling that it suited his vocal style better. He released his first album, ''GLENN'', that year. It was relatively well received, selling 50 thousand copies; R&B was generally not popular in Indonesia at the time.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}}\n\nIn 2000, Fredly released his second solo album, ''Kembali'' (''Return''), with the single \"Kasih Putih\" (\"White Love\") receiving much airplay.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} In 2001, he placed third in the Russian Asia Dauzy International Song Festival.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}\n\nHe married singer [[Dewi Sandra]] in [[Uluwatu]], [[Bali]] on 3 April 2006. Glenn filed for divorce in 2009.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-25, Glenn files}}\n\nIn March 2009, Fredly was one of the main performers in a tribute concert to deceased Indonesian singer [[Chrisye]] during the [[Java Jazz Festival]].{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}} That same year, he performed tribute concerts to [[Michael Jackson]] in five cities throughout Indonesia, covering Jackson's hit songs.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}\n\nIn 2011, he joined with Tompi and [[Sandhy Sondoro]] to perform a set of concerts under the name Trio Lestari (The Eternal Trio).{{sfn|Fawilia 2011-06-26, An evening}}\n\nFredly celebrated his 17th anniversary in the music business with a sold-out concert in front of 7,500 people at [[Istora Gelora Bung Karno]] on 2 September 2012.\n\nIn 2014, he entered film producing with the film ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]'', which received the best movie award from the [[Indonesian Film Festival]].\n\n==Death==\nFredly died on 8 April 2020 at the age of 44 in Jakarta. It was reported that his cause of death was [[meningitis]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Glenn Fredly Meninggal karena Sakit Meningitis|url=https://kumparan.com/kumparanhits/glenn-fredly-meninggal-karena-sakit-meningitis-1tBV6Z3yxZD|language=id|website=Kumparan.com|date=8 April 2020}}</ref> He is survived by his wife for 7.5 months (married on 19 August 2019), the 25-year-old Mutia Ayu, and their 40-day-old daughter, who was born on 28 February 2020.\n\n==Influences==\nFredly credited [[Michael Jackson]] as being one of his influences, saying that Jackson inspired him \"through his music, his style, his dancing, everything\". He also credited Jackson's humanitarian work for inspiring his own charitable work.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} He also admired [[Marvin Gaye]] and [[Quincy Jones]],{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} and was a fan of [[Chrisye]].{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}}\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:G.Fredly.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Fredly during performance in the Netherlands in 2011.]]\n===Music===\n*''GLENN'' (1998)\n*''Kembali'' (''Return'', 2000)\n*''Selamat Pagi, Dunia'' (''Good Morning, World'', 2003)\n*''Selamat Pagi, Dunia Repackaged'' (2004)\n*DVD & CD Selamat Pagi,Dunia Repackaged (2004)\n*''OST Cinta Silver'' (2005)\n*''Aku dan Wanita'' (''Women and I'', 2006)\n*''Terang'' (''Clear'',  2006)\n*''Happy Sunday (2007)\n*''Private Collection (2008)\n*''DVD Tribute to Chrisye (2009)\n*''Lovevolution'' (2010)\n*DVD Lovevolution Live in Esplanade  (2010)\n*''Luka, Cinta & Merdeka'' (2012)\n*''DVD Glenn Fredly & The Bakuucakar live at Lokananta'' (2012)\n\n===Movies===\n* ''[[Tanda Tanya]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]'' (2014)\n*Filosofi Kopi (2015)\n*Surat dari Praha (2016)\n*Pretty Boys (2019)\n** {{judulfilm|Tanda Tanya||2011}} sebagai Aktor\n** {{judulfilm|Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku|Cahaya dari Timur|2014}} sebagai Produser dan Aktor\n** Filosofi Kopi (2015) sebagai Produser\n** Surat dari Praha (2016) sebagai Produser\n** Pretty Boys (2019) sebagai Aktor\n\n==References==\n;Footnotes\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/06/26/an-evening-with-trio-lestari.html|last=Fawilia|first=Aliendheasja |title=An evening with Trio Lestari |date=26 June 2011 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|Fawilia 2011-06-26, An evening}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/03/25/glenn-files-divorce.html|title=Glenn files for divorce|date=25 March 2009|work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-25, Glenn files}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://selebriti.indonesiaselebriti.com/selebriti/bio/283212744214/Glenn-Fredly|title=Glenn Fredly|date=|work=IndonesiaSelebriti.com|ref={{harvid|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}}|language=Indonesian|accessdate=29 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316153631/http://selebriti.indonesiaselebriti.com/selebriti/bio/283212744214/Glenn-Fredly|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/03/07/glenn-sing-chrisye-java-jazz.html|title=Glenn to sing for Chrisye in Java Jazz|date=7 March 2009 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/08/09/glenn-fredly-get-ready-welcome-new-glenn039.html|last=Kurniasari|first=Titik |title=Glenn Fredly: Get ready to welcome the `new Glenn' |date=9 August 2009 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.glennfredly.com/v4/ }}\n\n{{The Voice Indonesia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fredly, Glenn}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Moluccan people]]\n[[Category:Indonesian Christians]]\n[[Category:Indonesian male singers]]\n[[Category:Anugerah Musik Indonesia winners]]\n[[Category:People from Ambon]]\n[[Category:Deaths from meningitis]]\n", "name_user": "Goudotmobi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glenn_Fredly"}
{"title_page": "Roberto Amadio", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist and sports manager}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Roberto Amadio\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Roberto Amadio\n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1963|7|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Portogruaro]], [[Italy]]\n| currentteam    = {{ct|CAN}}<ref>{{cite web|author=ProCyclingStats |url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/1688991-Roberto-Amadio |title=Roberto Amadio |publisher=ProCyclingStats |date=1963-07-10 |accessdate=2013-09-06}}</ref>\n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider (retired)<br>Team manager\n| ridertype      = \n| proyears1      = 1985\n| proteam1       = Santini - Krups\n| proyears2      = 1986-1987\n| proteam2       = Supermercati Brianzoli\n| proyears3      = 1988-1989\n| proteam3       = [[Chateau d'Ax]]\n| manageyears1   = 1992\u20131994\n| manageteam1    = [[Jolly Modular]]\n| manageyears2   = 1995\u20131997\n| manageteam2    = [[Aki-Safi|Aki]]\n| manageyears3   = 1998\u20131999\n| manageteam3    = {{ct|VIN|1998}}\n| manageyears4   = 2000\u20132001\n| manageteam4    = Liquigas\n| manageyears5   = 2002\n| manageteam5    = [[Cage Maglierie]]\n| manageyears6   = 2004\n| manageteam6    = {{ct|VIN|2004}}\n| manageyears7   = 2005\u2013\n| manageteam7    = {{ct|LIQ|2005}}\n| majorwins      = 1985: Team pursuit\n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Roberto Amadio''' (born 10 July 1963, in [[Portogruaro]], [[Italy]]) is an Italian sports manager and former [[road cycling|road]] and [[track cycling|track cyclist]]. Professional from 1985 to 1989, he was the world champion in the team pursuit in 1985. He also competed in the [[Cycling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team pursuit|team pursuit]] event at the [[1984 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/am/roberto-amadio-1.html |title=Roberto Amadio Olympic Results |accessdate=3 June 2015 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref> Since 2005 he is team manager and director of the team {{ct|CAN}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amadio, Roberto}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from the Metropolitan City of Venice]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Veneto]]\n[[Category:Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Roberto Amadio\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Roberto Amadio\n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1963|7|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Portogruaro]], [[Italy]]\n| currentteam    = {{ct|CAN}}<ref>{{cite web|author=ProCyclingStats |url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/1688991-Roberto-Amadio |title=Roberto Amadio |publisher=ProCyclingStats |date=1963-07-10 |accessdate=2013-09-06}}</ref>\n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider (retired)<br>Team manager\n| ridertype      = \n| proyears1      = 1985\n| proteam1       = Santini - Krups\n| proyears2      = 1986-1987\n| proteam2       = Supermercati Brianzoli\n| proyears3      = 1988-1989\n| proteam3       = [[Chateau d'Ax]]\n| manageyears1   = 1992\u20131994\n| manageteam1    = [[Jolly Modular]]\n| manageyears2   = 1995\u20131997\n| manageteam2    = [[Aki-Safi|Aki]]\n| manageyears3   = 1998\u20131999\n| manageteam3    = {{ct|VIN|1998}}\n| manageyears4   = 2000\u20132001\n| manageteam4    = Liquigas\n| manageyears5   = 2002\n| manageteam5    = [[Cage Maglierie]]\n| manageyears6   = 2004\n| manageteam6    = {{ct|VIN|2004}}\n| manageyears7   = 2005\u2013\n| manageteam7    = {{ct|LIQ|2005}}\n| majorwins      = 1985: Team pursuit\n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Roberto Amadio''' (born 10 July 1963, in [[Portogruaro]], [[Italy]]) is an Italian sports manager and former [[road cycling|road]] and [[track cycling|track cyclist]]. Professional from 1985 to 1989, he was the world champion in the team pursuit in 1985. He also competed in the [[Cycling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team pursuit|team pursuit]] event at the [[1984 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/am/roberto-amadio-1.html |title=Roberto Amadio Olympic Results |accessdate=3 June 2015 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref> Since 2005 he is team manager and director of the team {{ct|CAN}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amadio, Roberto}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from the Metropolitan City of Venice]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Veneto]]\n[[Category:Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roberto_Amadio"}
{"title_page": "Gavin Williamson", "text_new": "{{about|the British politician|other people of the same name|Gavin Williamson (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Gavin Williamson\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|size=100%}} [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Gavin Williamson MP crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Secretary of State for Education]]\n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 24 July 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Damian Hinds]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Secretary of State for Defence]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1 = 2 November 2017\n| term_end1 = 1 May 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n| successor1 = [[Penny Mordaunt]]\n| office2 = [[Chief Whip|Chief Whip of the House of Commons]]<br />[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start2 = 14 July 2016\n| term_end2 = 2 November 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Mark Harper]]\n| successor2 = [[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Staffordshire]]\n| term_start5 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end5 = \n| predecessor5 = [[Patrick Cormack]]\n| successor5 = \n| majority5 = 28,250 (56.5%)\n| birth_name = Gavin Alexander Williamson\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1976|6|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[North Yorkshire]], England\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| spouse = Joanne Eland\n| children = 2\n| education = [[Raincliffe School]]<br />[[Scarborough Sixth Form College]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Bradford]]\n| website = {{URL|gavinwilliamson.org}}\n| caption = Williamson in 2020\n}}\n'''Gavin Alexander Williamson''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|MP}} (born 25 June 1976) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician serving as [[Secretary of State for Education]] since 2019  under the [[First Johnson ministry|Johnson ministry]]. Williamson served as [[Secretary of State for Defence]] from November 2017 to 2019. On 1 May 2019 he was [[List of resignations from the second May ministry|dismissed as Defence Secretary]], following a leak from the [[National Security Council (United Kingdom)|National Security Council]]; Williamson has denied leaking the information.\n\nHe has served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Staffordshire]] since the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Williamson_Gavin.aspx |title=The Conservative Party: Gavin Williamson MP |publisher=Conservatives.com |date=19 July 2012 |accessdate=17 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914151805/http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Williamson_Gavin.aspx |archivedate=14 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Williamson served in the [[Second Cameron ministry]] as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to [[Patrick McLoughlin]], the [[Secretary of State for Transport]]<ref name =\"About Gavin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gavinwilliamson.org/about-gavin|title=About Gavin|website=Rt. Hon. Gavin Williamson MP|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613194335/http://www.gavinwilliamson.org/about-gavin|archivedate=13 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> prior to being appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary to the Prime Minister]] in October 2013. From 14 July 2016 to 2 November 2017, he served as [[Chief Whip of the Conservative Party|Chief Whip]] in the [[First May ministry|May Government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/highlights/2016/09/profile-gavin-williamson-the-baby-faced-assassin-who-is-now-chief-whip.html|title=Profile: Gavin Williamson, the \"baby-faced assassin\" who was Chief Whip. As of 2 November 2017 he became the new defence secretary\u2013 Conservative Home|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608230020/http://www.conservativehome.com/highlights/2016/09/profile-gavin-williamson-the-baby-faced-assassin-who-is-now-chief-whip.html|archivedate=8 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nWilliamson is originally from [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[North Yorkshire]]. His parents, Ray, a local government worker, and Beverly, a job centre worker,<ref name=\"BBC1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41841887|title=Profile: Who is Gavin Williamson, the new defence secretary?|newspaper=BBC News|date=2 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126230537/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41841887|archivedate=26 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cetusnews.com/news/ANDREW-PIERCE-profiles-new-defence-secretary-Gavin-Williamson%C2%A0.SkX7iHtAb.html|title=ANDREW PIERCE profiles new defence secretary Gavin Williamson|publisher=Cetusnews|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112160657/http://www.cetusnews.com/news/ANDREW-PIERCE-profiles-new-defence-secretary-Gavin-Williamson%C2%A0.SkX7iHtAb.html|archivedate=12 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> were both [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] voters.<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{cite web|last1=Eaton|first1=George|title=Gavin Williamson: the cunning Tory chief whip with a tarantula on his desk|website=The New Statesman|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/observations/2017/07/gavin-williamson-cunning-tory-chief-whip-tarantula-his-desk/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828102927/http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/observations/2017/07/gavin-williamson-cunning-tory-chief-whip-tarantula-his-desk|archivedate=28 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Williamson was educated in Scarborough, at [[East Ayton]] Primary School, followed by [[Raincliffe School]], a state comprehensive school, and the [[Scarborough Sixth Form College]], where he studied Government and Politics and Economics at [[A-levels|\"A\" Level]]. He obtained a [[BSc]] in [[Social Sciences]] from the [[University of Bradford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U251292/ |title=Who's Who |publisher=Ukwhoswho.com |date= |accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson was the penultimate national chairman of [[Conservative Collegiate Forum|Conservative Students]], before it was abolished in 1998 and the separate youth wings of the party were amalgamated as [[Conservative Future]]. He was elected a county councillor in 2001 for the [[Seamer, Scarborough|Seamer]] division in [[North Yorkshire]] but later stood down in 2005. Williamson is a former Deputy Chairman of Staffordshire Area Conservatives, Chairman of Stoke-on-Trent Conservative Association, and Vice-Chairman of Derbyshire Dales Conservative Association.<ref name=\"southstaffordshireconservatives.com\"/>\n\nWilliamson worked as managing director of fireplace manufacturer Elgin & Hall, a subsidiary of [[Aga Rangemaster Group|AGA]], until 2004.<!-- The 'office romance' is covered below. --><ref name=\"Kentish\"/><ref name=\"Syal\"/>\n\nWilliamson had become managing director of [[Aynsley China]], a [[Staffordshire|Staffordshire-based]] pottery firm by 2005. It sold ceramic tableware and he later became co-owner. In April 2005, Williamson was quoted in reports on the consumer rush to buy items with the wrong wedding date on for [[Wedding of Charles, Prince of Wales, and Camilla Parker Bowles|Charles and Camilla's wedding]]. He told ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', \"We've literally had fights in our own retail shops. On the first day after the announcement I went into our factory shop in Stoke-on-Trent and we had people fighting over the last plate that we had on the shop floor. I think everybody has decided that this is going to be their pension.\"<ref name=\"BBC1\" /><ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1487452/Ebay-bidders-go-wild-for-April-8-memorabilia.html|title=Ebay bidders go wild for April 8 memorabilia|last=Barrow|first=Becky|date=9 April 2005|work=The Telegraph|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/staffordshire/4411749.stm|title=Royal wedding pottery snapped up|date=5 April 2005|work=BBC News|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe has also worked for an architectural design firm until he became an MP in 2010.<ref name=\"About Gavin\" /><ref name=\"politics-bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/gavin-williamson |title=Gavin Williamson \u2013 Biography |website=politics.co.uk |accessdate=28 January 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826074140/http://politics.co.uk/reference/gavin-williamson |archivedate=26 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]], he stood unsuccessfully as the Conservative Party candidate in [[Blackpool North and Fleetwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackpool North and Fleetwood]].<ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\"/> After 2005, Williamson then moved to Derbyshire.<ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\">{{cite web |url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2010/01/gavin-williamson-selected-for-south-staffordshire.html |title=ConservativeHome's Seats & Candidates blog: Gavin Williamson selected for South Staffordshire |publisher=Conservativehome.blogs.com |date=30 January 2010 |accessdate=17 August 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619101829/http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2010/01/gavin-williamson-selected-for-south-staffordshire.html |archivedate=19 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n[[File:James Mattis, Jens Stoltenberg and Gavin Williamson 171108-D-GY869-142 (26487861869).jpg|thumb|left|Williamson meets with US Secretary of Defense [[Jim Mattis]] and NATO Secretary General [[Jens Stoltenberg]] in Brussels in November 2017]]\n\n=== Early parliamentary career (2010\u20132011) ===\nIn January 2010, Williamson was selected as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate in [[South Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Staffordshire]] for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]]. The incumbent, [[Patrick Cormack]], had announced that he was retiring. The selection went to five ballots, but in the end Williamson won out over local councillor Robert Light in the final ballot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2010/01/gavin-williamson-selected-for-south-staffordshire.html|title=Gavin Williamson selected for South Staffordshire|date=30 January 2010|work=Conservative Home|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref> Williamson was subsequently elected with a majority of 16,590 votes. Shortly after being elected, he cited his political inspiration as [[Rab Butler]] and, when asked what department of any he would most like to lead, he said the [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]] as it is \"business and manufacturing that can lead the way out of difficult economic times\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2010/09/gavin-williamson-mp-answers-conhomes-twenty-questions-for-the-class-of-2010.html|title=Gavin Williamson MP answers ConHome's Twenty Questions for the Class of 2010|date=6 September 2010|work=Conservative Home|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson made his maiden speech on 8 June 2010, on the same day as [[Nicky Morgan]] and [[Kwasi Kwarteng]]. During his speech, he said that \"We do not sing enough the praises of our designers, engineers and manufacturers. We need to change that ethos and have a similar one to that of Germany or Japan. We will have a truly vibrant economy only when we recreate the Victorian spirit of ingenuity and inventiveness that made Britain such a vibrant country, as I am sure it will be again.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2010/06/nicky-morgan-and-gavin-williamson-stress-the-importance-of-manufacturing-as-kwasi-kwarteng-uses-his.html|title=Nicky Morgan and Gavin Williamson stress the importance of manufacturing as Kwasi Kwarteng uses his maiden speech to accuse Labour MPs of being in \"never-never land\"|date=9 June 2010|work=Conservative Home|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref> Williamson campaigned on a number of issues in his first year in Parliament.\n\nIn July 2010, Williamson called for a new law to allow local authorities to clamp down on [[car boot sale]]s that disrupted traffic flow, citing villages in his constituency as examples.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2010/07/31/new-law-call-on-car-boot-sales/|title=New law call on car boot sales|last=Patel|first=Sunita|date=31 July 2010|work=Express and Star|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref> In June 2011, he expressed support for postwoman Julie Roberts, who had been suspended after clinging for over a mile onto the bonnet of her post van that had been stolen. He said that \"People want her back in work and they want the [[Royal Mail]] to show some common sense and some common decency\" and asked the Royal Mail to reinstate her into her old job.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/news/crime/mp-backs-axed-have-a-go-postie-1-3513467|title=MP backs axed have-a-go postie|date=24 June 2011|work=The Scarborough News|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref> Williamson was one of several MPs who was absent or abstained on the 21 March 2011 vote on supporting UN-backed action in Libya. The vote ultimately passed 557\u201313.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-12816279|title=The full list of how MPs voted on Libya action|date=22 March 2011|work=BBC News|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Parliamentary Private Secretaryships (2011\u20132016) ===\nIn October 2011, Williamson was appointed as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Northern Ireland Office|Minister of State for Northern Ireland]], [[Hugo Swire]]. He replaced [[Conor Burns]], who became [[Owen Paterson]]'s new PPS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/gavin-williamson-appointed-pps/|title=PoliticsHome.com|website=PoliticsHome.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111029154319/http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/gavin-williamson-appointed-pps/|archivedate=29 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In September 2012, Williamson became PPS to [[Patrick McLoughlin]], Secretary of State for Transport, and in 2013 became PPS to the Prime Minister, [[David Cameron]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/35247.stm|title=Gavin Williamson MP|work=Democracy Live|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=20 October 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102104216/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/35247.stm|archivedate=2 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn Parliament, Williamson was a member of the [[Northern Ireland Affairs Select Committee]] and was Chair of the [[All Party Parliamentary Group]] on [[Motor Neurone Disease]].<ref name=\"About Gavin\"/>\n\nWilliamson supported the United Kingdom's remain campaign during the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU membership referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough|first1=Tom|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence?|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|accessdate=11 October 2016|work=The Spectator|date=16 February 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203120144/http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|archivedate=3 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/02/gavin-williamson-meteoric-rise-tarantula-owning-remain-voting/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-11-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102203637/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/02/gavin-williamson-meteoric-rise-tarantula-owning-remain-voting/ |archivedate=2 November 2017 |df=dmy-all |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2018-01-11 |last1=Maidment |first1=Jack }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.herefordtimes.com/news/regional/14756008.Kinver_s_MP_Gavin_Williamson_talks_frankly_about_new_Chief_Whip_role/ |title=Kinver's MP Gavin Williamson talks frankly about new Chief Whip role |accessdate=2017-11-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107020956/http://www.herefordtimes.com/news/regional/14756008.Kinver_s_MP_Gavin_Williamson_talks_frankly_about_new_Chief_Whip_role/ |archivedate=7 November 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nWilliamson voted against an investigation into Tony Blair's role in the [[Iraq War]].<ref>\"[http://metro.co.uk/2017/11/02/how-has-our-new-defence-secretary-voted-on-the-key-issues-7049644/ How has our new defence secretary voted on the key issues?]\". Metro.co.uk. 2 November 2017.</ref>\n\n===Chief Whip (2016\u20132017)===\n\nFollowing [[David Cameron|David Cameron's]] resignation, Williamson \"privately vowed\" to stop the front-runner [[Boris Johnson]] from becoming Conservative Party leader. He assessed [[Theresa May]] to be the likeliest candidate to defeat Johnson, offered his help to her, and was invited to be her parliamentary [[campaign manager]].<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\"/> When May became prime minister, Williamson was appointed [[Chief Whip]].<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\"/>\n\nFollowing the [[Conservative\u2013DUP agreement]] after the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 General Election]], Williamson visited [[Belfast]] to discuss arrangements with the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]].<ref name=\"itvwhoisthemostpowerfulperson\">{{cite news|title=Who is the most powerful person in Britain?|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2017-06-11/who-is-the-most-powerful-person-in-britain/|accessdate=11 June 2017|work=ITV|date=11 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611150824/http://www.itv.com/news/2017-06-11/who-is-the-most-powerful-person-in-britain/|archivedate=11 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Defence Secretary (2017\u20132019)===\nWilliamson was appointed [[Secretary of State for Defence]] on 2 November 2017 after the resignation of Sir [[Michael Fallon]] the preceding evening.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/michael-fallon-uk-defense-secretary-resigns/|title=Theresa May appoints Gavin Williamson as defense secretary|date=2017-11-01|work=POLITICO|access-date=2017-11-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101233713/https://www.politico.eu/article/michael-fallon-uk-defense-secretary-resigns/|archivedate=1 November 2017|url-status=live|language=en-US|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41844320|title=Williamson is named defence secretary|date=2017-11-02|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-11-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102212620/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41844320|archivedate=2 November 2017|url-status=live|language=en-GB|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Williamson dined with Lubov Chernukhin, the wife of a former Putin minister, in exchange for a \u00a330,000 donation to the Conservative party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-tennis-russian-billionaire-putin-minister-tory-donation-a8261871.html|title=Boris Johnson defends playing tennis with wife of Putin's ex-minister in return for \u00a3160,000 Tory donation|work=The Independent|date=18 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> Later that month, Williamson alleged that the leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], [[Jeremy Corbyn]], in meeting a Czech diplomat (later revealed to be a spy) during the 1980s, had \"betray[ed]\" his country. In response to the statement, a spokesman for Corbyn stated: \"Gavin Williamson should focus on his job and not give credence to entirely false and ridiculous smears\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Fisher|first=Lucy|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/corbyn-spy-row-shows-he-can-t-be-trusted-says-gavin-williamson-9xgq8lrc8|title=Jeremy Corbyn 'can't be trusted' after claims he met Soviet spy, says Gavin Williamson|work=The Times|date=15 February 2018|accessdate=21 February 2018|issn=0140-0460}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Gavin Williamson and James Mattis 171110-D-GY869-202 (38254472376).jpg|left|thumb|220x220px|Williamson meeting with  [[United States Secretary of Defense]], [[Jim Mattis]] in 2017]]\n\nWilliamson has supported the [[Saudi Arabia]]n-led [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|military intervention in Yemen]] against the [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Houthis]] despite concerns from human rights activists and Labour MPs about war crimes allegedly committed by the Saudi military.<ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/uk-saudi-arabia-yemen-bombing-campaigns-mohammed-bin-salman-crown-prince-visit-theresa-may-cabinet-a8244136.html UK Government must be held accountable for children killed during Saudi Arabia's Yemen bombing, says Labour]\". ''The Independent.'' 7 March 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/09/world/middleeast/uk-saudi-arms-jets-yemen.html Britain to Sell Jets to Saudis Despite Conduct of Yemen War]\". ''The New York Times.'' 9 March 2018.</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2018, in the wake of the [[Poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal|Salisbury poisoning]], Williamson answered a question about Russia's potential response to the UK's punitive measures against Russia by saying that \"frankly, Russia should go away, and it should shut up\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Merrick|first=Rob|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/gavin-williamson-putin-russia-spies-response-british-diplomats-expel-salisbury-defence-secretary-a8257136.html|title=Defence Secretary Gavin Williamson tells Putin to 'go away and shut up' rather than expel British diplomats from Russia|work=The Independent|date=15 March 2018|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> Meanwhile, Major-General [[Igor Konashenkov]], the spokesman of the [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Defence Ministry]], said: \"The market wench talk that British defence secretary Gavin Williamson resorted to reflects his extreme intellectual impotency\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cecil|first1=Nicholas|last2=Murphy|first2=Joe|last3=Stewart|first3=Will|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/russians-taunt-gavin-williamson-the-wench-as-west-is-united-a3791831.html|title=Russians taunt 'Gavin Williamson the wench' as West is united|work=London Evening Standard|date=16 March 2018|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://tvzvezda.ru/news/vstrane_i_mire/content/201803152110-tc86.htm \u0412 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0431\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u044b\u043f\u0430\u0434 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044b \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0432 \u0430\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0441 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438] [[Zvezda (TV channel)|TV Zvezda]], 15 March 2018.</ref> Williamson's remark was quoted by the [[president of Ukraine]], [[Petro Poroshenko]], who posted a comment on his official Twitter account: \"The Kremlin's 'chemical attack' in the UK is nothing but an encroachment on British sovereignty. And our message to Russia is the same as that of British defense secretary Gavin Williamson: 'shut up and go away'.\"<ref>[https://www.unian.info/politics/10045706-poroshenko-joins-britain-urging-russia-to-shut-up-and-go-away.html Poroshenko joins Britain urging Russia to \"shut up and go away\"] unian.info, 17 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://ria.ru/world/20180317/1516572339.html \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0432\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434 \u0437\u0430 \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0442\u043a\u043d\u0443\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f\u200d] [[RIA Novosti]], 17 March 2018.</ref>\n[[File:Gavin Williamson MSC 2019 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Williamson during the [[Munich Security Conference|MSC]] 2019|alt=]]\nIn December 2018, Williamson expressed \"grave\" and \"very deep concerns\" about the Chinese telecommunications company [[Huawei]] providing technology to upgrade Britain's services to [[5G]]. He accused China of acting \"sometimes in a malign way\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46690627|title=Huawei: 'Deep concerns' over firm's role in UK 5G upgrade|website=BBC News|language=en-gb|date=27 December 2018}}</ref> [[Ministry of National Defense of the People's Republic of China|China's Defence Ministry]] spokesman [[Wu Qian (military officer)|Wu Qian]] criticised Williamson's comments, saying: \"The remarks just reinforced the deep-rooted ignorance, prejudice and anxiety among some British people.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Czech Prime Minister Andrej Babi\u0161 hits back at Chinese diplomats' Huawei and ZTE claims |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/2179833/czech-prime-minister-hits-back-chinese-diplomats-huawei-claims |work=South China Morning Post |date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 February 2019, Williamson delivered the speech \"Defence in Global Britain\" at the [[Royal United Services Institute]] outlining the future direction of the British armed forces.<ref>{{Cite Web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/defence-in-global-britain|title=Speech Defence in Global Britain|work=Ministry of Defence GOV.UK|date=11 February 2019|access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref> The speech, among other things, outlined plans to send Britain's new aircraft carrier to the Pacific;<ref>{{cite news |last1=James |first1=William |title=Post-Brexit Britain ready to use 'hard power': defense minister |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-defence/post-brexit-britain-ready-to-use-hard-power-defense-minister-idUSKCN1Q000F |work=Reuters |date=10 February 2019}}</ref> the Chinese Government in turn cancelled trade talks with Chancellor of the Exchequer [[Philip Hammond]] and prompted Hammond to state that the decision to deploy the aircraft carrier was premature.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-china-talks/china-cancels-trade-talks-with-uk-in-protest-over-defence-secretarys-speech-the-sun-idUKKCN1Q314G|title=China cancels trade talks with UK in protest over defence secretary's speech|work=Reuters|date=14 February 2019|access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=guardian-20190221>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/21/hammond-uk-china-relations-not-made-simpler-by-williamson |title=Hammond: UK-China relations 'not made simpler' by Williamson |last=Perraudin |first=Frances |newspaper=The Guardian |date=21 February 2019 |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> ''The Mail on Sunday'' quoted an unnamed ally of Hammond comparing Williamson to [[Private Pike]], a hapless character in the sitcom '' [[Dad's Army]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/philip-hammond-s-allies-take-aim-at-private-pike-minister-gavin-williamson-777z808w5|title=Philip Hammond's allies take aim at 'Private Pike' minister Gavin Williamson|first=Henry|last=Zeffman|date=4 December 2017|accessdate=1 May 2019|work=The Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2019, Williamson was asked to resign from his position as Defence Secretary, following the leaking of confidential information relating to a [[National Security Council (United Kingdom)|National Security Council]] meeting. He refused to resign and was then sacked.<ref name=guardian1>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/may/01/gavin-williamson-sacked-as-defence-secretary-over-huawei-leak|title=Gavin Williamson sacked as defence secretary over Huawei leak|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=2019-05-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Theresa May said that she had \"compelling evidence\" that Williamson had leaked the information and that she had \"lost confidence in his ability to serve in his role\". Williamson denied the allegation and said that a \"thorough and formal inquiry\" would have vindicated his position.<ref name=\"dismissal\">{{cite news |title=Defence Secretary Gavin Williamson sacked over Huawei leak |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48126974 |website=BBC News |date=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"denial\">{{cite news |title=Gavin Williamson sacking: Former defence secretary denies Huawei leak |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48129280 |website=BBC News |date=2 May 2019}}</ref> Opposition MPs have called for a police investigation into the matter.<ref name=\"dismissal\"/><ref name=\"denial\"/>\n\n=== Education Secretary (2019\u2013present) ===\nWilliamson became [[Secretary of State for Education]] upon [[Boris Johnson]]'s election as Prime Minister on 24 July 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://feweek.co.uk/2019/07/24/gavin-williamson-becomes-new-education-secretary/|title=Gavin Williamson becomes new education secretary|last=Whieldon|first=Fraser|website=FE Week|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[deplatforming]] of history professor [[Selina Todd]] and former Home Secretary [[Amber Rudd]] by student societies at [[Oxford University]], in March 2020 Williamson called for \"robust action\" to enforce free speech codes, and stated that the government would intervene to protect [[freedom of speech]] at universities if they failed to do so themselves.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/03/06/government-looks-strengthen-free-speech-campus-oxfords-no-platforming|title=Government looks to strengthen free speech on campus after Oxford's no-platforming of Amber Rudd|last=Yorke|first=Harry|date=6 March 2020|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=6 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> ''[[HuffPost]]'' reported that Williamson's department had drafted legislation to \"strengthen academic freedom and free speech in universities\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/gavin-williamson-new-law-freedom-of-speech-university-oxford_uk_5e63fa78c5b6670e72f90ef5|title=Ministers Preparing New Law To 'Protect Freedom Of Speech' At Universities|last=Waugh|first=Paul|date=7 March 2020|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Williamson announced that schools in England would close from 20 March until further notice. He said that exams in the current academic year would not go ahead.<ref>{{Cite news|title=BBC News - Coronavirus: Schools to close until further notice from Friday|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314|work=BBC News|date=18 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and honours==\n\nWilliamson is married to Joanne, a former primary school teacher. The couple have two daughters, Annabel and Grace.<ref name=\"southstaffordshireconservatives.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.southstaffsconservatives.org.uk/rt-hon-gavin-williamson-cbe-mp|title=The Rt. Hon. Gavin Williamson CBE MP|publisher=South Staffordshire \u2013 Conservative Association|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828012126/https://www.southstaffsconservatives.org.uk/rt-hon-gavin-williamson-cbe-mp|archivedate=28 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was a charity trustee at a [[Citizen's Advice Bureau]], and a [[school governor]].<ref name=\"About Gavin\"/>\n\nWilliamson is a patron of the World Owl Trust and while chief whip kept a [[Mexican redknee tarantula]], Cronus, in his parliamentary office,<ref name=\"BBC1\"/> for which he was criticised by parliamentary authorities in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCann|first1=Kate|title=Revealed: The first picture of Cronus, the chief whip's pet tarantula|work=The Daily Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/11/24/revealed-first-picture-cronus-chief-whips-pet-tarantula/|date=24 November 2016|accessdate=2 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828040857/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/11/24/revealed-first-picture-cronus-chief-whips-pet-tarantula/|archivedate=28 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he was sworn in as a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]], giving him the [[Honorific|Honorific Title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for life.\n\nIn the [[2016 Prime Minister's Resignation Honours]], Williamson was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) \"for political and public service\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Resignation Honours 2016|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/543929/Resignation-Honours-2016.pdf|website=GOV.UK|publisher=Cabinet Office|accessdate=4 August 2016|date=4 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920054449/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/543929/Resignation-Honours-2016.pdf|archivedate=20 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, it became known that Williamson, while he was managing director of fireplace firm Elgin & Hall in 2004, had an office romance. To save his marriage, he has said he left the firm.<ref name=\"Kentish\">{{cite news|last=Kentih|first=Benjamin|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/gavin-williamson-cheating-defence-secretary-admit-romance-affair-russia-marriage-wife-a8179056.html|title=Gavin Williamson: Tory Defence Secretary admits to 'kissing' trysts with married former colleague|work=The Independent|date=26 January 2018|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127145707/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/gavin-williamson-cheating-defence-secretary-admit-romance-affair-russia-marriage-wife-a8179056.html|archivedate=27 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to Williamson, it became \"flirtatious and a couple of times we shared a kiss\", but it \"never went further\", Williamson told the ''[[Daily Mail]]''.<ref name=\"Syal\">{{cite news|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/26/defence-secretary-questions-relationship-colleague-gavin-williamson|title=Defence secretary refuses to answer questions about relationship with past colleague|work=The Guardian|date=26 January 2018|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127151405/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/26/defence-secretary-questions-relationship-colleague-gavin-williamson|archivedate=27 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \"My family means everything to me and I almost threw it away\", Williamson said. \"This incident nearly destroyed two marriages\".<ref name=\"Kentish\"/> ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'' reported that a senior co-worker stated that the woman involved was in tears when reporting the incident at work and that Williamson was subsequently the subject of a meeting with managers.<ref name=telegraph-20180128>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/27/female-colleague-gavin-williamson-shared-kiss-tears-claimed/ |title=Female colleague Gavin Williamson 'shared kiss' with was in tears, it was claimed |first=Nicola |last=Harley|first2= Steve |last2=Bird|first3= Victoria |last3=Ward |newspaper=Sunday Telegraph |date=28 January 2018 |accessdate=28 January 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127221036/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/27/female-colleague-gavin-williamson-shared-kiss-tears-claimed/ |archivedate=27 January 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.gavinwilliamson.org/ Official site]\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = gavin-williamson/4108 | publicwhip = Gavin_Williamson | theywork = gavin_williamson }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120914151805/http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Williamson_Gavin.aspx Conservative Party]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131106015050/http://www.southstaffsconservatives.org.uk/gavin-williamson-mp South Staffordshire Conservative Association]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Patrick Cormack]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[South Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Staffordshire]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Mark Harper]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Fallon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Defence]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Penny Mordaunt]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Damian Hinds]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Education]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Harper]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip of the Conservative Party|Conservative Chief Whip of the]] [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{First May Cabinet}}\n{{Second May Cabinet}}\n{{Secretaries of State for Education}}\n{{Secretary of State for Defence}}\n{{Conservative Chief Whips}}\n{{West Midlands Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williamson, Gavin}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bradford]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary Private Secretaries to the Prime Minister]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Scarborough, North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Defence (UK)]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the British politician|other people of the same name|Gavin Williamson (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Gavin Williamson\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|size=100%}} [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Gavin Williamson MP crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Secretary of State for Education]]\n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 24 July 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Damian Hinds]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Secretary of State for Defence]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1 = 2 November 2017\n| term_end1 = 1 May 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n| successor1 = [[Penny Mordaunt]]\n| office2 = [[Chief Whip|Chief Whip of the House of Commons]]<br />[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start2 = 14 July 2016\n| term_end2 = 2 November 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Mark Harper]]\n| successor2 = [[Julian Smith (politician)|Julian Smith]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[South Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Staffordshire]]\n| term_start5 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end5 = \n| predecessor5 = [[Patrick Cormack]]\n| successor5 = \n| majority5 = 28,250 (56.5%)\n| birth_name = Gavin Alexander Williamson\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1976|6|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[North Yorkshire]], England\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| spouse = Joanne Eland\n| children = 2\n| education = [[Raincliffe School]]<br />[[Scarborough Sixth Form College]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Bradford]]\n| website = {{URL|gavinwilliamson.org}}\n| caption = Williamson in 2020\n}}\n'''Gavin Alexander Williamson''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|MP}} (born 25 June 1976) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician serving as [[Secretary of State for Education]] since 2019  under the [[First Johnson ministry|Johnson ministry]]. Williamson served as [[Secretary of State for Defence]] from November 2017 to 2019. On 1 May 2019 he was [[List of resignations from the second May ministry|dismissed as Defence Secretary]], following a leak from the [[National Security Council (United Kingdom)|National Security Council]]; Williamson has denied leaking the information.\n\nHe has served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Staffordshire]] since the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Williamson_Gavin.aspx |title=The Conservative Party: Gavin Williamson MP |publisher=Conservatives.com |date=19 July 2012 |accessdate=17 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914151805/http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Williamson_Gavin.aspx |archivedate=14 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Williamson served in the [[Second Cameron ministry]] as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to [[Patrick McLoughlin]], the [[Secretary of State for Transport]]<ref name =\"About Gavin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gavinwilliamson.org/about-gavin|title=About Gavin|website=Rt. Hon. Gavin Williamson MP|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613194335/http://www.gavinwilliamson.org/about-gavin|archivedate=13 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> prior to being appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary to the Prime Minister]] in October 2013. From 14 July 2016 to 2 November 2017, he served as [[Chief Whip of the Conservative Party|Chief Whip]] in the [[First May ministry|May Government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/highlights/2016/09/profile-gavin-williamson-the-baby-faced-assassin-who-is-now-chief-whip.html|title=Profile: Gavin Williamson, the \"baby-faced assassin\" who was Chief Whip. As of 2 November 2017 he became the new defence secretary\u2013 Conservative Home|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608230020/http://www.conservativehome.com/highlights/2016/09/profile-gavin-williamson-the-baby-faced-assassin-who-is-now-chief-whip.html|archivedate=8 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nWilliamson is originally from [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[North Yorkshire]]. His parents, Ray, a local government worker, and Beverly, a job centre worker,<ref name=\"BBC1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41841887|title=Profile: Who is Gavin Williamson, the new defence secretary?|newspaper=BBC News|date=2 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126230537/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41841887|archivedate=26 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cetusnews.com/news/ANDREW-PIERCE-profiles-new-defence-secretary-Gavin-Williamson%C2%A0.SkX7iHtAb.html|title=ANDREW PIERCE profiles new defence secretary Gavin Williamson|publisher=Cetusnews|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112160657/http://www.cetusnews.com/news/ANDREW-PIERCE-profiles-new-defence-secretary-Gavin-Williamson%C2%A0.SkX7iHtAb.html|archivedate=12 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> were both [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] voters.<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{cite web|last1=Eaton|first1=George|title=Gavin Williamson: the cunning Tory chief whip with a tarantula on his desk|website=The New Statesman|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/observations/2017/07/gavin-williamson-cunning-tory-chief-whip-tarantula-his-desk/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828102927/http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/observations/2017/07/gavin-williamson-cunning-tory-chief-whip-tarantula-his-desk|archivedate=28 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Williamson was educated in Scarborough, at [[East Ayton]] Primary School, followed by [[Raincliffe School]], a state comprehensive school, and the [[Scarborough Sixth Form College]], where he studied Government and Politics and Economics at [[A-levels|\"A\" Level]]. He obtained a [[BSc]] in [[Social Sciences]] from the [[University of Bradford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U251292/ |title=Who's Who |publisher=Ukwhoswho.com |date= |accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson was the penultimate national chairman of [[Conservative Collegiate Forum|Conservative Students]], before it was abolished in 1998 and the separate youth wings of the party were amalgamated as [[Conservative Future]]. He was elected a county councillor in 2001 for the [[Seamer, Scarborough|Seamer]] division in [[North Yorkshire]] but later stood down in 2005. Williamson is a former Deputy Chairman of Staffordshire Area Conservatives, Chairman of Stoke-on-Trent Conservative Association, and Vice-Chairman of Derbyshire Dales Conservative Association.<ref name=\"southstaffordshireconservatives.com\"/>\n\nWilliamson worked as managing director of fireplace manufacturer Elgin & Hall, a subsidiary of [[Aga Rangemaster Group|AGA]], until 2004.<!-- The 'office romance' is covered below. --><ref name=\"Kentish\"/><ref name=\"Syal\"/>\n\nWilliamson had become managing director of [[Aynsley China]], a [[Staffordshire|Staffordshire-based]] pottery firm by 2005. It sold ceramic tableware and he later became co-owner. In April 2005, Williamson was quoted in reports on the consumer rush to buy items with the wrong wedding date on for [[Wedding of Charles, Prince of Wales, and Camilla Parker Bowles|Charles and Camilla's wedding]]. He told ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', \"We've literally had fights in our own retail shops. On the first day after the announcement I went into our factory shop in Stoke-on-Trent and we had people fighting over the last plate that we had on the shop floor. I think everybody has decided that this is going to be their pension.\"<ref name=\"BBC1\" /><ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1487452/Ebay-bidders-go-wild-for-April-8-memorabilia.html|title=Ebay bidders go wild for April 8 memorabilia|last=Barrow|first=Becky|date=9 April 2005|work=The Telegraph|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/staffordshire/4411749.stm|title=Royal wedding pottery snapped up|date=5 April 2005|work=BBC News|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe has also worked for an architectural design firm until he became an MP in 2010.<ref name=\"About Gavin\" /><ref name=\"politics-bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/gavin-williamson |title=Gavin Williamson \u2013 Biography |website=politics.co.uk |accessdate=28 January 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826074140/http://politics.co.uk/reference/gavin-williamson |archivedate=26 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]], he stood unsuccessfully as the Conservative Party candidate in [[Blackpool North and Fleetwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackpool North and Fleetwood]].<ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\"/> After 2005, Williamson then moved to Derbyshire.<ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\">{{cite web |url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2010/01/gavin-williamson-selected-for-south-staffordshire.html |title=ConservativeHome's Seats & Candidates blog: Gavin Williamson selected for South Staffordshire |publisher=Conservativehome.blogs.com |date=30 January 2010 |accessdate=17 August 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619101829/http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2010/01/gavin-williamson-selected-for-south-staffordshire.html |archivedate=19 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n[[File:James Mattis, Jens Stoltenberg and Gavin Williamson 171108-D-GY869-142 (26487861869).jpg|thumb|left|Williamson meets with US Secretary of Defense [[Jim Mattis]] and NATO Secretary General [[Jens Stoltenberg]] in Brussels in November 2017]]\n\n=== Early parliamentary career (2010\u20132011) ===\nIn January 2010, Williamson was selected as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate in [[South Staffordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Staffordshire]] for the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]]. The incumbent, [[Patrick Cormack]], had announced that he was retiring. The selection went to five ballots, but in the end Williamson won out over local councillor Robert Light in the final ballot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2010/01/gavin-williamson-selected-for-south-staffordshire.html|title=Gavin Williamson selected for South Staffordshire|date=30 January 2010|work=Conservative Home|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref> Williamson was subsequently elected with a majority of 16,590 votes. Shortly after being elected, he cited his political inspiration as [[Rab Butler]] and, when asked what department of any he would most like to lead, he said the [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]] as it is \"business and manufacturing that can lead the way out of difficult economic times\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2010/09/gavin-williamson-mp-answers-conhomes-twenty-questions-for-the-class-of-2010.html|title=Gavin Williamson MP answers ConHome's Twenty Questions for the Class of 2010|date=6 September 2010|work=Conservative Home|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nWilliamson made his maiden speech on 8 June 2010, on the same day as [[Nicky Morgan]] and [[Kwasi Kwarteng]]. During his speech, he said that \"We do not sing enough the praises of our designers, engineers and manufacturers. We need to change that ethos and have a similar one to that of Germany or Japan. We will have a truly vibrant economy only when we recreate the Victorian spirit of ingenuity and inventiveness that made Britain such a vibrant country, as I am sure it will be again.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2010/06/nicky-morgan-and-gavin-williamson-stress-the-importance-of-manufacturing-as-kwasi-kwarteng-uses-his.html|title=Nicky Morgan and Gavin Williamson stress the importance of manufacturing as Kwasi Kwarteng uses his maiden speech to accuse Labour MPs of being in \"never-never land\"|date=9 June 2010|work=Conservative Home|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref> Williamson campaigned on a number of issues in his first year in Parliament.\n\nIn July 2010, Williamson called for a new law to allow local authorities to clamp down on [[car boot sale]]s that disrupted traffic flow, citing villages in his constituency as examples.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2010/07/31/new-law-call-on-car-boot-sales/|title=New law call on car boot sales|last=Patel|first=Sunita|date=31 July 2010|work=Express and Star|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref> In June 2011, he expressed support for postwoman Julie Roberts, who had been suspended after clinging for over a mile onto the bonnet of her post van that had been stolen. He said that \"People want her back in work and they want the [[Royal Mail]] to show some common sense and some common decency\" and asked the Royal Mail to reinstate her into her old job.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/news/crime/mp-backs-axed-have-a-go-postie-1-3513467|title=MP backs axed have-a-go postie|date=24 June 2011|work=The Scarborough News|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref> Williamson was one of several MPs who was absent or abstained on the 21 March 2011 vote on supporting UN-backed action in Libya. The vote ultimately passed 557\u201313.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-12816279|title=The full list of how MPs voted on Libya action|date=22 March 2011|work=BBC News|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Parliamentary Private Secretaryships (2011\u20132016) ===\nIn October 2011, Williamson was appointed as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Northern Ireland Office|Minister of State for Northern Ireland]], [[Hugo Swire]]. He replaced [[Conor Burns]], who became [[Owen Paterson]]'s new PPS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/gavin-williamson-appointed-pps/|title=PoliticsHome.com|website=PoliticsHome.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111029154319/http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/gavin-williamson-appointed-pps/|archivedate=29 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In September 2012, Williamson became PPS to [[Patrick McLoughlin]], Secretary of State for Transport, and in 2013 became PPS to the Prime Minister, [[David Cameron]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/35247.stm|title=Gavin Williamson MP|work=Democracy Live|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=20 October 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102104216/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/35247.stm|archivedate=2 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn Parliament, Williamson was a member of the [[Northern Ireland Affairs Select Committee]] and was Chair of the [[All Party Parliamentary Group]] on [[Motor Neurone Disease]].<ref name=\"About Gavin\"/>\n\nWilliamson supported the United Kingdom's remain campaign during the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU membership referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough|first1=Tom|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence?|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|accessdate=11 October 2016|work=The Spectator|date=16 February 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203120144/http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|archivedate=3 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/02/gavin-williamson-meteoric-rise-tarantula-owning-remain-voting/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-11-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102203637/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/02/gavin-williamson-meteoric-rise-tarantula-owning-remain-voting/ |archivedate=2 November 2017 |df=dmy-all |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2018-01-11 |last1=Maidment |first1=Jack }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.herefordtimes.com/news/regional/14756008.Kinver_s_MP_Gavin_Williamson_talks_frankly_about_new_Chief_Whip_role/ |title=Kinver's MP Gavin Williamson talks frankly about new Chief Whip role |accessdate=2017-11-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107020956/http://www.herefordtimes.com/news/regional/14756008.Kinver_s_MP_Gavin_Williamson_talks_frankly_about_new_Chief_Whip_role/ |archivedate=7 November 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nWilliamson voted against an investigation into Tony Blair's role in the [[Iraq War]].<ref>\"[http://metro.co.uk/2017/11/02/how-has-our-new-defence-secretary-voted-on-the-key-issues-7049644/ How has our new defence secretary voted on the key issues?]\". Metro.co.uk. 2 November 2017.</ref>\n\n===Chief Whip (2016\u20132017)===\n\nFollowing [[David Cameron|David Cameron's]] resignation, Williamson \"privately vowed\" to stop the front-runner [[Boris Johnson]] from becoming Conservative Party leader. He assessed [[Theresa May]] to be the likeliest candidate to defeat Johnson, offered his help to her, and was invited to be her parliamentary [[campaign manager]].<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\"/> When May became prime minister, Williamson was appointed [[Chief Whip]].<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\"/>\n\nFollowing the [[Conservative\u2013DUP agreement]] after the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 General Election]], Williamson visited [[Belfast]] to discuss arrangements with the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]].<ref name=\"itvwhoisthemostpowerfulperson\">{{cite news|title=Who is the most powerful person in Britain?|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2017-06-11/who-is-the-most-powerful-person-in-britain/|accessdate=11 June 2017|work=ITV|date=11 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611150824/http://www.itv.com/news/2017-06-11/who-is-the-most-powerful-person-in-britain/|archivedate=11 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Defence Secretary (2017\u20132019)===\nWilliamson was appointed [[Secretary of State for Defence]] on 2 November 2017 after the resignation of Sir [[Michael Fallon]] the preceding evening.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/michael-fallon-uk-defense-secretary-resigns/|title=Theresa May appoints Gavin Williamson as defense secretary|date=2017-11-01|work=POLITICO|access-date=2017-11-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101233713/https://www.politico.eu/article/michael-fallon-uk-defense-secretary-resigns/|archivedate=1 November 2017|url-status=live|language=en-US|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41844320|title=Williamson is named defence secretary|date=2017-11-02|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-11-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102212620/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-41844320|archivedate=2 November 2017|url-status=live|language=en-GB|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Williamson dined with Lubov Chernukhin, the wife of a former Putin minister, in exchange for a \u00a330,000 donation to the Conservative party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/boris-johnson-tennis-russian-billionaire-putin-minister-tory-donation-a8261871.html|title=Boris Johnson defends playing tennis with wife of Putin's ex-minister in return for \u00a3160,000 Tory donation|work=The Independent|date=18 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> Later that month, Williamson alleged that the leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], [[Jeremy Corbyn]], in meeting a Czech diplomat (later revealed to be a spy) during the 1980s, had \"betray[ed]\" his country. In response to the statement, a spokesman for Corbyn stated: \"Gavin Williamson should focus on his job and not give credence to entirely false and ridiculous smears\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Fisher|first=Lucy|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/corbyn-spy-row-shows-he-can-t-be-trusted-says-gavin-williamson-9xgq8lrc8|title=Jeremy Corbyn 'can't be trusted' after claims he met Soviet spy, says Gavin Williamson|work=The Times|date=15 February 2018|accessdate=21 February 2018|issn=0140-0460}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Gavin Williamson and James Mattis 171110-D-GY869-202 (38254472376).jpg|left|thumb|220x220px|Williamson meeting with  [[United States Secretary of Defense]], [[Jim Mattis]] in 2017]]\n\nWilliamson has supported the [[Saudi Arabia]]n-led [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|military intervention in Yemen]] against the [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Houthis]] despite concerns from human rights activists and Labour MPs about war crimes allegedly committed by the Saudi military.<ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/uk-saudi-arabia-yemen-bombing-campaigns-mohammed-bin-salman-crown-prince-visit-theresa-may-cabinet-a8244136.html UK Government must be held accountable for children killed during Saudi Arabia's Yemen bombing, says Labour]\". ''The Independent.'' 7 March 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/09/world/middleeast/uk-saudi-arms-jets-yemen.html Britain to Sell Jets to Saudis Despite Conduct of Yemen War]\". ''The New York Times.'' 9 March 2018.</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2018, in the wake of the [[Poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal|Salisbury poisoning]], Williamson answered a question about Russia's potential response to the UK\u2032s punitive measures against Russia by saying that \"frankly, Russia should go away, and it should shut up\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Merrick|first=Rob|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/gavin-williamson-putin-russia-spies-response-british-diplomats-expel-salisbury-defence-secretary-a8257136.html|title=Defence Secretary Gavin Williamson tells Putin to 'go away and shut up' rather than expel British diplomats from Russia|work=The Independent|date=15 March 2018|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> Meanwhile, Major-General [[Igor Konashenkov]], the spokesman of the [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Defence Ministry]], said: \"The market wench talk that British defence secretary Gavin Williamson resorted to reflects his extreme intellectual impotency\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cecil|first1=Nicholas|last2=Murphy|first2=Joe|last3=Stewart|first3=Will|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/russians-taunt-gavin-williamson-the-wench-as-west-is-united-a3791831.html|title=Russians taunt 'Gavin Williamson the wench' as West is united|work=London Evening Standard|date=16 March 2018|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://tvzvezda.ru/news/vstrane_i_mire/content/201803152110-tc86.htm \u0412 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0431\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u044b\u043f\u0430\u0434 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044b \u0431\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0432 \u0430\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0441 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438] [[Zvezda (TV channel)|TV Zvezda]], 15 March 2018.</ref> Williamson\u2032s remark was quoted by the [[president of Ukraine]], [[Petro Poroshenko]], who posted a comment on his official Twitter account: \"The Kremlin's 'chemical attack' in the UK is nothing but an encroachment on British sovereignty. And our message to Russia is the same as that of British defense secretary Gavin Williamson: 'shut up and go away'.\"<ref>[https://www.unian.info/politics/10045706-poroshenko-joins-britain-urging-russia-to-shut-up-and-go-away.html Poroshenko joins Britain urging Russia to \"shut up and go away\"] unian.info, 17 March 2018.</ref><ref>[https://ria.ru/world/20180317/1516572339.html \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0432\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434 \u0437\u0430 \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0442\u043a\u043d\u0443\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f\u200d] [[RIA Novosti]], 17 March 2018.</ref>\n[[File:Gavin Williamson MSC 2019 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Williamson during the [[Munich Security Conference|MSC]] 2019|alt=]]\nIn December 2018, Williamson expressed \"grave\" and \"very deep concerns\" about the Chinese telecommunications company [[Huawei]] providing technology to upgrade Britain's services to [[5G]]. He accused China of acting \"sometimes in a malign way\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46690627|title=Huawei: 'Deep concerns' over firm's role in UK 5G upgrade|website=BBC News|language=en-gb|date=27 December 2018}}</ref> [[Ministry of National Defense of the People's Republic of China|China's Defence Ministry]] spokesman [[Wu Qian (military officer)|Wu Qian]] criticised Williamson\u2019s comments, saying: \"The remarks just reinforced the deep-rooted ignorance, prejudice and anxiety among some British people.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Czech Prime Minister Andrej Babi\u0161 hits back at Chinese diplomats' Huawei and ZTE claims |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/2179833/czech-prime-minister-hits-back-chinese-diplomats-huawei-claims |work=South China Morning Post |date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 February 2019, Williamson delivered the speech \"Defence in Global Britain\" at the [[Royal United Services Institute]] outlining the future direction of the British armed forces.<ref>{{Cite Web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/defence-in-global-britain|title=Speech Defence in Global Britain|work=Ministry of Defence GOV.UK|date=11 February 2019|access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref> The speech, among other things, outlined plans to send Britain's new aircraft carrier to the Pacific;<ref>{{cite news |last1=James |first1=William |title=Post-Brexit Britain ready to use 'hard power': defense minister |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-defence/post-brexit-britain-ready-to-use-hard-power-defense-minister-idUSKCN1Q000F |work=Reuters |date=10 February 2019}}</ref> the Chinese Government in turn cancelled trade talks with Chancellor of the Exchequer [[Philip Hammond]] and prompted Hammond to state that the decision to deploy the aircraft carrier was premature.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-china-talks/china-cancels-trade-talks-with-uk-in-protest-over-defence-secretarys-speech-the-sun-idUKKCN1Q314G|title=China cancels trade talks with UK in protest over defence secretary's speech|work=Reuters|date=14 February 2019|access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=guardian-20190221>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/21/hammond-uk-china-relations-not-made-simpler-by-williamson |title=Hammond: UK-China relations 'not made simpler' by Williamson |last=Perraudin |first=Frances |newspaper=The Guardian |date=21 February 2019 |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> ''The Mail on Sunday'' quoted an unnamed ally of Hammond comparing Williamson to [[Private Pike]], a hapless character in the sitcom '' [[Dad's Army]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/philip-hammond-s-allies-take-aim-at-private-pike-minister-gavin-williamson-777z808w5|title=Philip Hammond's allies take aim at 'Private Pike' minister Gavin Williamson|first=Henry|last=Zeffman|date=4 December 2017|accessdate=1 May 2019|work=The Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2019, Williamson was asked to resign from his position as Defence Secretary, following the leaking of confidential information relating to a [[National Security Council (United Kingdom)|National Security Council]] meeting. He refused to resign and was then sacked.<ref name=guardian1>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/may/01/gavin-williamson-sacked-as-defence-secretary-over-huawei-leak|title=Gavin Williamson sacked as defence secretary over Huawei leak|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=2019-05-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Theresa May said that she had \"compelling evidence\" that Williamson had leaked the information and that she had \"lost confidence in his ability to serve in his role\". Williamson denied the allegation and said that a \"thorough and formal inquiry\" would have vindicated his position.<ref name=\"dismissal\">{{cite news |title=Defence Secretary Gavin Williamson sacked over Huawei leak |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48126974 |website=BBC News |date=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"denial\">{{cite news |title=Gavin Williamson sacking: Former defence secretary denies Huawei leak |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48129280 |website=BBC News |date=2 May 2019}}</ref> Opposition MPs have called for a police investigation into the matter.<ref name=\"dismissal\"/><ref name=\"denial\"/>\n\n=== Education Secretary (2019\u2013present) ===\nWilliamson became [[Secretary of State for Education]] upon [[Boris Johnson]]'s election as Prime Minister on 24 July 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://feweek.co.uk/2019/07/24/gavin-williamson-becomes-new-education-secretary/|title=Gavin Williamson becomes new education secretary|last=Whieldon|first=Fraser|website=FE Week|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[deplatforming]] of history professor [[Selina Todd]] and former Home Secretary [[Amber Rudd]] by student societies at [[Oxford University]], in March 2020 Williamson called for \"robust action\" to enforce free speech codes, and stated that the government would intervene to protect [[freedom of speech]] at universities if they failed to do so themselves.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/03/06/government-looks-strengthen-free-speech-campus-oxfords-no-platforming|title=Government looks to strengthen free speech on campus after Oxford's no-platforming of Amber Rudd|last=Yorke|first=Harry|date=6 March 2020|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=6 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> ''[[HuffPost]]'' reported that Williamson's department had drafted legislation to \"strengthen academic freedom and free speech in universities\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/gavin-williamson-new-law-freedom-of-speech-university-oxford_uk_5e63fa78c5b6670e72f90ef5|title=Ministers Preparing New Law To 'Protect Freedom Of Speech' At Universities|last=Waugh|first=Paul|date=7 March 2020|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Williamson announced that schools in England would close from 20 March until further notice. He said that exams in the current academic year would not go ahead.<ref>{{Cite news|title=BBC News - Coronavirus: Schools to close until further notice from Friday|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314|work=BBC News|date=18 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and honours==\n\nWilliamson is married to Joanne, a former primary school teacher. The couple have two daughters, Annabel and Grace.<ref name=\"southstaffordshireconservatives.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.southstaffsconservatives.org.uk/rt-hon-gavin-williamson-cbe-mp|title=The Rt. Hon. Gavin Williamson CBE MP|publisher=South Staffordshire \u2013 Conservative Association|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828012126/https://www.southstaffsconservatives.org.uk/rt-hon-gavin-williamson-cbe-mp|archivedate=28 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was a charity trustee at a [[Citizen's Advice Bureau]], and a [[school governor]].<ref name=\"About Gavin\"/>\n\nWilliamson is a patron of the World Owl Trust and while chief whip kept a [[Mexican redknee tarantula]], Cronus, in his parliamentary office,<ref name=\"BBC1\"/> for which he was criticised by parliamentary authorities in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCann|first1=Kate|title=Revealed: The first picture of Cronus, the chief whip's pet tarantula|work=The Daily Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/11/24/revealed-first-picture-cronus-chief-whips-pet-tarantula/|date=24 November 2016|accessdate=2 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828040857/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/11/24/revealed-first-picture-cronus-chief-whips-pet-tarantula/|archivedate=28 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he was sworn in as a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]], giving him the [[Honorific|Honorific Title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for life.\n\nIn the [[2016 Prime Minister's Resignation Honours]], Williamson was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) \"for political and public service\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Resignation Honours 2016|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/543929/Resignation-Honours-2016.pdf|website=GOV.UK|publisher=Cabinet Office|accessdate=4 August 2016|date=4 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920054449/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/543929/Resignation-Honours-2016.pdf|archivedate=20 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, it became known that Williamson, while he was managing director of fireplace firm Elgin & Hall in 2004, had an office romance. To save his marriage, he has said he left the firm.<ref name=\"Kentish\">{{cite news|last=Kentih|first=Benjamin|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/gavin-williamson-cheating-defence-secretary-admit-romance-affair-russia-marriage-wife-a8179056.html|title=Gavin Williamson: Tory Defence Secretary admits to 'kissing' trysts with married former colleague|work=The Independent|date=26 January 2018|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127145707/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/gavin-williamson-cheating-defence-secretary-admit-romance-affair-russia-marriage-wife-a8179056.html|archivedate=27 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to Williamson, it became \"flirtatious and a couple of times we shared a kiss\", but it \"never went further\", Williamson told the ''[[Daily Mail]]''.<ref name=\"Syal\">{{cite news|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/26/defence-secretary-questions-relationship-colleague-gavin-williamson|title=Defence secretary refuses to answer questions about relationship with past colleague|work=The Guardian|date=26 January 2018|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127151405/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/26/defence-secretary-questions-relationship-colleague-gavin-williamson|archivedate=27 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \"My family means everything to me and I almost threw it away\", Williamson said. \"This incident nearly destroyed two marriages\".<ref name=\"Kentish\"/> ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'' reported that a senior co-worker stated that the woman involved was in tears when reporting the incident at work and that Williamson was subsequently the subject of a meeting with managers.<ref name=telegraph-20180128>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/27/female-colleague-gavin-williamson-shared-kiss-tears-claimed/ |title=Female colleague Gavin Williamson 'shared kiss' with was in tears, it was claimed |first=Nicola |last=Harley|first2= Steve |last2=Bird|first3= Victoria |last3=Ward |newspaper=Sunday Telegraph |date=28 January 2018 |accessdate=28 January 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127221036/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/27/female-colleague-gavin-williamson-shared-kiss-tears-claimed/ |archivedate=27 January 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://