-29|website=Cafe Dissensus Everyday|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n*-- (31 March, 2020). \"Corona-phobia: Times of Stress and Angst\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/472838/Coronaphobia:-Times-of-Stress-and-Angst|title=Corona-phobia: Times of Stress and Angst|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Book review==\n\n* \u201c''The Story of an Inspirational Figure''\u201d- a review by Askari of the [[biography]] of [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman|Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] by Syed Badrul Ahsan published by the Embassy of [[Bangladesh]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C]]. News on 15 Jan 2014.[[File:On the Great Wall of China.png|thumb|Askari climbing the Great Wall of China (May 2019)]]\n* A review of his book \u201c''Nineteen Seventy One''\u201d published by Rubric Publishing, [[New Delhi]], [[India]] in 2019\u00a0 has been published in the March\u2013April 2019 edition of Indian [[Literature]] published by [[Sahitya Akademi]], India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=131541|title=Nineteen seventy one and other stories - Book Review - observerbd.com|website=The Daily Observer|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n*A review of the book \u201c''Nineteen Seventy One''\u201d published by the International Journal of Community and Social Development, written by Dr. Manohar Pawar, Professor of Social Work at [[Charles Sturt University]], NSW, [[Australia]], and the President of the International Consortium for Social Development.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pawar|first=Manohar|date=2019-12-01|title=Askari Rashid, Nineteen Seventy One: Short Stories.|journal=The International Journal of Community and Social Development|language=en|volume=1|issue=4|pages=357\u2013358|doi=10.1177/2516602619889245|issn=2516-6026}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAskari was married to Masuma Ferdous in 1994 and fathered a son, Humayun Rashid Askari (born 1999) and a daughter, Roja Askari (born 2006). He has a natural inclination to read and collect books and to travel around the world.\n\n==Awards==\n\n*Askari has been awarded the Oitijjo Gold Medal 2019 by [[Bangladesh]] [[Folklore studies|Folklore]] Research Centre of [[Rajshahi University]] for his contribution to the fields of [[literature]] and [[education]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/arcprint/details/385380/Abul-Hossain-Askari-awarded-for-contribution-to-education-sector-%0A/2019-04-16|title=Abul Hossain, Askari awarded for contribution to education sector|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ourtimebd.com/beta/2019/04/17/iu-vc-dr-rashid-askari-awarded-oitijjha-gold-medal/|title=IU VC Dr. Rashid Askari awarded 'Oitijjha Gold Medal'|date=2019-04-16|website=OurtimeBD|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n* He has also received \"Janonetri Sheikh Hasina Award 2019\" for his outstanding contribution to [[education]] sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/427995/IU-VC-awarded-\u2018Jononetri-Sheikh-Hasina-Sommanona-Padak2019\u2019|title=IU VC awarded 'Jononetri Sheikh Hasina Sommanona Padak-2019'|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n*Rashid Askari won the Dhaka University Alumni News Award 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/219291/?regenerate|title=IU VC wins DU Alumni News Award {{!}} The Asian Age Online, Bangladesh|website=The Asian Age|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite news |title=The Wounded Land: A Reflection on today's Bangladesh |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2245967821.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011163021/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2245967821.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 October 2013 |newspaper=Dhaka Courier |date=23 January 2011 |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |url-access=subscription }}\n* {{cite web |url=https://iu.ac.bd/public/images/teacher/98ed3195b5e64441bf3901059b4905a3.pdf |title=Curriculum Vitae: Rashid Askari |website=Islamic University, Kushtia |accessdate=12 November 2013}}\n\n{{refend}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Askari, Rashid}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi academics]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male writers]]\n[[Category:University of Dhaka alumni]]\n[[Category:Savitribai Phule Pune University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Tone|date=April 2020}}\n{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Bangladeshi writer and academic}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Harun-Ur-Rashid Askari\n| native_name         = \u09b0\u09be\u09b6\u09bf\u09a6 \u0986\u09b8\u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09c0\n| image               = Rashid.jpg\n| caption             = Askari in January 2020\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1965|06|01}}\n| birth_place         = Askarpur, [[Mithapukur]], [[Rangpur District|Rangpur]], [[East Pakistan]], Present day [[Bangladesh]]\n| office              = [[Vice-Chancellor]] of [[Islamic University, Bangladesh|Islamic University]]\n| term_start          = 21 August 2016\n| nationality         = Bangladeshi\n| occupation          = Writer, fictionist, columnist, university academic, media personality\n| alma_mater          = {{unbulleted list|[[University of Dhaka]]|[[University of Pune]]}}\n| signature           = \u09b0\u09be\u09b6\u09bf\u09a6 \u0986\u09b8\u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09c0\u09b0 \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09b0.png\n}}\n\n'''Harun-Ur-Rashid Askari''' (born 1 June 1965), popularly known as '''Rashid Askari''', is a Bengali-English writer, fictionist, columnist, translator, media personality and an academic in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://themissingslate.com/2015/10/01/a-brief-history-of-bangladeshi-writing-in-english/2/| title= A brief history of Bangladeshi writing in English| publisher=The Missing Slate | date=1 October 2015 | accessdate= 9 July 2017}}</ref> He is the current and the 12th [[vice-chancellor]] of [[Islamic University, Bangladesh]] in [[Kushtia]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newagebd.net/247604/rashid-askari-made-iu-vc/ | title=Rashid Askari made IU VC | publisher=New Age | date=22 August 2016 | accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRashid was born in a sleepy little village called Askarpur situated in the district of Rangpur<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sangatreview.org/blog/2016/04/30/rashid-askari/|title=Rashid Askari \u2013 Sangat Book Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> in 1965 in erstwhile East Pakistan (now Bangladesh) during one of the most tumultuous times in the country's history. M. A. Mannan, an English teacher and headmaster, was his father and Setara Begum, a naive housewife, is his mother. Rashid passed the secondary school and higher secondary certificate examinations in 1980 and 1982 with outstanding merit. He \"obtained Honours and Master\u2019s degrees in English from [[Dhaka University]] with distinction, and a PhD in [[Indian English Literature]] from the [[University of Poona]]\".<ref name=\"ds18Sep2016\">{{cite news |title=A Talk with IU VC |url=http://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/167531/A-Talk-with-IU-VC |newspaper=Daily Sun |location=Dhaka |date=18 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306035353/http://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/167531/A-Talk-with-IU-VC |archive-date=6 March 2017}}</ref> Bangladesh Liberation War of 1971 broke out when Rashid was a 7-year- old boy. To his utter shock and horror, he saw the ravages of the war which have made a tremendous impact on his juvenile mind.\n\n==Career==\n\nAskari joined [[Islamic University, Bangladesh|Islamic University]], Kushtia as a lecturer in English in 1990. He became a professor in 2005 and was head of the English department more than once. He served with King Khalid University- the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia as a professor of English for five years (2008-2013). He had occasions to work and mix with multinational and multicultural academics and scholars.Dr. Askari emerged as a writer in the mid nineties of the last century (20 th ). Until recently, he has written half a dozen books and a large number of articles, essays and newspaper columns on a great variety of themes ranging from national to international, colonial to postcolonial, which have been published at home and abroad. He was elected the Secretary General of Federation of Bangladesh University Teachers' Association for 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Farid made president, Rashid secy gen of FBUTA |url=http://old-archives.newagebd.net/detail.php?date=2014-03-09&nid=86011 |newspaper=New Age |location=Dhaka |agency=BSS |date=9 March 2014}}</ref> He was \"made new chairman of Folklore Studies Department of the university in [[Kushtia District|Kushtia]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=IU Folklore Dept gets new chairman|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2016/01/21/11828|newspaper=The Financial Express|location=Dhaka |agency=BSS |date=21 January 2016}}</ref> Askari has been nominated as a part-time member of the University Grants Commission of Bangladesh (UGC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/434781/Dr-Rashid-Askari-nominated-UGC-parttime-member|title=Dr Rashid Askari nominated UGC part-time member|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref> He is working as a member of \"the international publication and translation sub-committee\" under \"Bangabandhu\u2019s Birth Centenary Celebration National Implementation Committee\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bssnews.net/?p=283009|title=Coffee table book to be published on Bangabandhu {{!}} Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha (BSS)|last=Mosharrof|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> and translated Sheikh Mujib's 10 January speech delivered at the Race Course into English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/supplements/bangabandhus-homecoming-day/news/we-dont-know-defeat-1852090|title='We don't know defeat'|date=2020-01-10|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nHe is a peer reviewer and a Quality Assurance(QA) expert nominated by the Quality Assurance Unit of the Government of [[Bangladesh|People's Republic of Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qau.gov.bd/system/files/reports/Peer%20Reviewers%20panel%20(Bangladesh).pdf |title=Peer Reviewers Panel (QA experts) |website=Quality Assurance Unit, University Grants Commission |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921020121/http://www.qau.gov.bd/system/files/reports/Peer%20Reviewers%20panel%20(Bangladesh).pdf |archive-date=21 September 2016}}</ref> \"...Askari regularly writes columns in various newspapers\"...<ref name=\"ds18Sep2016\" /> \"The areas of his academic interest include Modern and Postmodern Fiction, Colonial and Postcolonial Literatures, South-Asian Writing in English, Literary Theories and Creative Writing\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.sangatreview.org/rashid-askari/ | title=Rashid Askari \u2013 Sangat Book Review}}</ref> In the recent past \"Askari has been accorded gold medal for his contribution to advancement of education sector\" in Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/385380|title=Abul Hossain, Askari awarded for contribution to education sector|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/173438/?regenerate|title=IU VC got PBA gold medal {{!}} The Asian Age Online, Bangladesh|website=The Asian Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> He has also received \"Janonetri Sheikh Hasina Award 2019\" for his outstanding contribution to education sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/427995/IU-VC-awarded-\u2018Jononetri-Sheikh-Hasina-Sommanona-Padak2019\u2019|title=IU VC awarded 'Jononetri Sheikh Hasina Sommanona Padak-2019'|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>   \n\n==Writing style==\n\nDr. Askari had a flair for creative writing since his school days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sangatreview.org/blog/2016/04/30/rashid-askari/|title=Rashid Askari \u2013 Sangat Book Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> An unsigned profile in ''The Kushtia Times'' stated that Askari writes \"both Bengali and English with equal ease and efficiency\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile of the week--Dr. Rashid Askari: Fiction writer, critic, columnist, teacher, and social analyst |url=http://www.thekushtiatimes.com/09/01/2012/profile-of-the-week/ |newspaper=The Kushtia Times |date=9 January 2012}}</ref> Bangladeshi novelist and critic [[Syed Manzoorul Islam]] notes: \"He writes witty, racy stories with surprisingly serious undertones. Picking real-life events from the remote areas and the marginal people of the country and weaving them into various fictional forms are the hallmarks of his storytelling. ... Though not new in a ground-breaking way, his stories are both intense and original. The overall tone of his language is gently sarcastic ...\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Islam |first=Syed Manzoorul |authorlink=Syed Manzoorul Islam |date=16 February 2012 |title=Nineteen seventy one and other stories: a collection of short stories |url=http://www.dhakacourier.com.bd/?p=4899 |newspaper=Dhaka Courier |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523232442/http://www.dhakacourier.com.bd/?p=4899 |archive-date=23 May 2013}}</ref> \"Dr. Askari has demonstrated enough artistic talent to come up with fiction in English, which must be a source of inspiration for many of us\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/arcprint/details/167531/A-Talk-with-IU-VC/2016-09-18|title=A Talk with IU VC|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In his short story collection ''Nineteen Seventy One and Other Stories''(2011) \"Rashid Askari speaks of a long-ago war, revisiting the age of brutality we emerged free of through beating back the denizens of darkness\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/opinion/op-ed/2019/08/22/a-chronicler-of-the-human-soul?fbclid=IwAR05ybsYp1fZgPL_slBomUp0ifBBZvZsLx4CIqHWzZpH6dwOq9V5pwAgubI|title=A chronicler of the human soul|date=2019-08-22|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The book has been translated into [[French language|French Language]] and also into [[Hindi]]\"'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bangladeshpost.net/iu-vcs-book-translated-into-french|title=IU VC's book translated into French|last=Desk|first=BD Post|date=2018-12-01|website=A Daily with a Difference {{!}} Latest Online English Daily among Bangladesh Newspapers|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>.''' ''His story \"''The Disclosure''\"'' was published in the emerging and seasoned writers publishing platform Kitaab'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kitaab.org/2019/10/12/short-story-the-disclosure/|title=Short Story: The Disclosure|last=Chakravarty|first=Mitali|date=2019-10-12|website=kitaab|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Another story \"The virgin whore\" was published in  the [[New York City|New York]] City and [[India]] based magazine Cafe Dissensus''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cafedissensusblog.com/2019/03/31/short-story-the-virgin-whore/|title=Short Story: The virgin whore|last=WordPress.com|first=Blog at|date=2019-03-31|website=Cafe Dissensus Everyday|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>''. His short story \"Virus''\"'' was published in the Daily Sun's Eid Special 2017 and \u201cA slice of sky\u201d has been published in the Contemporary Literary Review India (CLRI), a peer-reviewed , internationally refereed and high impact factor journal.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Askari|first=Dr Rashid|date=2019-11-05|title=A Slice of Sky|url=https://literaryjournal.in/index.php/clri/article/view/385|journal=Contemporary Literary Review India|language=en|volume=6|issue=4|pages=68\u201391|issn=2394-6075}}</ref> \"Sharp and minute detailed description of human behaviour, and pictorial presentation of events and settings in his carefully chosen words demonstrate Rashid Askari\u2019s mastery in story writing/telling,\" says the President of the International Consortium for Social Development and Professor of Social Work at Charles Sturt University, NSW, Australia, Dr. Manohar Pawar.'''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pawar|first=Manohar|date=2019-12-01|title=Askari Rashid, Nineteen Seventy One: Short Stories.|journal=The International Journal of Community and Social Development|language=en|volume=1|issue=4|pages=357\u2013358|doi=10.1177/2516602619889245|issn=2516-6026}}</ref>'''\n\n==Works==\n[[File:Addressing an international conference in Kunming, China. December 2018.jpg|thumb|Askari addressing an international conference in Kunming, China. (December 15, 2018)]]\n\n=== Books ===\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |year=1996 |script-title=bn:\u09ae\u09c1\u09ae\u09c2\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7\u09c1 \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 |trans-title=The Dying Homeland |location=Dhaka |language=bn}}  \n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=1996 | script-title=bn:\u0987\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cb-\u0987\u0982\u09b0\u09c7\u099c\u09bf \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af \u0993 \u0985\u09a8\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af|trans-title= Indo-English Literature and Others|location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=1997 |script-title=bn:\u098f\u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b0\u09c2\u09aa\u0995\u09a5\u09be|trans-title=Today's Folktale|location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2001 |script-title=bn:\u09ac\u09bf\u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09cd\u09ae\u09bf\u09a4 \u09ad\u09be\u09ac\u09a8\u09be |trans-title=Deconstructing Thoughts |location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2002 |script-title=bn:\u0989\u09a4\u09cd\u09a4\u09b0\u09be\u09a7\u09c1\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af \u0993 \u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09b2\u09cb\u099a\u09a8\u09be \u09a4\u09a4\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac |trans-title=Postmodern Literary and Critical Theory |location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2010 |title=The Wounded Land: Peoples, Politics, Culture, Literature, Liberation War, War Crimes, and Militancy in Bangladesh |location=Dhaka |publisher=Pathak Shamabesh |oclc=708243896}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2011 |title=Nineteen seventy one and other stories: a collection of short stories |location=Dhaka |publisher=Pathak Shamabesh |isbn=978-9848866436}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2012\u201313 |title= English Writings of Tagore(3 volumes) |location=Dhaka |publisher=Pathak Shamabesh |language=English|isbn=978-984-8866-40-5}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2018 |title=1971 Aur Anya Kahaniyan: Hindi translation of short story collection |location=New Delhi |publisher= Bhashak an imprint of Rubric Publishing |isbn=978-81935295-7-7}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2018 |title=Les CONTES D\u00e9chirants De 1971: French translation of short story collection |location=New Delhi |publisher= Rubric Publishing |isbn=9788193831281}}\n\n=== Short stories ===\n\n* \u2014\u2014 (3 August 2011). {{cite journal |last= |first= |date= |title=Lottery |url=http://www.contemporaryliteraryreviewindia.com/2011/08/lottery-short-story-by-dr-rashid-askari.html |journal=Contemporary Literary Review India |volume= |issue= |pages= |issn= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023060908/http://www.contemporaryliteraryreviewindia.com/2011/08/lottery-short-story-by-dr-rashid-askari.html |archive-date=23 October 2013|via=}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=December 2011 |title=Nineteen seventy one |url=http://www.jpcs.in/upload/756969896Nineteen%20seventy%20one.pdf |journal=Journal of Postcolonial Cultures and Societies |publisher=Wright State University |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=118\u2013122 |issn=1948-1845}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=January 2012 |title=Jihad |url= |journal=Contemporary Literary Review India |volume= |issue= |pages=15\u201318 |issn=2250-3366 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=June 2012 |title=Locked-in Syndrome |url=http://issuu.com/khurshid_alam/docs/clrijun2012 |journal=Contemporary Literary Review India |volume= |issue= |pages=33\u201340 |issn=2250-3366}}\n*\u2014\u2014 (12 October, 2019) ''\"''The Disclosure''\"'' .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kitaab.org/2019/10/12/short-story-the-disclosure/|title=Short Story: The Disclosure|last=Chakravarty|first=Mitali|date=2019-10-12|website=kitaab|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n*\u2014\u2014 (31 March, 2019) \"The virgin whore\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cafedissensusblog.com/2019/03/31/short-story-the-virgin-whore/|title=Short Story: The virgin whore|last=WordPress.com|first=Blog at|date=2019-03-31|website=Cafe Dissensus Everyday|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n*\u2014\u2014 (2017) \"Virus''\"'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/arcprint/details/236318/Virus/2017-06-25|title=Virus|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>.\n*\u2014\u2014(November 2019) \u201cA slice of sky\u201d<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Askari|first=Dr Rashid|date=2019-11-05|title=A Slice of Sky|url=https://literaryjournal.in/index.php/clri/article/view/385|journal=Contemporary Literary Review India|language=en|volume=6|issue=4|pages=68\u201391|issn=2394-6075}}</ref>\n\n=== Articles ===\n\n* {{cite journal |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=December 2011 |title=Future of literature: Global Art-Malady and its Consequences |url=http://litsearch.co.in/Volume%201%20No.%201/1-4.pdf |journal=Litsearch |publisher=M. A. Hafiz Siddiqui |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=1\u20134 |issn=2277-6990}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=15 December 2007 |title=War crime and the criminal |url=http://www.bt.com.bn/node/28066/print |newspaper=The Brunei Times}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=14 March 2012 |title=Eve-teasing in Bangladesh: Crime and punishment |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/03/14/eve-teasing-in-bangladesh-crime-and-punishment/ |newspaper=African Herald Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315201627/http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/03/14/eve-teasing-in-bangladesh-crime-and-punishment/ |archive-date=15 March 2012}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=14 March 2012 |title=Psychological torture on women and the legal cure |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/03/17/psychological-torture-on%C2%A0women-and-the-legal-cure/ |newspaper=African Herald Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318174240/http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/03/17/psychological-torture-on%C2%A0women-and-the-legal-cure/ |archive-date=18 March 2012}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=10 April 2012 |title=Population explosion and the fate of mankind |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/04/10/population-explosion-and-the-fate-of-mankind-by-dr-rashid-askari/ |newspaper=African Herald Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422120955/http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/04/10/population-explosion-and-the-fate-of-mankind-by-dr-rashid-askari/ |archive-date=22 April 2012}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=10 May 2012 |title=Bangladesh's conquest of the sea: a daunting prospect |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/05/10/bangladeshs-conquest-of-the-sea-a-daunting-prospect/ |newspaper=African Herald Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120629114321/http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/05/10/bangladeshs-conquest-of-the-sea-a-daunting-prospect/ |archive-date=29 June 2012}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=17 February 2013 |title=Historic 21 February and the birth of a nation |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2013/02/17/historic-21st-february-and-the-birth-of-nation-by-rashid-askari/ |newspaper=African Herald Express}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=5 May 2013 |title=The biggest industrial disaster in Bangladesh |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2013/05/05/the-biggest-industrial-disaster-in-bangladesh-by-dr-rashid-askari-2/ |newspaper=African Herald Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615080512/http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2013/05/05/the-biggest-industrial-disaster-in-bangladesh-by-dr-rashid-askari-2/ |archive-date=15 June 2013}}\n*\u2014\u2014 ( January 2012). \"Tipaimukh Dam and Indian Hydropolitics\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.thedailystar.net/forum/2012/January/tipaimukh.htm?fbclid=IwAR3SFbUl-UdrRJ7BR_L-aAH89VSkoCKXeQuxJSLYqnqFcUvRe7wkYJK8MQY|title=Forum|website=archive.thedailystar.net|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Newspaper columns ==\n[[File:Travel .jpg|thumb|On a cruise in Bosphorus Strait. 2019]]\n\n*-- (28 February, 2018). \"Bangla Should Be a UN Language\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/291923/Bangla-Should-Be-a-UN-Language|title=Bangla Should Be a UN Language|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n* ''--'' (13th February, 2018). \"Valentine\u2019s Day and an Anatomy of Love\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/post/288819/Valentine\u2019s-Day-and-an-Anatomy-of-Love|title=Valentine\u2019s Day and an Anatomy of Love|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n*-- (3 November, 2018). \"Dhaka Translation Fest: A Window on the World\".<ref>{{Cite w