l Unrest, Peace and Development\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cafedissensusblog.com/2019/09/22/7th-icsdap-conference-on-social-unrest-peace-and-development/|title=7th ICSDAP Conference on Social Unrest, Peace and Development|last=WordPress.com|first=Blog at|date=2019-09-22|website=Cafe Dissensus Everyday|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n*-- (30 March, 2020). \"Life in the Time of Corona\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cafedissensusblog.com/2020/03/30/life-in-the-time-of-corona/|title=Life in the Time of Corona|last=WordPress.com|first=Create a free website or blog at|date=2020-03-29|website=Cafe Dissensus Everyday|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n*-- (31 March, 2020). \"Corona-phobia: Times of Stress and Angst\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/472838/Coronaphobia:-Times-of-Stress-and-Angst|title=Corona-phobia: Times of Stress and Angst|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Book review==\n\n* \u201c''The Story of an Inspirational Figure''\u201d- a review by Askari of the [[biography]] of [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman|Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] by Syed Badrul Ahsan published by the Embassy of [[Bangladesh]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington D.C]]. News on 15 Jan 2014.[[File:On the Great Wall of China.png|thumb|Askari climbing the Great Wall of China (May 2019)]]\n* A review of his book \u201c''Nineteen Seventy One''\u201d published by Rubric Publishing, [[New Delhi]], [[India]] in 2019\u00a0 has been published in the March\u2013April 2019 edition of Indian [[Literature]] published by [[Sahitya Akademi]], India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=131541|title=Nineteen seventy one and other stories - Book Review - observerbd.com|website=The Daily Observer|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n*A review of the book \u201c''Nineteen Seventy One''\u201d published by the International Journal of Community and Social Development, written by Dr. Manohar Pawar, Professor of Social Work at [[Charles Sturt University]], NSW, [[Australia]], and the President of the International Consortium for Social Development.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pawar|first=Manohar|date=2019-12-01|title=Askari Rashid, Nineteen Seventy One: Short Stories.|journal=The International Journal of Community and Social Development|language=en|volume=1|issue=4|pages=357\u2013358|doi=10.1177/2516602619889245|issn=2516-6026}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAskari was married to Masuma Ferdous in 1994 and fathered a son, Humayun Rashid Askari (born 1999) and a daughter, Roja Askari (born 2006). He has a natural inclination to read and collect books and to travel around the world.\n\n==Awards==\n\n*Askari has been awarded the Oitijjo Gold Medal 2019 by [[Bangladesh]] [[Folklore studies|Folklore]] Research Centre of [[Rajshahi University]] for his contribution to the fields of [[literature]] and [[education]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/arcprint/details/385380/Abul-Hossain-Askari-awarded-for-contribution-to-education-sector-%0A/2019-04-16|title=Abul Hossain, Askari awarded for contribution to education sector|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ourtimebd.com/beta/2019/04/17/iu-vc-dr-rashid-askari-awarded-oitijjha-gold-medal/|title=IU VC Dr. Rashid Askari awarded 'Oitijjha Gold Medal'|date=2019-04-16|website=OurtimeBD|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n* He has also received \"Janonetri Sheikh Hasina Award 2019\" for his outstanding contribution to [[education]] sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/427995/IU-VC-awarded-\u2018Jononetri-Sheikh-Hasina-Sommanona-Padak2019\u2019|title=IU VC awarded 'Jononetri Sheikh Hasina Sommanona Padak-2019'|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n*Rashid Askari won the Dhaka University Alumni News Award 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/219291/?regenerate|title=IU VC wins DU Alumni News Award {{!}} The Asian Age Online, Bangladesh|website=The Asian Age|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite news |title=The Wounded Land: A Reflection on today's Bangladesh |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2245967821.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011163021/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2245967821.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 October 2013 |newspaper=Dhaka Courier |date=23 January 2011 |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |url-access=subscription }}\n* {{cite web |url=https://iu.ac.bd/public/images/teacher/98ed3195b5e64441bf3901059b4905a3.pdf |title=Curriculum Vitae: Rashid Askari |website=Islamic University, Kushtia |accessdate=12 November 2013}}\n\n{{refend}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Askari, Rashid}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi academics]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male writers]]\n[[Category:University of Dhaka alumni]]\n[[Category:Savitribai Phule Pune University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Shanta9090", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education:I have fixed the article's tone as per wiki rules", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rashid_Askari"}
{"title_page": "G\u00e9rald Genta", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Gerald Charles Genta\n| image                     = Gerald Genta.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = G\u00e9rald Charles Genta\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1931|5|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Geneva]], [[Restoration (Switzerland)|Switzerland]]\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|2011|8|17|1931|5|1|df=y}}\n| death_place               = \n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = Swiss\n| known_for                 = \n| education                 = \n| occupation                = Watchmaker, businessman, designer\n}}\n\n'''G\u00e9rald Charles Genta''' (1931-2011) was a Swiss watch designer and artist. He is known for his eponymous line of timepieces as well as his design work with other high-end watch manufacturers, including [[International Watch Company|IWC]], [[Omega SA]], [[Universal Gen\u00e8ve]], [[Patek Philippe]] and [[Audemars Piguet]].  [[Christie's]] auction house of New York has called Genta's work ''\"the [[Faberg\u00e9]] of watches\"'',<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Guest\n  | first = Tim\n  | title = My Life in Orange: Growing Up with the Guru (page 258)\n  | publisher = Mariner Books\n  | year = 2005\n  | isbn = 0-15-603106-X\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/mylifeinorange00gues\n  }}</ref> while ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' has called them the \"world's most complicated and pricey watches\".<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | work = [[The Wall Street Journal]] (Index, Volume 1; page 429) | publisher = [[Dow Jones & Company]]\n  | year = 1996\n  | isbn = \n}}</ref>\n\n==Early Life==\nGenta was born in Geneva to a Swiss mother and father of [[Piemonte]] (Northern Italian) descent.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} At age 20, Genta finished jewellery and [[goldsmith]] training in his native Switzerland, earning a Swiss federal diploma.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n== Starting career with Universal Gen\u00e8ve ==\nSubsequently, Genta was recruited by [[Universal Gen\u00e8ve]] SA, at the time one of the most recognized manufactures in both the U.S. and Europe for its chronograph models.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} After Universal Gen\u00e8ve settled a patent dispute involving the micro-rotor caliber, Genta designed Universal's [[Universal Gen\u00e8ve#1950s-1960s: Microtor automatics|Polerouter Microtors]] in the 1950s, as well as the Golden and White Shadows during the mid-1960s.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} The Shadows contained a micro-rotor, [[Unisonic Products Corporation|unisonic]] and [[accutron]] movement, the latter two a result of the [[quartz crisis]] starting in the late 1960s.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n== Notable watch designs ==\nGenta's work with Universal would be a precursor to future collaborations with other brands in Switzerland and throughout Europe, including Omega's ''Constellation'' (1959); [[Patek Philippe]]'s ''Golden Ellipse'' (1968). [[Audemars Piguet]]'s ''Royal Oak'' (1970), [[International Watch Company|IWC]]'s ''Ingenieur'' (1976); Patek Philippe's ''Nautilus'' (1976); and [[Cartier (jeweler)|Cartier]]'s ''Pasha de Cartier'' (1985).{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n== Eponymous brand & Designs ==\n[[File:G\u00e9rald Genta watch.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Gerald Genta ''Gefica Mt. Kilimanjaro'']]\n\nAfter starting his own brand in 1969, Genta would create the [[sonnerie]]s, among them the G\u00e9rald Genta ''Octo Granda Sonnerie Tourbillion'', which contained four [[gong]]s and an emulated [[Westminster Quarters]] bell ring at each quarter and on the hour, \"the same melody rung out by London's Big Ben\", and priced at $810,200.<ref>Jack Forster, \"For whom the bell tolls; For thee if you wear a minute repeater, the most complicated watch there is\", p. 101 December 2009 ''Forbes Life''</ref> In 1994, he designed the ''Grande Sonnerie Retro'', the world's most complicated wristwatch, and priced at approximately $2 million.<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Aylmer, Editor in Chief\n  | first = Sean\n  | title = [[Business Review Weekly]] (Volume 13, Issues 33-42)\n  | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]]\n  | year = 1998\n  | isbn = \n}}</ref> For private requests, Genta hand-designed the movements, dials and cases of his timepieces and employed limited or no external assistance, outsourcing or mechanization during the process; it was not unusual for a single watch to take up to 5 years to complete.<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Chilton &\n  | first = Co\n  | title = Jewelers' circular-keystone (CK., Volume 166, Issues 7-9)\n  | publisher = \n  | year = 1995\n  | isbn = \n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, Genta obtained special licensing with [[The Walt Disney Company]] and distributed a limited edition of Disney character watches to the public; previously, they had been an unofficial private request by one of Genta's repeat customers. The dials consisted of illustrations of [[Mickey Mouse]], Minnie Mouse, [[Donald Duck]], Scrooge and Goofy, with cases made of [[18 carat]] gold. Designed in [[Le Brassus]], Switzerland, the watches retailed between $3250\u2013$3650 in 1988.<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | title = [[Texas Monthly]] (December 1988)\n  | publisher = [[Emmis Communications]]\n  | year = 1988\n  | isbn = \n}}</ref>\n\n=== Previous clients ===\n[[File:Evolution.jpg|thumb|125px|right|Gerald Charles ''A-Evolution'']]\n\nGenta's clients have included athletes, businesspeople, musicians, movie stars, politicians, and royalty, including [[Prince Rainier of Monaco]], King [[Hassan II of Morocco]], King [[Juan Carlos]] and Queen [[Sofia of Spain]], King [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]] of England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.watchtime.at/archive/wt_2006_06/WT_2006_06_134.pdf|accessdate=3 January 2013|title=The Genta Touch}}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisition by Bulgari ===\nAfter his eponymous company, trade marks, patents and designs were acquired by [[Bulgari]] in 2000, Genta resigned and created a new venture called [[Gerald Charles (company)|Gerald Charles]]. As of 2010, Gerald Genta watches were marketed solely under the Bulgari brand. In 2019, Bulgari celebrated the 50th anniversary of the Gerald Genta mark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monochrome-watches.com/bvlgari-tribute-to-gerald-genta-platinum-arena-bi-retro-limited-edition-2019-price/|title=SIHH 2019 - Bvlgari Gerald Genta 50th Anniversary 103191 Arena Bi-Retro|date=2019-01-15|website=Monochrome Watches|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>.\n\n== Death ==\nGenta died in August 2011 at age 80.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.audemarspiguet.com/manufacture/news/tribute-to-gerald-genta-98/|accessdate=28 August 2011|title=Tribute to G\u00e9rald Genta|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910090905/http://www.audemarspiguet.com/manufacture/news/tribute-to-gerald-genta-98/|archivedate=10 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Genta, Gerald}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Swiss people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Swiss businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Geneva]]\n[[Category:Swiss watchmakers (people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Gerald Charles Genta\n| image                     = Gerald Genta.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = G\u00e9rald Charles Genta\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1931|5|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Geneva]], [[Restoration (Switzerland)|Switzerland]]\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|2011|8|17|1931|5|1|df=y}}\n| death_place               = \n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = Swiss\n| known_for                 = \n| education                 = \n| occupation                = Watchmaker, businessman, designer\n}}\n\n'''G\u00e9rald Charles Genta''' (1931-2011) was a Swiss watch designer and artist. He is known for his eponymous line of timepieces as well as his design work with other high-end watch manufacturers, including [[International Watch Company|IWC]], [[Omega SA]], [[Universal Gen\u00e8ve]], [[Patek Philippe]] and [[Audemars Piguet]].  [[Christie's]] auction house of New York has called Genta's work ''\"the [[Faberg\u00e9]] of watches\"'',<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Guest\n  | first = Tim\n  | title = My Life in Orange: Growing Up with the Guru (page 258)\n  | publisher = Mariner Books\n  | year = 2005\n  | isbn = 0-15-603106-X\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/mylifeinorange00gues\n  }}</ref> while ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' has called them the \"world's most complicated and pricey watches\".<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | work = [[The Wall Street Journal]] (Index, Volume 1; page 429) | publisher = [[Dow Jones & Company]]\n  | year = 1996\n  | isbn = \n}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nGenta was born in Geneva to a Swiss mother and father of [[Piemonte]] (Northern Italian) descent.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} At age 20, Genta finished jewellery and [[goldsmith]] training in his native Switzerland, earning a Swiss federal diploma.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nSubsequently, Genta was recruited by [[Universal Gen\u00e8ve]] SA, at the time one of the most recognized manufactures in both the U.S. and Europe for its chronograph models.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} After Universal Gen\u00e8ve settled a patent dispute involving the micro-rotor caliber, Genta designed Universal's [[Universal Gen\u00e8ve#1950s-1960s: Microtor automatics|Polerouter Microtors]] in the 1950s, as well as the Golden and White Shadows during the mid-1960s.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} The Shadows contained a micro-rotor, [[Unisonic Products Corporation|unisonic]] and [[accutron]] movement, the latter two a result of the [[quartz crisis]] starting in the late 1960s.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nGenta's work with Universal would be a precursor to future collaborations with other brands in Switzerland and throughout Europe, including Omega's ''Constellation'' (1959); [[Patek Philippe]]'s ''Golden Ellipse'' (1968). [[Audemars Piguet]]'s ''Royal Oak'' (1970), [[International Watch Company|IWC]]'s ''Ingenieur'' (1976); Patek Philippe's ''Nautilus'' (1976); and [[Cartier (jeweler)|Cartier]]'s ''Pasha de Cartier'' (1985).{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n[[File:G\u00e9rald Genta watch.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Gerald Genta ''Gefica Mt. Kilimanjaro'']]\n\nAfter starting his own brand in 1969, Genta would create the [[sonnerie]]s, among them the G\u00e9rald Genta ''Octo Granda Sonnerie Tourbillion'', which contained four [[gong]]s and an emulated [[Westminster Quarters]] bell ring at each quarter and on the hour, \"the same melody rung out by London's Big Ben\", and priced at $810,200.<ref>Jack Forster, \"For whom the bell tolls; For thee if you wear a minute repeater, the most complicated watch there is\", p. 101 December 2009 ''Forbes Life''</ref> In 1994, he designed the ''Grande Sonnerie Retro'', the world's most complicated wristwatch, and priced at approximately $2 million.<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Aylmer, Editor in Chief\n  | first = Sean\n  | title = [[Business Review Weekly]] (Volume 13, Issues 33-42)\n  | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]]\n  | year = 1998\n  | isbn = \n}}</ref> For private requests, Genta hand-designed the movements, dials and cases of his timepieces and employed limited or no external assistance, outsourcing or mechanization during the process; it was not unusual for a single watch to take up to 5 years to complete.<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Chilton &\n  | first = Co\n  | title = Jewelers' circular-keystone (CK., Volume 166, Issues 7-9)\n  | publisher = \n  | year = 1995\n  | isbn = \n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, Genta obtained special licensing with [[The Walt Disney Company]] and distributed a limited edition of Disney character watches to the public; previously, they had been an unofficial private request by one of Genta's repeat customers. The dials consisted of illustrations of [[Mickey Mouse]], Minnie Mouse, [[Donald Duck]], Scrooge and Goofy, with cases made of [[18 carat]] gold. Designed in [[Le Brassus]], Switzerland, the watches retailed between $3250\u2013$3650 in 1988.<ref>{{cite book\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | title = [[Texas Monthly]] (December 1988)\n  | publisher = [[Emmis Communications]]\n  | year = 1988\n  | isbn = \n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Evolution.jpg|thumb|125px|right|Gerald Charles ''A-Evolution'']]\n\nGenta's clients have included athletes, businesspeople, musicians, movie stars, politicians, and royalty, including [[Prince Rainier of Monaco]], King [[Hassan II of Morocco]], King [[Juan Carlos]] and Queen [[Sofia of Spain]], King [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]] of England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.watchtime.at/archive/wt_2006_06/WT_2006_06_134.pdf|accessdate=3 January 2013|title=The Genta Touch}}</ref>\n\nAfter his eponymous company, trade marks, patents and designs were acquired by [[Bulgari]] in 2000, Genta resigned and created a new venture called [[Gerald Charles (company)|Gerald Charles]]. As of 2010, Gerald Genta watches were marketed solely under the Bulgari brand. In 2019, Bulgari celebrated the 50th anniversary of the Gerald Genta mark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monochrome-watches.com/bvlgari-tribute-to-gerald-genta-platinum-arena-bi-retro-limited-edition-2019-price/|title=SIHH 2019 - Bvlgari Gerald Genta 50th Anniversary 103191 Arena Bi-Retro|date=2019-01-15|website=Monochrome Watches|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>.\n\nGenta died in August 2011 at age 80.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.audemarspiguet.com/manufacture/news/tribute-to-gerald-genta-98/|accessdate=28 August 2011|title=Tribute to G\u00e9rald Genta|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910090905/http://www.audemarspiguet.com/manufacture/news/tribute-to-gerald-genta-98/|archivedate=10 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Genta, Gerald}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Swiss people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Swiss businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Geneva]]\n[[Category:Swiss watchmakers (people)]]\n", "name_user": "SerAntoniDeMiloni", "label": "safe", "comment": "Categorisation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%A9rald_Genta"}
{"title_page": "Chris Williamson (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Chris Williamson\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Official portrait of Chris Williamson crop 2.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government|Shadow Minister for Fire and Emergency Services]]\n| leader = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start = 3 July 2017\n| term_end = 11 January 2018\n| predecessor = Position established\n| successor = [[Karen Lee (politician)|Karen Lee]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]]\n| parliament2 = \n| majority2 = 2,015 (4.1%)\n| term_start2 = 9 June 2017\n| term_end2 = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Amanda Solloway]]\n| successor2 = Amanda Solloway\n| term_start3 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end3 = 30 March 2015\n| predecessor3 = [[Bob Laxton]]\n| successor3 = [[Amanda Solloway]]\n| birth_name = Christopher Williamson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1956|9|16}}<ref>{{cite book|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.251187|title=Who's Who 2018|publisher=A.C. Black/Bloomsbury/Oxford University Press|year=2017|chapter=Williamson, Christopher, (born 16 Sept. 1956), MP (Lab) Derby North, 2010\u201315 and since 2017}} {{page needed|date=April 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Derby]], [[Derbyshire]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| death_date1 = \n| death_place1 = \n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2019\u2013present)\n| otherparty = [[Labour Party(UK)|Labour]] (1976\u20132019)\n| spouse = {{unbulleted list|{{marriage|Lonny Wilsoncroft<br>|1997|21 May 2004|end=d}}|Maggie Amsbury<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Carr|editor-first1=Tim|editor-last2=Dale|editor-first2=Iain|editor-last3=Waller|editor-first3=Robert|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8cXADgAAQBAJ&pg=PT422&lpg=PT423|title=The Politicos Guide to the New House of Commons 2017|location=London|publisher=Politicos|year=2017|page=423|isbn=9781785902789|accessdate=9 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110061724/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8cXADgAAQBAJ&pg=PT422&lpg=PT423|archivedate=10 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n| alma_mater = [[De Montfort University|Leicester Polytechnic]]\n| website = {{url|chriswilliamsonmp.com|Official website}}\n| caption = Williamson in 2017\n}}\n'''Christopher Williamson''' (born 16 September 1956) is a British [[politician]] who was the [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]] from [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]<ref name=\"UK Parliament\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/chris-williamson/3976|title=Chris Williamson MP|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=16 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617181707/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/chris-williamson/3976|archivedate=17 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> to [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000662|website=BBC News|accessdate=13 December 2019|url-status=live|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122214906/https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000662|archive-date=22 November 2019}}</ref> and from [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]] until [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/general-election-derby-north-results/story-26461496-detail/story.html|title=Chris Williamson|newspaper=[[Derby Telegraph]]|accessdate=16 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151008095123/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/General-Election-Derby-North-results/story-26461496-detail/story.html|archivedate=8 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was [[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government|Shadow Minister for Communities and Local Government]] from October 2010 to October 2013.<ref name=\"UK Parliament\"/>\n\nWilliamson was also a local councillor in [[Derby]], representing the [[Normanton, Derby|Normanton]] ward from 1991 until 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/Chris-Williamson-MP-stands-city-councillor/story-11630752-detail/story.html|title=DERBY North MP Chris Williamson has resigned from his position as councillor for Normanton after 20 years.|publisher=This is Derbyshire|date=26 March 2011|accessdate=19 October 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505085113/http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/Chris-Williamson-MP-stands-city-councillor/story-11630752-detail/story.html|archivedate=5 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> serving twice as leader of [[Derby City Council]].\n\nIn February 2019, Williamson was notified of a formal investigation and later suspended from the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] for his comments about the party's response to criticism over its handling of allegations of [[antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism within the party]].<ref name=suspended>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47393626|title=Labour MP Chris Williamson suspended in anti-Semitism row|date=27 February 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=27 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227171732/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47393626|archivedate=27 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After an investigation, Williamson was reinstated in June 2019 with a formal warning<ref>BBC. \"Labour anti-Semitism row: Chris Williamson allowed back into party\". 26 June 2019, https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48778129 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626171709/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48778129 |date=26 June 2019 }}</ref> but was resuspended two days later when the party decided to review the disciplinary decision.<ref name=\"Kentish\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-williamson-labour-whip-suspended-antisemitism-row-a8979896.html |title=Chris Williamson: Labour MP suspension descends into farce after he has whip removed again two days after being readmitted to party |last=Kentish |first=Benjamin |date=28 June 2019 |work=[[The Independent]] |access-date=29 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629075147/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-williamson-labour-whip-suspended-antisemitism-row-a8979896.html |archive-date=29 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2019, Williamson won a High Court challenge to the legality of the review of the disciplinary decision but similar charges had been made on 3 September 2019, involving a further suspension, and the High Court ruled the Labour Party's disciplinary procedure with regard to these charges should run its course. In November that year, [[National Executive Committee (UK Labour Party)|Labour's National Executive Committee]] blocked Williamson from standing as a Labour candidate in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Labour blocks Corbyn loyalist from standing at general election over antisemitism claims |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-williamson-general-election-labour-roger-godsiff-stephen-hepburn-corbyn-a9187711.html |accessdate=6 November 2019 |work=The Independent |date=6 November 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106162054/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-williamson-general-election-labour-roger-godsiff-stephen-hepburn-corbyn-a9187711.html |archive-date=6 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He resigned from the Labour Party and stood as an Independent, losing the seat and his deposit.<ref name=standard-20191107>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/general-election-news-latest-chris-williamson-to-stand-as-independent-mp-after-labour-bans-him-from-a4280721.html |title=Chris Williamson to stand as independent MP in general election after Labour bans him from party |last=Speare-Cole |first=Rebecca |newspaper=Evening Standard |location=London |date=7 November 2019 |accessdate=7 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107054151/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/general-election-news-latest-chris-williamson-to-stand-as-independent-mp-after-labour-bans-him-from-a4280721.html |archive-date=7 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in [[Derby]], Williamson attended the St. John Fisher Primary School in [[Alvaston]], [[Castle Donington]] High School and St. Thomas More High School in [[Allenton, Derbyshire|Allenton]], followed by Leicester Polytechnic (now [[De Montfort University]]), where he obtained a [[Qualifications for professional social work|professional social work qualification]] (a CQSW) in 1985.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} After working as a craft apprentice for a year from 1972, Williamson then worked as a [[bricklayer]] for six years. He was a [[social worker]] in Derby from 1983 to 1986 before working as a welfare rights officer.\n\nWilliamson joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in 1976. He became a councillor on Derby City Council in 1991. Appointed Chair of Housing, he supported [[private finance initiative]] (PFI) projects.<ref name=\"Casalicchio\">{{cite news|last=Casalicchio|first=Emilio|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/jeremy-corbyn/house/house-magazine/94700/chris-williamson-|title=Chris Williamson: 'It's like all my Christmases have come together \u2013 the sort of Labour party I dreamed about'|work=Politics Home|agency=[[The House (magazine)|The House]]|date=26 April 2018|accessdate=28 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427053735/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/jeremy-corbyn/house/house-magazine/94700/chris-williamson-|archivedate=27 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Interviewed in 2018, he termed his approach then as \"innovative pragmatism\", seeking to \"be as radical as we possibly could within the confines that we were subjected to by central government\", arguing that \"It was a bullshit scheme\u2014I wouldn't have chosen it at all. It didn't give value for money. But what were we supposed to do as a local authority? We either [do it or] say we are not going to build these schools or we are not going to refurbish these unfit dwellings.\"<ref name=\"Casalicchio\"/>\n\nHe became leader of the Labour Group on [[Derby City Council]], serving as leader of Derby City Council on two separate occasions. While council leader, Williamson presided over a coalition with the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] for two years after Labour lost its majority in 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theredroar.com/2018/01/chris-williamsons-tory-love-in-backbencher-formed-alliance-with-conservatives-as-labour-leader-of-derby-council/|title=Chris Williamson's Tory love-in: backbencher formed alliance with Conservatives as Labour leader of Derby council|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=6 July 2019|work=Red Roar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706043003/https://www.theredroar.com/2018/01/chris-williamsons-tory-love-in-backbencher-formed-alliance-with-conservatives-as-labour-leader-of-derby-council/|archive-date=6 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was instrumental in setting up [[Holocaust Memorial Day]] events in the city and rescinded the obsolete medieval [[proscription]] barring Jews from living in Derby.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/01/chris-williamson-labour-mp-antisemitism-row|title=Chris Williamson: 'no place' in Labour for MP embroiled in antisemitism row|last=Parveen|first=Nazia|date=1 July 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113234714/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/01/chris-williamson-labour-mp-antisemitism-row|archive-date=13 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe is vice chair of the Local Government Anti Poverty Forum.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Derby+North/Chris+Williamson |title=Chris Williamson \u2013 Parliamentary candidates |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=19 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306092325/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Derby%2BNorth/Chris%2BWilliamson |archivedate=6 March 2012  }}</ref>\n\nHe has been [[Teetotalism|teetotal]] and a [[veganism|vegan]] since the 1970s, and is a member of the [[League Against Cruel Sports]].<ref name=\"full transcript column 898\">Kerry McCarthy MP [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm111101/debtext/111101-0004.htm full transcript (column 898)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901202753/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm111101/debtext/111101-0004.htm |date=1 September 2017 }}, World Vegan Day, Adjournment Debate, House of Commons, 1 November 2011.</ref><ref name=\"Casalicchio\"/><ref name=\"full transcript column 898\"/>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n===First term (2010\u201315)===\nIn the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], Williamson was elected for Derby North with a majority of 613 over the Conservative candidate.\n\nWilliamson supported [[Ed Miliband]] in the [[2010 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2010 Labour leadership election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.labour.org.uk/leadership-mps-and-meps|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101171158/http://www2.labour.org.uk/leadership-mps-and-meps|archivedate=1 January 2011|title=Leadership \u2013 MPs and MEPs \u2013 The Labour Party|date=1 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, Williamson became Shadow Fire and Emergency Services Minister within the Shadow Communities and Local Government team after just four months as an MP but, after a reshuffle of the [[Shadow Cabinet of Ed Miliband|shadow cabinet]] in 2013, was replaced by [[Lyn Brown (politician)|Lyn Brown]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.leftfutures.org/2013/10/ed-miliband-shifts-leftwards-at-conference-but-rightwards-in-the-plp/|title=Ed Miliband shifts Leftwards at conference but Rightwards in the PLP|date=9 October 2013|work=Left Futures|accessdate=10 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803074636/http://www.leftfutures.org/2013/10/ed-miliband-shifts-leftwards-at-conference-but-rightwards-in-the-plp/|archivedate=3 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He served as a member of the [[Housing, Communities and Local Government Committee|Communities and Local Government Committee]] between July and November 2010 and from November 2013 to March 2015.<ref name=\"UK Parliament\"/>\n\nIn 2014, Williamson voted to support the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|Cameron coalition's]] [[2011 military intervention in Libya]] and the [[Operation Shader|British action against ISIS in Iraq]]. In April 2018, Williamson said that, while he was initially undetermined, he was \"naive\" to support the votes. He abstained on the [[Immigration Act 2014|Immigration Bill in 2014]], following an instruction from Labour [[Whip (politics)|whips]], saying later: \"I have to say\u2014if I'm being honest\u2014I didn't study it enough or fully appreciate the implications.\"<ref name=\"Casalicchio\"/>\n\nWilliamson was one of 16 signatories of an open letter to Ed Miliband in January 2015 calling on the party to oppose further austerity, take rail franchises back into public ownership and strengthen collective bargaining arrangements.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eaton|first1=George|title=The Labour left demand a change of direction \u2013 why their intervention matters|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/01/labour-left-demand-change-direction-why-their-intervention-matters|accessdate=5 April 2015|work=New Statesman|date=26 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412090810/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/01/labour-left-demand-change-direction-why-their-intervention-matters|archivedate=12 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Williamson lost the Derby North seat to [[Amanda Solloway]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] by 41 votes. Labour Leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] described Williamson in early 2016 as a \"very great friend\", saying that his defeat at the 2015 general election was \"the worst result of that night\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/corbyn-chris-williamson-losing-derby-north-worst/story-28718402-detail/story.html|title=Corbyn: Chris Williamson losing Derby North was 'the worst result of that night'|work=[[Derby Telegraph]]|date=11 February 2016|accessdate=12 June 2017}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Second term (2017\u20132019)===\nDuring the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] campaign, he was described by the ''[[New Statesman]]'' as the \"most pro-Jeremy Corbyn candidate in England's most marginal constituency\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Chakelian|first=Anoosh|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/life-labour-s-most-pro-jeremy-corbyn-candidate-england-s-most-marginal|title=Life as Labour's most pro-Jeremy Corbyn candidate in England's most marginal constituency|work=[[New Statesman]]|date=10 May 2017|accessdate=12 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609133732/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/life-labour-s-most-pro-jeremy-corbyn-candidate-england-s-most-marginal|archivedate=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson said that his candidacy would be a \"test case for Corbynism\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/jeremy-corbyn-must-absolutely-remain-labour-leader-should-he-lose-the-election-says-ally-chris-williamson_uk_59089d43e4b0bb2d0871f129 |title=Corbyn Must 'Absolutely' Remain Labour Leader Even If He Loses The Election, Says Ally|work=[[HuffPost UK]]|date=3 May 2017|accessdate=12 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613091554/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/jeremy-corbyn-must-absolutely-remain-labour-leader-should-he-lose-the-election-says-ally-chris-williamson_uk_59089d43e4b0bb2d0871f129 |archivedate=13 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and Corbyn campaigned for him.<ref name=\"Casalicchio\"/> Williamson regained his former seat from Amanda Solloway of the Conservatives with a majority of 2,015 votes.\n\nOn 3 July 2017, Williamson was appointed Shadow Fire and Emergency Services Minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsocialist.org.uk/reshuffle-2-the-ma/|title=Reshuffle 2: The Maintenance of the Malcontents|date=8 July 2017|work=New Socialist.|accessdate=10 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031024616/https://newsocialist.org.uk/reshuffle-2-the-ma/|archivedate=31 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://press.labour.org.uk/post/162548382729/jeremy-corbyn-appoints-20-mps-to-labours-front|title=Jeremy Corbyn appoints 20 MPs to Labour's front bench|website=Labour Press|accessdate=10 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706130458/http://press.labour.org.uk/post/162548382729/jeremy-corbyn-appoints-20-mps-to-labours-front|archivedate=6 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson resigned this role on 11 January 2018; a day earlier he had suggested that [[Council Tax|council tax]] on the highest-value homes should be doubled. The comment, which was not party policy and outside his remit, was made without the knowledge of [[Andrew Gwynne]], the shadow secretary of state for communities and local government. When the issue was raised, Williamson, rather than agree to confine his public statements to his own policy area, resigned. He said: \"I've taken this decision to bring me closer to the membership of our party and to allow me to work on a broader range of issues, from environmental policy to animal rights and local government.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Heather|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/11/chris-williamson-quits-labour-frontbench-after-double-council-tax-call|title=Chris Williamson quits Labour frontbench after 'double council tax' call|work=The Guardian|date=11 January 2018|accessdate=11 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111153949/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/11/chris-williamson-quits-labour-frontbench-after-double-council-tax-call|archivedate=11 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Williamson voiced doubts that the Syrian government was responsible for the [[Douma chemical attack|gas attack on Douma]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Harrison |first=Tristia |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/world/middle-east/2018/08/labour-can-be-jo-cox-s-party-or-chris-williamson-s-it-cannot-be-both |title=Labour can be Jo Cox's party or Chris Williamson's \u2013 it cannot be both |work=Newstatesman.com |date=21 August 2018 |accessdate=20 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126095758/https://www.newstatesman.com/world/middle-east/2018/08/labour-can-be-jo-cox-s-party-or-chris-williamson-s-it-cannot-be-both |archivedate=26 November 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In August 2018, he said it was a \"privilege\" to hear a talk by a pro-[[Bashar al-Assad|Assad]] [[blog]]ger, Vanessa Beeley.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/labour-mp-chris-williamson-vanessa-beeley_uk_5b7adee4e4b018b93e963784 |title=Labour's Chris Williamson Praises Vanessa Beeley, Blogger Who Called Jo Cox A 'Warmongering Blairite' |work=Huffingtonpost.co.uk |date=20 August 2018 |accessdate=16 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929041331/https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/labour-mp-chris-williamson-vanessa-beeley_uk_5b7adee4e4b018b93e963784 |archivedate=29 September 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/world/middle-east/2018/08/labour-can-be-jo-cox-s-party-or-chris-williamson-s-it-cannot-be-both|title=Labour can be Jo Cox's party or Chris Williamson's \u2013 it cannot be both|work=Newstatesman.com|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=20 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126095758/https://www.newstatesman.com/world/middle-east/2018/08/labour-can-be-jo-cox-s-party-or-chris-williamson-s-it-cannot-be-both|archivedate=26 November 2018|url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Friedman |first=Gabe |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/uk-labour-mp-slammed-for-praising-anti-semitic-pro-assad-conspiracist/ |title=UK Labour MP slammed for praising anti-Semitic pro-Assad conspiracist |work=The Times of Israel |date=22 August 2018 |accessdate=20 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221113512/https://www.timesofisrael.com/uk-labour-mp-slammed-for-praising-anti-semitic-pro-assad-conspiracist/ |archivedate=21 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nHe says that, with Corbyn as leader, the party has \"a common-sense socialist\" who does not place MPs in the situation of risking being in conflict with the party whips. Williamson said he is \"not one for undermining the leadership publicly\", explaining the difference between his history in the [[Division of the assembly|division lobbies]] and Corbyn's earlier frequent parliamentary vote rebellions as Corbyn expressing the opinions of party members.<ref name=\"Casalicchio\"/>\n\nWilliamson supports a mandatory reselection process for all Labour MPs and, in 2018, toured the country to promote this change from the existing procedure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/09/labour-mp-chris-williamson-democracy-roadshow-mandatory-reselection|title=Labour MP Chris Williamson launches 'democracy' roadshow|last=Crerar|first=Pippa|date=9 July 2018|accessdate=6 August 2019|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806073650/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/09/labour-mp-chris-williamson-democracy-roadshow-mandatory-reselection|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Views on handling of antisemitism allegations===\nIn 2017, Williamson said that attacks on Corbyn's handling of alleged [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism within the Labour Party]] were \"proxy wars and bullshit\" and that \"I'm not saying it never ever happens but it is a really dirty, lowdown trick, particularly the antisemitism smears. Many people in the Jewish community are appalled by what they see as the weaponisation of antisemitism for political ends.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/aug/28/make-labour-leadership-rules-more-democratic-urges-shadow-minister|title=MPs should have no say over who leads Labour, argues shadow minister|work=The Guardian|date=28 August 2017|accessdate=2 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002215225/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/aug/28/make-labour-leadership-rules-more-democratic-urges-shadow-minister|archivedate=2 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Marie van der Zyl]], the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews|Board of Deputies]] vice-president, said that Williamson should \"show solidarity with those suffering racism within his own party rather than blaming the victims\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-chris-williamson-dismisses-jew-hate-allegations-1.443446|title=Anger as 'deplorable' Labour MP dismisses antisemitism allegations as 'smears'|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=29 August 2017|accessdate=2 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002215617/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-chris-williamson-dismisses-jew-hate-allegations-1.443446|archivedate=2 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson described antisemitism as being \"utterly repugnant and a scourge on society, which is why I stand in absolute solidarity with anyone who is subjected to antisemitic abuse\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-chris-williamson-dismisses-jew-hate-allegations-1.443446|title=Anger as 'deplorable' Labour MP dismisses antisemitism allegations as 'smears'|work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=29 August 2017|accessdate=2 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002215617/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-chris-williamson-dismisses-jew-hate-allegations-1.443446|archivedate=2 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He added that his critics' \"accusations of anti-Semitism (against him) were positively sinister\" and \"highly offensive and hurtful\" in suggesting \"that I was an anti-Semite myself, yet I have fought racism all my adult life\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Williamson|first=Chris|url=http://www.tribunemagazine.org/2017/09/agenda-setting-8/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170924121639/http://www.tribunemagazine.org/2017/09/agenda-setting-8/|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 September 2017|title=Agenda setting|work=Tribune|date=9 September 2017|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Williamson referenced [[Ken Livingstone]]: \"We've got these ridiculous suspensions and expulsions from the party\" made \"in the most grotesque and unfair way\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/chris-williamson-condemned-by-board-of-deputies-after-calling-for-ken-livingstone-to-be-reinstated-by-labour-party-1.460999|title=Board of Deputies condemns Labour MP's comments backing Ken Livingstone|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=19 March 2018|accessdate=18 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419053413/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/chris-williamson-condemned-by-board-of-deputies-after-calling-for-ken-livingstone-to-be-reinstated-by-labour-party-1.460999|archivedate=19 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Supporting [[Len McCluskey]], who had accused some Labour MPs of using the issue of antisemitism in campaigning against Corbyn, he described some of his colleagues as \"malcontents\" who were \"completely out of step with party members\" and voters,<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Lucy|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sir-keir-starmer-hits-back-at-union-leader-len-mccluskey-in-antisemitism-row-7gg0chqdc|title=Sir Keir Starmer hits back at Union leader Len McCluskey in antisemitism row|work=The Times|date=26 April 2018|accessdate=28 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427183755/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sir-keir-starmer-hits-back-at-union-leader-len-mccluskey-in-antisemitism-row-7gg0chqdc|archivedate=27 April 2018|url-status=live }}{{subscription required}}</ref> but that deselection of MPs was \"a matter for Labour Party members in each constituency and not a matter for me or indeed Len\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Matt|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/94697/chris-williamson-blasts-malcontent-labour-mps-amid|title=Chris Williamson blasts 'malcontent' Labour MPs amid bitter anti-Semitism row|work=Politics Home|date=26 April 2018|accessdate=28 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428183909/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/94697/chris-williamson-blasts-malcontent-labour-mps-amid|archivedate=28 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, during a visit to Derbyshire, [[Jeremy Corbyn]] defended Williamson, saying that \"Chris Williamson is a very good, very effective Labour MP. He's a very strong anti-racist campaigner. He is not anti-semitic in any way.\"<ref>\"Jeremy Corbyn defends ally Chris Williamson against anti-semitism claims\" 1 February 2019, https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/101537/jeremy-corbyn-defends-ally-chris-williamson {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626172218/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/101537/jeremy-corbyn-defends-ally-chris-williamson |date=26 June 2019 }}</ref>\n\n====Formal investigation and suspension====\nIn February 2019, Williamson was criticised for booking a room in the [[Houses of Parliament]] for a screening of ''[[Witch Hunt (2019 film)|Witch Hunt]]'', a film about suspended party member [[Jackie Walker (activist)|Jackie Walker]], to be hosted by [[Jewish Voice for Labour]].<ref name=\"set for clash\">{{cite news|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-mp-chris-williamson-party-too-apologetic-over-antisemitism-complaints|title=Corbyn set for clash with Watson over MP's antisemitism remarks|last=Mason|first=Rowena|work=The Guardian|date=27 February 2019|accessdate=28 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228012452/https://amp.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-mp-chris-williamson-party-too-apologetic-over-antisemitism-complaints|archivedate=28 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref> At the same time, a video was published by ''[[The Yorkshire Post]]'' of him telling a [[Momentum]] meeting in [[Sheffield]] that the party was being \"demonised as a racist, bigoted party\", partly because, in response to criticism, the party had \"given too much ground (and) been too apologetic\", going on to say \"We've done more to address the scourge of anti-Semitism than any other political party.\"<ref name=\"Bates 2019\">{{cite web | last=Bates | first=Elizabeth | title=Chris Williamson: Labour has been too apologetic about anti-Semitism | website=Yorkshire Post | date=26 February 2019 | url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/chris-williamson-labour-has-been-too-apologetic-about-anti-semitism-1-9618191 | accessdate=6 March 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303073859/https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/chris-williamson-labour-has-been-too-apologetic-about-anti-semitism-1-9618191 | archivedate=3 March 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=suspended/> [[Deputy Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Labour Deputy Leader]] [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] said that Williamson should have the Labour whip removed for his comments and a group of 38 Labour MPs had written to the party's General Secretary to ask that he be suspended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/mp-chris-williamson-suspended-from-labour-party-amid-antisemitism-storm-a4078386.html|title=Labour MP suspended over anti-Semitism remarks|date=27 February 2019|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=27 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228010127/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/mp-chris-williamson-suspended-from-labour-party-amid-antisemitism-storm-a4078386.html|archivedate=28 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref> There was also pressure from London mayor [[Sadiq Khan]], [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]] leader Tim Roache, anti-racism charity [[HOPE not hate]], the [[Jewish Labour Movement]] and the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2019/02/chris-williamson-suspended-from-the-labour-party/|title=Chris Williamson suspended from the Labour Party|date=27 February 2019|website=[[LabourList]]|accessdate=27 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228010216/https://labourlist.org/2019/02/chris-williamson-suspended-from-the-labour-party/|archivedate=28 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"splits exposed\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-suspends-chris-williamson-over-antisemitism-remarks|title=Labour splits exposed as MP is suspended over antisemitism remarks|work=[[The Guardian]]|first1=Heather|last1=Stewart|first2=Peter|last2=Walker|date=27 February 2019|accessdate=27 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227174126/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-suspends-chris-williamson-over-antisemitism-remarks|archivedate=27 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/mp-chris-williamson-accused-trolling-jewish-community-by-hosting-jackie-walker-film-parliament-1.480691|title=MP Chris Williamson accused of 'trolling Jewish community' by hosting Jackie Walker film in Parliament|last=Doherty|first=Rosa|date=26 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227060330/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/mp-chris-williamson-accused-trolling-jewish-community-by-hosting-jackie-walker-film-parliament-1.480691|archivedate=27 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref> Jewish Voice for Labour defended Williamson, as did the \"[[Labour Against the Witchhunt]]\" pressure group and the Sheffield Hallam constituency branch of the Labour Party who voted 40 to 0 in favour of a motion stating Williamson's comments had been taken out of context.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/01/local-labour-parties-drawn-into-row-over-antisemitism-claims |title=Local Labour parties drawn into row over antisemitism claims |accessdate=4 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304042847/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/01/local-labour-parties-drawn-into-row-over-antisemitism-claims |archivedate=4 March 2019 |url-status=live |newspaper=The Guardian |date=March 2019 |last1=Sabbagh |first1=Dan }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/labour-suspension-of-chris-williamson-branded-madness|title=Labour suspension of Chris Williamson branded 'madness'|first1=Lamiat|last1=Sabin|date=27 February 2019|website=Morning Star|accessdate=3 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306044446/https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/labour-suspension-of-chris-williamson-branded-madness|archivedate=6 March 2019|url-status=live }}</ref> Williamson apologised for his comments saying: \"I deeply regret, and apologise for, my recent choice of words when speaking about how the Labour Party has responded to the ongoing fight against antisemitism inside of our party. I was trying to stress how much the party has done to tackle anti-Semitism\".<ref name=\"to be investigated\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47385108|title=MP to be investigated in anti-Semitism row|date=27 February 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=27 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228133322/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47385108|archivedate=28 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-mp-chris-williamson-party-too-apologetic-over-antisemitism-complaints |title=Corbyn set for clash with Watson over MP's antisemitism remarks |work=[[The Guardian]] |first1=Rowena |last1=Mason |first2=Peter |last2=Walker |first3=Jessica |last3=Elgot |date=27 February 2019 |accessdate=27 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227103438/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-mp-chris-williamson-party-too-apologetic-over-antisemitism-complaints |archivedate=27 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 27 February 2019, he was put under formal notice of investigation,<ref name=\"to be investigated\"/><ref name=\"set for clash\"/> and later that day suspended from the party.<ref name=suspended/><ref name=\"splits exposed\"/>\n\n====Formal warning, resuspension and further charges====\nLabour readmitted Williamson on 26 June 2019 after a [[National Executive Committee]] panel considered his case and issued him with a formal warning. A party source said: \"An NEC panel, advised by an independent barrister, found Chris Williamson had breached the party's rules and gave him a formal sanction. He could face further, more severe, action if he repeats any similar comments or behaviour.\"<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">BBC. \"Labour anti-Semitism row: Chris Williamson allowed back into party\". 26 July 2019, https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48778129 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626171709/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48778129 |date=26 June 2019 }}</ref> It was suggested that the decision for readmission was made in order to enable Williamson to enter the Labour MP reselection process then underway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/26/chris-williamson-back-in-labour-party-after-antisemitism-remarks|title=Chris Williamson back in Labour party after antisemitism remarks|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626185149/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/26/chris-williamson-back-in-labour-party-after-antisemitism-remarks|archive-date=26 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The decision to readmit Williamson was criticised by Labour parliamentarians and parliamentary staff<ref name=LAW>'''Statement on Chris Williamson''', 27 June 2019: \nWe cannot overstate the depth and breadth of hurt and anger felt about the readmission of Chris Williamson into the Labour Party and the questions that arise about the fairness of the process.<br>\nThe offficer recommendation - that Mr. Williamson should be referred to the National Constitutional Committee for action - was ignored by the members of the NEC panel. That the composition of that panel was changed at short notice seems highly irregular.<br>Justice needs to be seen to be done and this process has not done that.<br>Given that the Labour Party is being investigated by the EHRC over allegations of institutional antisemitism this case is particularly important.<br>It is clear to us that the Labour Party's disciplinary process remains mired by the appearance of political interference. This must stop. We need a truly independent process.<br>We call on Jeremy Corbyn to show leadership by asking for this inappropriate, offensive and reputationally damaging decision to be overturned and reviewed.<br>Ultimately, it is for Jeremy Corbyn to decide whether Chris Willamson retains the Labour whip. He must remove it immediately if we are to stand any hope of persuading anyone that the Labour Party is taking antisemitism seriously.<br>'''Signed'''\n{|\n|-\n|\n[[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]<br>[[Molly Lynch]]<br>[[Stella Creasy]]<br>[[Anna Turley]]<br>[[Rosie Duffield]]<br>[[Louise Ellman]]<br>[[Ruth Smeeth]]<br>[[Jenny Chapman]]<br>[[Roberta Blackman-Woods]]<br>[[Stephen Doughty]]<br>[[Karin Smyth]]<br>[[Baroness Thornton]]<br>[[Iain McNicol|Lord McNicol]]<br>[[Baroness Morgan of Huyton]]<br>[[Lord Turnberg]]<br>[[Gloria De Piero]]<br>[[Baroness Royall of Blaisdon]]<br>[[Yvette Cooper]]<br>[[Baroness Massey of Darwen]]<br>[[Baroness Kingsmill]]<br>[[Lord Soley]]<br>[[Madeleine Moon]]\n|\n[[Kate Green]]<br>[[Ruth Cadbury]]<br>[[Owen Smith]]<br>[[Seema Malhotra]]<br>[[Liz Kendall]]<br>[[Chris Matheson (politician)|Chris Matheson]]<br>[[Margaret Hodge]]<br>[[Stephen Kinnock]]<br>[[Jeff Smith (British politician)|Jeff Smith]]<br>[[Chris Bryant]]<br>[[Wes Streeting]]<br>[[Julie Elliott]]<br>[[Lord Levy]]<br>[[Lord Knight of Weymouth]]<br>[[Lord Harris of Haringey]]<br>[[Ali McGovern]]<br>[[James Frith]]<br>[[Lucy Powell]]<br>[[Bridget Phillipson]]<br>[[Pat McFadden]]<br>[[Baroness McIntosh of Hudnall]]<br>[[Lord Triesman]]<br>[[Lord Dubs]]<br>[[Ian Murray (Scottish politician)|Ian Murray]]\n|\n[[Darren Jones (politician)|Darren Jones]]<br>[[Alex Sobel]]<br>[[Karen Buck]]<br>[[Neil Coyle]]<br>[[Lord Mandelson]]<br>[[Anna McMorrin]]<br>[[Chi Onwurah]]<br>[[Baroness Taylor of Bolton]]<br>[[Lord Willie Bach]]<br>[[Susan Elan Jones]]<br>[[Ged Killen]]<br>[[Baroness Ramsay of Cartvale]]<br>[[Lord Livermore]]<br>[[Kevin Barron]]<br>[[Dan Jarvis]]<br>[[Jess Phillips]]<br>[[Martin Whitfield]]<br>[[Rachel Reeves]]<br>[[Peter Kyle]]<br>[[Baroness Armstrong of Hill Top]]<br>[[Lord Young of Norwood Green]]<br>[[Ellie Reeves]]\n|\n[[Baroness Maggie Jones]]<br>[[Rushanara Ali]]<br>[[Debbie Abrahams]]<br>[[Daniel Zeichner]]<br>[[Lilian Greenwood]]<br>[[Graham Jones (politician)|Graham Jones]]<br>[[Toby Perkins]]<br>[[George Robertson, Baron Robertson of Port Ellen|Lord George Robertson]]<br>[[Baroness Mary Goudie]]<br>[[Barry Sheerman]]<br>[[Tonia Antoniazzi]]<br>[[Ian Lucas]]<br>[[Lord George Foulkes]]<br>[[Lord Wood of Anfield]]<br>[[Cat McKinnell]]<br>[[Ben Bradshaw]]<br>[[Lord Haskell]]<br>[[Lisa Nandy]]<br>[[Gareth Thomas (English politician)|Gareth Thomas]]<br>[[Clive Brooke, Baron Brooke of Alverthorpe|Lord Brooke]]<br>[[Sharon Hodgson]]<br>[[Lord Kennedy of Southwark]]\n\n|}\n''from'' http://www.labouragainstthewitchhunt.org/, ''also see'' https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/tom-watson-and-labour-mps-demand-jeremy-corbyn-overturn-chris-williamson-decision_uk_5d14c696e4b0d0a2c0ad0c03</ref> and by Jewish communal bodies.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>Mathilde Frot. \"Labour MP Chris Williamson let back in with \u2018formal warning\u2019. Jewish News. 26 June 2019.https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/labour-mp-chris-williamson-let-back-in-with-formal-warning-after-suspension</ref> Two days later, he was resuspended after the Labour Party decided to review the decision.<ref name=\"Kentish\"/>\n\nAdditional allegations of misconduct resulting in a separate suspension was imposed on 3 September. Williamson's barrister, who called these allegations \"similar in nature\" to the first set, said \"It appears from the timing ... that the purpose of the decision to raise these allegations now, and to impose a second suspension on the claimant, is to seek to ensure that he will remain suspended even if this claim is successful and that he will therefore remain disqualified from selection in the forthcoming general election.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/derby-north-mp-chris-williamsons-3314988|title=Derby North MP Chris Williamson's legal fight is heard in the High Court|last=Hawley|first=Zena|date=13 September 2019|accessdate=10 October 2019|work=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927020550/https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/derby-north-mp-chris-williamsons-3314988|archive-date=27 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Reaction to resuspension====\nIn July 2019, the [[Labour Party in Northern Ireland]] (LPNI) released a statement opposing the resuspension of Williamson on the grounds that it was \"arbitrary and unreasonable\" and \"the Labour Party does not have any form of particular problem with anti-semitism\".<ref name=\"LPNIstat\">{{cite web|title=Statement on Chris Williamson MP, and on the allegation that the Labour Party is anti-semitic.|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1yXdpUPy67TmkfkURHkJicaIKE02jeS3j/view|publisher=[[Labour Party in Northern Ireland]]|accessdate=5 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705224721/https://drive.google.com/file/d/1yXdpUPy67TmkfkURHkJicaIKE02jeS3j/view|archive-date=5 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the same month, in a survey of LabourList readers with over 10,000 responses, over two thirds of those expressing a view supported Williamson's readmission.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://labourlist.org/2019/07/readmit-williamson-and-adopt-an-independent-complaints-process-say-labourlist-readers/|title=Readmit Williamson and adopt an independent complaints process, say LabourList readers|last=Rodgers|first=Sienna|date=2 July 2019|accessdate=5 July 2019|work=Labour List|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703140455/https://labourlist.org/2019/07/readmit-williamson-and-adopt-an-independent-complaints-process-say-labourlist-readers/|archive-date=3 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The leading Jewish scholar and activist [[Noam Chomsky]] stated that there was \"nothing even remotely antisemitic\" in Williamson's comments at Sheffield, and remarked that the way accusations were being used in cases such as Williamson was \"not only a disgrace, but also \u2013 to put it simply \u2013 an insult to the memory of the victims of the Holocaust.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cowles |first1=Ben |title=Chomsky speaks out against the attacks on Chris Williamson |url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/chomsky-speaks-out-against-the-attacks-on-chris-williamson |accessdate=25 September 2019 |work=Morning Star |publisher=The People\u2019s Press Society |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716002915/https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/chomsky-speaks-out-against-the-attacks-on-chris-williamson |url-status=live |archive-date=16 July 2019 |date=5 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"JVL Suspending Williamson\">{{cite web |title=Suspending Chris Williamson \u2013 The Fury And The Fakery |url=https://www.jewishvoiceforlabour.org.uk/article/suspending-chris-williamson-the-fury-and-the-fakery/ |publisher=Jewish Voice for Labour |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925150229/https://www.jewishvoiceforlabour.org.uk/article/suspending-chris-williamson-the-fury-and-the-fakery/ |archive-date=25 September 2019 |url-status=live |date=5 July 2019 |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thecanary.co/trending/2019/07/05/noam-chomsky-backs-chris-williamson-and-calls-the-antisemitism-smear-campaign-an-insult-to-the-memory-of-holocaust-victims/|title=Noam Chomsky backs Chris Williamson, and calls the antisemitism smear campaign 'an insult to the memory' of Holocaust victims|last=Mendoza|first=Kerry-anne|date=5 July 2019|accessdate=6 July 2019|work=The Canary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706053103/https://www.thecanary.co/trending/2019/07/05/noam-chomsky-backs-chris-williamson-and-calls-the-antisemitism-smear-campaign-an-insult-to-the-memory-of-holocaust-victims/|archive-date=6 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Campaign for Chris Williamson, established to support him, includes Israeli and British academics, film directors [[Mike Leigh]] and [[Ken Loach]], musicians [[Brian Eno]] and [[Roger Waters]], journalist [[John Pilger]], actor [[Miriam Margolyes]] and comedian [[Alexei Sayle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/derby-north-mp-chris-williamsons-3314988|title=Derby North MP Chris Williamson's legal fight is heard in the High Court|last=Hawley|first=Zena|date=13 September 2019|accessdate=16 September 2019|work=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918030434/https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/derby-north-mp-chris-williamsons-3314988|archive-date=18 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, more than one hundred signatories, describing themselves as \"all Jews\", including Noam Chomsky<ref name=\"Board complains\"/> signed a letter of support for Williamson.<ref>[https://archive.today/20190708173939/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2019/jul/08/jewish-support-for-chris-williamson 'Jewish support for Chris Williamson'], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 8 July 2019. Quote: \"We the undersigned, all Jews, are writing in support of Chris Williamson and to register our dismay at the recent letter organised by Tom Watson, and signed by parliamentary Labour party and House of Lords members, calling for his suspension\"</ref> The letter was later removed from the Guardian website, after questions were raised about the listed affiliation of some individuals on the list of signatories. [[Hope not Hate]] said that the person who used the organisation's name had not been authorised to do so and the Board of Deputies of British Jews said that two of the signatories had promoted 9/11 conspiracy theories.<ref name=\"York 2019\">{{cite web | author= Chris York | title= 'Misleading And Inaccurate' Letter Supporting MP Chris Williamson Removed By The Guardian | website=HuffPost  | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/chris-williamson-guardian-letter_uk_5d249fefe4b07e698c412ab5 | access-date=2019-07-31| date= 9 July 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Board complains\">{{cite web |author=Daniel Sugarman| title= Board of Deputies complains to Guardian about letter from 'prominent' Jews supporting Chris Williamson | website=Jewish Chronicle | url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/board-of-deputies-complains-to-guardian-about-letter-from-prominent-jews-supporting-chris-williams-1.4862605 | date= July 9, 2019 | access-date=2019-07-31}}{{dead link |date=August 2019}}</ref>\n\nPolitical opponents have sought to prevent him speaking, such as in Hull<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/hull-east-yorkshire-news/chris-williamson-mp-suspended-hull-3133754|title=Row erupts as suspended MP Chris Williamson in Hull to speak to trades union activists|last=Young|first=Angus|date=25 July 2019|accessdate=6 August 2019|work=Hull Live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806172416/https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/hull-east-yorkshire-news/chris-williamson-mp-suspended-hull-3133754|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and Hebden Bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/uk/yorkshire-town-hall-meeting-featuring-mp-chris-williamson-cancelled-over-fears-it-might-affect-wedding-at-the-same-venue-1-9912110|title=Yorkshire town hall meeting featuring MP Chris Williamson cancelled over fears it might affect wedding at the same venue|last=Greenwood|first=John|date=2 August 2019|accessdate=6 August 2019|work=Yorkshire Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802124112/https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/uk/yorkshire-town-hall-meeting-featuring-mp-chris-williamson-cancelled-over-fears-it-might-affect-wedding-at-the-same-venue-1-9912110|archive-date=2 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Similarly, an event due to be hosted by Williamson at the Brighthelm Centre in [[Brighton]] was cancelled after local MP [[Peter Kyle]] contacted the venue to express his concerns over Williamson's alleged antisemitism. A second venue withdrew when staff were threatened in person and abused in phone calls and on their personal social media accounts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/brighton-holiday-inn-cancels-chris-williamson-event-after-complaints-1.487218|title=Brighton Holiday Inn cancels event with suspended Labour MP Chris Williamson after complaints|last=Harpin|first=Lee|date=7 August 2019|accessdate=7 August 2019|work=Jewish Chronicle|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807112525/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/brighton-holiday-inn-cancels-chris-williamson-event-after-complaints-1.487218|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Board of Deputies of British Jews and the [[Jewish Leadership Council]] called a protest against Chris Williamson speaking, with a third venue then cancelling the booking after threats of violence were received.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/news-features/after-dropping-chris-williamson-event-quakers-take-time-to-reflect-on-hosting-speakers-accused-of-1.487569|title=After dropping Chris Williamson event, Quakers 'take time to reflect' on hosting speakers accused of antisemitism|last=Weich|first=Ben|date=16 August 2019|accessdate=18 August 2019|work=Jewish Chronicle|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818181721/https://www.thejc.com/news/news-features/after-dropping-chris-williamson-event-quakers-take-time-to-reflect-on-hosting-speakers-accused-of-1.487569|archive-date=18 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\nSupporters of the MP talked of the importance of protecting freedom of speech.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/chris-williamson-event-brighton-labour-antisemitism-board-of-deputies-jlc-protest-1.487301|title=Quakers cancel Chris Williamson Brighton event as Jewish groups planned protest|last=Weich|first=|date=8 August 2019|accessdate=8 August 2019|work=Jewish Chronicle|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808154356/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/chris-williamson-event-brighton-labour-antisemitism-board-of-deputies-jlc-protest-1.487301|archive-date=8 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In response, Williamson said: \"The grotesque slurs that Peter Kyle and others have levelled against me are truly despicable. I have a long and proud record of fighting racism, which has always involved standing up for every oppressed and marginalised group in society, including Jewish people. When Peter Kyle was still in nappies, I was an active member of the Anti-Nazi League, physically confronting foul racists and anti-Semites in the National Front.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/17792339.chris-williamson-event-cancelled-venue-mp-39-s-intervention|work=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]]|title=Chris Williamson event CANCELLED by venue after MP's intervention|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=24 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724165131/https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/17792339.chris-williamson-event-cancelled-venue-mp-39-s-intervention/|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}{{better source|date=July 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, the [[Union of Jewish Students]] and the Nottingham Jewish Society demanded that the [[University of Nottingham]] cancel a planned lecture by Williamson.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jewish-students-call-for-nottingham-university-to-cancel-chris-williamson-invitation-1.489683|title=Jewish students call for the University of Nottingham to cancel Chris Williamson invitation|last=Sugarman|first=Daniel|date=4 October 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=The Jewish Chronicle|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005141505/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jewish-students-call-for-nottingham-university-to-cancel-chris-williamson-invitation-1.489683|archive-date=5 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The demand was supported by the Jewish Labour Movement and the Board of Deputies of British Jews. The university said \u201cWhile the university is committed to supporting the well-being of all students within our community, we also have a legal duty to ensure that lawful free speech should not be prevented on campus.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-groups-furious-after-mp-chris-williamson-invited-to-deliver-lecture/|title=University of Nottingham defends invitation to Chris Williamson despite concern|last=Frot|first=Mathilde|date=4 October 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=Jewish News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191007193714/https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-groups-furious-after-mp-chris-williamson-invited-to-deliver-lecture/|archive-date=7 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\nA similar venue denial campaign was mounted by Jewish groups against [[Jackie Walker (activist)|Jackie Walker]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/389750/controversial-momentum-figure-jackie-walker-to-address-dundee-university-audience-despite-anti-semitic-allegations/|title=Controversial Momentum figure Jackie Walker to address Dundee University audience despite anti-semitic allegations|last=Sneddon|first=Ciaran|work=\u201dThe Courier\u201d|date=19 March 2017|accessdate=1 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302024514/https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/389750/controversial-momentum-figure-jackie-walker-to-address-dundee-university-audience-despite-anti-semitic-allegations/|archive-date=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/396453/jackie-walker-lecture-dundee-university-goes-ahead-despite-hate-speech-claims/|title=Jackie Walker lecture at Dundee University goes ahead despite \"hate speech\" claims|last=Vidinova|first=Nadia|work=\u201dThe Courier\u201d|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=1 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302024541/https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/396453/jackie-walker-lecture-dundee-university-goes-ahead-despite-hate-speech-claims/|archive-date=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jackie-walker-claims-board-attempting-to-shut-down-show-1.442444|title=Jackie Walker claims Board of Deputies tried to shut down her Edinburgh show|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=4 August 2017|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701031021/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jackie-walker-claims-board-attempting-to-shut-down-show-1.442444|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Williamson lodged legal papers with the High Court to challenge Labour's right to take away the whip two days after he was allowed to return as a member.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/13/chris-williamson-sues-labour-over-his-suspension-from-party|title=Chris Williamson sues Labour over his suspension from party|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|date=2019-08-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815090208/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/13/chris-williamson-sues-labour-over-his-suspension-from-party|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49340347|title=MP sues Labour over anti-Semitism suspension|date=2019-08-14|access-date=2019-08-15|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815100540/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49340347|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 October 2019, the judge ruled that reopening the case was unfair, but upheld the legality of a further suspension on 3 September on other charges.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/breaking-chris-williamson-mp-loses-20554102|title=Chris Williamson MP loses bid to be reinstated to Labour party after anti-semitism suspension|last=Tobin|first=Sam|date=10 October 2019|accessdate=10 October 2019|work=Daily Mirror|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191010155944/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/breaking-chris-williamson-mp-loses-20554102|archive-date=10 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, a Methodist church in [[Downham]] cancelled the booking for a meeting he was due to speak at after \"its understanding\" of Williamson increased, having not known anything about him at the time of the booking.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lynnnews.co.uk/news/labour-party-distances-itself-from-downham-market-chris-williamson-meeting-9085834/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=12 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012014448/https://www.lynnnews.co.uk/news/labour-party-distances-itself-from-downham-market-chris-williamson-meeting-9085834/ |archive-date=12 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2019 General Election===\nWilliamson was prevented from standing as the Labour Candidate in his Derby North constituency in the 2019 General Election as a result of his active suspension. As a result, he resigned from the Labour Party and stood instead as an independent candidate. He won only 635 votes losing his deposit and coming bottom of the poll.<ref name=\"UK Parliament\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=chris-williamson/3976 |publicwhip=Chris_Williamson |theywork=chris_williamson}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bob Laxton]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = Member of Parliament for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]]\n | years = [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Amanda Solloway]] }}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Amanda Solloway]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]]|years=[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=Amanda Solloway}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{East Midlands Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williamson, Chris}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Leicester Polytechnic]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:English social workers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for constituencies in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:People from Normanton, Derby]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Chris Williamson\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Official portrait of Chris Williamson crop 2.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government|Shadow Minister for Fire and Emergency Services]]\n| leader = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start = 3 July 2017\n| term_end = 11 January 2018\n| predecessor = Position established\n| successor = [[Karen Lee (politician)|Karen Lee]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]]\n| parliament2 = \n| majority2 = 2,015 (4.1%)\n| term_start2 = 9 June 2017\n| term_end2 = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Amanda Solloway]]\n| successor2 = Amanda Solloway\n| term_start3 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end3 = 30 March 2015\n| predecessor3 = [[Bob Laxton]]\n| successor3 = [[Amanda Solloway]]\n| birth_name = Christopher Williamson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1956|9|16}}<ref>{{cite book|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.251187|title=Who's Who 2018|publisher=A.C. Black/Bloomsbury/Oxford University Press|year=2017|chapter=Williamson, Christopher, (born 16 Sept. 1956), MP (Lab) Derby North, 2010\u201315 and since 2017}} {{page needed|date=April 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Derby]], [[Derbyshire]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| death_date1 = \n| death_place1 = \n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2019\u2013present)\n| otherparty = [[Labour Party(UK)|Labour]] (1976\u20132019)\n| spouse = {{unbulleted list|{{marriage|Lonny Wilsoncroft<br>|1997|21 May 2004|end=d}}|Maggie Amsbury<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Carr|editor-first1=Tim|editor-last2=Dale|editor-first2=Iain|editor-last3=Waller|editor-first3=Robert|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8cXADgAAQBAJ&pg=PT422&lpg=PT423|title=The Politicos Guide to the New House of Commons 2017|location=London|publisher=Politicos|year=2017|page=423|isbn=9781785902789|accessdate=9 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110061724/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8cXADgAAQBAJ&pg=PT422&lpg=PT423|archivedate=10 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n| alma_mater = [[De Montfort University|Leicester Polytechnic]]\n| website = {{url|chriswilliamsonmp.com|Official website}}\n| caption = Williamson in 2017\n}}\n'''Christopher Williamson''' (born 16 September 1956) is a British [[politician]] who was the [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]] from [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]<ref name=\"UK Parliament\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/chris-williamson/3976|title=Chris Williamson MP|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=16 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617181707/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/chris-williamson/3976|archivedate=17 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> to [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000662|website=BBC News|accessdate=13 December 2019|url-status=live|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122214906/https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/E14000662|archive-date=22 November 2019}}</ref> and from [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]] until [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/general-election-derby-north-results/story-26461496-detail/story.html|title=Chris Williamson|newspaper=[[Derby Telegraph]]|accessdate=16 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151008095123/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/General-Election-Derby-North-results/story-26461496-detail/story.html|archivedate=8 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was [[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government|Shadow Minister for Communities and Local Government]] from October 2010 to October 2013.<ref name=\"UK Parliament\"/>\n\nWilliamson was also a local councillor in [[Derby]], representing the [[Normanton, Derby|Normanton]] ward from 1991 until 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/Chris-Williamson-MP-stands-city-councillor/story-11630752-detail/story.html|title=DERBY North MP Chris Williamson has resigned from his position as councillor for Normanton after 20 years.|publisher=This is Derbyshire|date=26 March 2011|accessdate=19 October 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505085113/http://www.thisisderbyshire.co.uk/Chris-Williamson-MP-stands-city-councillor/story-11630752-detail/story.html|archivedate=5 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> serving twice as leader of [[Derby City Council]].\n\nIn February 2019, Williamson was notified of a formal investigation and later suspended from the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] for his comments about the party's response to criticism over its handling of allegations of [[antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism within the party]].<ref name=suspended>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47393626|title=Labour MP Chris Williamson suspended in anti-Semitism row|date=27 February 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=27 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227171732/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-47393626|archivedate=27 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After an investigation, Williamson was reinstated in June 2019 with a formal warning<ref>BBC. \"Labour anti-Semitism row: Chris Williamson allowed back into party\". 26 June 2019, https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48778129 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626171709/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48778129 |date=26 June 2019 }}</ref> but was resuspended two days later when the party decided to review the disciplinary decision.<ref name=\"Kentish\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-williamson-labour-whip-suspended-antisemitism-row-a8979896.html |title=Chris Williamson: Labour MP suspension descends into farce after he has whip removed again two days after being readmitted to party |last=Kentish |first=Benjamin |date=28 June 2019 |work=[[The Independent]] |access-date=29 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629075147/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-williamson-labour-whip-suspended-antisemitism-row-a8979896.html |archive-date=29 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2019, Williamson won a High Court challenge to the legality of the review of the disciplinary decision but similar charges had been made on 3 September 2019, involving a further suspension, and the High Court ruled the Labour Party's disciplinary procedure with regard to these charges should run its course. In November that year, [[National Executive Committee (UK Labour Party)|Labour's National Executive Committee]] blocked Williamson from standing as a Labour candidate in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Labour blocks Corbyn loyalist from standing at general election over antisemitism claims |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-williamson-general-election-labour-roger-godsiff-stephen-hepburn-corbyn-a9187711.html |accessdate=6 November 2019 |work=The Independent |date=6 November 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106162054/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chris-williamson-general-election-labour-roger-godsiff-stephen-hepburn-corbyn-a9187711.html |archive-date=6 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He resigned from the Labour Party and stood as an Independent, losing the seat and his deposit.<ref name=standard-20191107>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/general-election-news-latest-chris-williamson-to-stand-as-independent-mp-after-labour-bans-him-from-a4280721.html |title=Chris Williamson to stand as independent MP in general election after Labour bans him from party |last=Speare-Cole |first=Rebecca |newspaper=Evening Standard |location=London |date=7 November 2019 |accessdate=7 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191107054151/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/general-election-news-latest-chris-williamson-to-stand-as-independent-mp-after-labour-bans-him-from-a4280721.html |archive-date=7 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in [[Derby]], Williamson attended the St. John Fisher Primary School in [[Alvaston]], [[Castle Donington]] High School and St. Thomas More High School in [[Allenton, Derbyshire|Allenton]], followed by Leicester Polytechnic (now [[De Montfort University]]), where he obtained a [[Qualifications for professional social work|professional social work qualification]] (a CQSW) in 1985.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} After working as a craft apprentice for a year from 1972, Williamson then worked as a [[bricklayer]] for six years. He was a [[social worker]] in Derby from 1983 to 1986 before working as a welfare rights officer.\n\nWilliamson joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in 1976. He became a councillor on Derby City Council in 1991. Appointed Chair of Housing, he supported [[private finance initiative]] (PFI) projects.<ref name=\"Casalicchio\">{{cite news|last=Casalicchio|first=Emilio|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/jeremy-corbyn/house/house-magazine/94700/chris-williamson-|title=Chris Williamson: 'It's like all my Christmases have come together \u2013 the sort of Labour party I dreamed about'|work=Politics Home|agency=[[The House (magazine)|The House]]|date=26 April 2018|accessdate=28 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427053735/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/jeremy-corbyn/house/house-magazine/94700/chris-williamson-|archivedate=27 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Interviewed in 2018, he termed his approach then as \"innovative pragmatism\", seeking to \"be as radical as we possibly could within the confines that we were subjected to by central government\", arguing that \"It was a bullshit scheme\u2014I wouldn't have chosen it at all. It didn't give value for money. But what were we supposed to do as a local authority? We either [do it or] say we are not going to build these schools or we are not going to refurbish these unfit dwellings.\"<ref name=\"Casalicchio\"/>\n\nHe became leader of the Labour Group on [[Derby City Council]], serving as leader of Derby City Council on two separate occasions. While council leader, Williamson presided over a coalition with the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] for two years after Labour lost its majority in 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theredroar.com/2018/01/chris-williamsons-tory-love-in-backbencher-formed-alliance-with-conservatives-as-labour-leader-of-derby-council/|title=Chris Williamson's Tory love-in: backbencher formed alliance with Conservatives as Labour leader of Derby council|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=6 July 2019|work=Red Roar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706043003/https://www.theredroar.com/2018/01/chris-williamsons-tory-love-in-backbencher-formed-alliance-with-conservatives-as-labour-leader-of-derby-council/|archive-date=6 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was instrumental in setting up [[Holocaust Memorial Day]] events in the city and rescinded the obsolete medieval [[proscription]] barring Jews from living in Derby.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/01/chris-williamson-labour-mp-antisemitism-row|title=Chris Williamson: 'no place' in Labour for MP embroiled in antisemitism row|last=Parveen|first=Nazia|date=1 July 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113234714/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/01/chris-williamson-labour-mp-antisemitism-row|archive-date=13 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe is vice chair of the Local Government Anti Poverty Forum.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Derby+North/Chris+Williamson |title=Chris Williamson \u2013 Parliamentary candidates |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=19 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306092325/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Derby%2BNorth/Chris%2BWilliamson |archivedate=6 March 2012  }}</ref>\n\nHe has been [[Teetotalism|teetotal]] and a [[veganism|vegan]] since the 1970s, and is a member of the [[League Against Cruel Sports]].<ref name=\"full transcript column 898\">Kerry McCarthy MP [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm111101/debtext/111101-0004.htm full transcript (column 898)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901202753/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm111101/debtext/111101-0004.htm |date=1 September 2017 }}, World Vegan Day, Adjournment Debate, House of Commons, 1 November 2011.</ref><ref name=\"Casalicchio\"/><ref name=\"full transcript column 898\"/>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n===First term (2010\u201315)===\nIn the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], Williamson was elected for Derby North with a majority of 613 over the Conservative candidate.\n\nWilliamson supported [[Ed Miliband]] in the [[2010 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2010 Labour leadership election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.labour.org.uk/leadership-mps-and-meps|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101171158/http://www2.labour.org.uk/leadership-mps-and-meps|archivedate=1 January 2011|title=Leadership \u2013 MPs and MEPs \u2013 The Labour Party|date=1 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, Williamson became Shadow Fire and Emergency Services Minister within the Shadow Communities and Local Government team after just four months as an MP but, after a reshuffle of the [[Shadow Cabinet of Ed Miliband|shadow cabinet]] in 2013, was replaced by [[Lyn Brown (politician)|Lyn Brown]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.leftfutures.org/2013/10/ed-miliband-shifts-leftwards-at-conference-but-rightwards-in-the-plp/|title=Ed Miliband shifts Leftwards at conference but Rightwards in the PLP|date=9 October 2013|work=Left Futures|accessdate=10 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803074636/http://www.leftfutures.org/2013/10/ed-miliband-shifts-leftwards-at-conference-but-rightwards-in-the-plp/|archivedate=3 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He served as a member of the [[Housing, Communities and Local Government Committee|Communities and Local Government Committee]] between July and November 2010 and from November 2013 to March 2015.<ref name=\"UK Parliament\"/>\n\nIn 2014, Williamson voted to support the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|Cameron coalition's]] [[2011 military intervention in Libya]] and the [[Operation Shader|British action against ISIS in Iraq]]. In April 2018, Williamson said that, while he was initially undetermined, he was \"naive\" to support the votes. He abstained on the [[Immigration Act 2014|Immigration Bill in 2014]], following an instruction from Labour [[Whip (politics)|whips]], saying later: \"I have to say\u2014if I'm being honest\u2014I didn't study it enough or fully appreciate the implications.\"<ref name=\"Casalicchio\"/>\n\nWilliamson was one of 16 signatories of an open letter to Ed Miliband in January 2015 calling on the party to oppose further austerity, take rail franchises back into public ownership and strengthen collective bargaining arrangements.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eaton|first1=George|title=The Labour left demand a change of direction \u2013 why their intervention matters|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/01/labour-left-demand-change-direction-why-their-intervention-matters|accessdate=5 April 2015|work=New Statesman|date=26 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412090810/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/01/labour-left-demand-change-direction-why-their-intervention-matters|archivedate=12 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Williamson lost the Derby North seat to [[Amanda Solloway]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] by 41 votes. Labour Leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] described Williamson in early 2016 as a \"very great friend\", saying that his defeat at the 2015 general election was \"the worst result of that night\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/corbyn-chris-williamson-losing-derby-north-worst/story-28718402-detail/story.html|title=Corbyn: Chris Williamson losing Derby North was 'the worst result of that night'|work=[[Derby Telegraph]]|date=11 February 2016|accessdate=12 June 2017}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Second term (2017\u20132019)===\nDuring the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] campaign, he was described by the ''[[New Statesman]]'' as the \"most pro-Jeremy Corbyn candidate in England's most marginal constituency\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Chakelian|first=Anoosh|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/life-labour-s-most-pro-jeremy-corbyn-candidate-england-s-most-marginal|title=Life as Labour's most pro-Jeremy Corbyn candidate in England's most marginal constituency|work=[[New Statesman]]|date=10 May 2017|accessdate=12 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609133732/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/life-labour-s-most-pro-jeremy-corbyn-candidate-england-s-most-marginal|archivedate=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson said that his candidacy would be a \"test case for Corbynism\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/jeremy-corbyn-must-absolutely-remain-labour-leader-should-he-lose-the-election-says-ally-chris-williamson_uk_59089d43e4b0bb2d0871f129 |title=Corbyn Must 'Absolutely' Remain Labour Leader Even If He Loses The Election, Says Ally|work=[[HuffPost UK]]|date=3 May 2017|accessdate=12 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613091554/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/jeremy-corbyn-must-absolutely-remain-labour-leader-should-he-lose-the-election-says-ally-chris-williamson_uk_59089d43e4b0bb2d0871f129 |archivedate=13 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and Corbyn campaigned for him.<ref name=\"Casalicchio\"/> Williamson regained his former seat from Amanda Solloway of the Conservatives with a majority of 2,015 votes.\n\nOn 3 July 2017, Williamson was appointed Shadow Fire and Emergency Services Minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsocialist.org.uk/reshuffle-2-the-ma/|title=Reshuffle 2: The Maintenance of the Malcontents|date=8 July 2017|work=New Socialist.|accessdate=10 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031024616/https://newsocialist.org.uk/reshuffle-2-the-ma/|archivedate=31 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://press.labour.org.uk/post/162548382729/jeremy-corbyn-appoints-20-mps-to-labours-front|title=Jeremy Corbyn appoints 20 MPs to Labour's front bench|website=Labour Press|accessdate=10 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706130458/http://press.labour.org.uk/post/162548382729/jeremy-corbyn-appoints-20-mps-to-labours-front|archivedate=6 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson resigned this role on 11 January 2018; a day earlier he had suggested that [[Council Tax|council tax]] on the highest-value homes should be doubled. The comment, which was not party policy and outside his remit, was made without the knowledge of [[Andrew Gwynne]], the shadow secretary of state for communities and local government. When the issue was raised, Williamson, rather than agree to confine his public statements to his own policy area, resigned. He said: \"I've taken this decision to bring me closer to the membership of our party and to allow me to work on a broader range of issues, from environmental policy to animal rights and local government.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Heather|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/11/chris-williamson-quits-labour-frontbench-after-double-council-tax-call|title=Chris Williamson quits Labour frontbench after 'double council tax' call|work=The Guardian|date=11 January 2018|accessdate=11 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111153949/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jan/11/chris-williamson-quits-labour-frontbench-after-double-council-tax-call|archivedate=11 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Williamson voiced doubts that the Syrian government was responsible for the [[Douma chemical attack|gas attack on Douma]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Harrison |first=Tristia |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/world/middle-east/2018/08/labour-can-be-jo-cox-s-party-or-chris-williamson-s-it-cannot-be-both |title=Labour can be Jo Cox's party or Chris Williamson's \u2013 it cannot be both |work=Newstatesman.com |date=21 August 2018 |accessdate=20 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126095758/https://www.newstatesman.com/world/middle-east/2018/08/labour-can-be-jo-cox-s-party-or-chris-williamson-s-it-cannot-be-both |archivedate=26 November 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In August 2018, he said it was a \"privilege\" to hear a talk by a pro-[[Bashar al-Assad|Assad]] [[blog]]ger, Vanessa Beeley.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/labour-mp-chris-williamson-vanessa-beeley_uk_5b7adee4e4b018b93e963784 |title=Labour's Chris Williamson Praises Vanessa Beeley, Blogger Who Called Jo Cox A 'Warmongering Blairite' |work=Huffingtonpost.co.uk |date=20 August 2018 |accessdate=16 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929041331/https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/labour-mp-chris-williamson-vanessa-beeley_uk_5b7adee4e4b018b93e963784 |archivedate=29 September 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/world/middle-east/2018/08/labour-can-be-jo-cox-s-party-or-chris-williamson-s-it-cannot-be-both|title=Labour can be Jo Cox's party or Chris Williamson's \u2013 it cannot be both|work=Newstatesman.com|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=20 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126095758/https://www.newstatesman.com/world/middle-east/2018/08/labour-can-be-jo-cox-s-party-or-chris-williamson-s-it-cannot-be-both|archivedate=26 November 2018|url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Friedman |first=Gabe |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/uk-labour-mp-slammed-for-praising-anti-semitic-pro-assad-conspiracist/ |title=UK Labour MP slammed for praising anti-Semitic pro-Assad conspiracist |work=The Times of Israel |date=22 August 2018 |accessdate=20 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221113512/https://www.timesofisrael.com/uk-labour-mp-slammed-for-praising-anti-semitic-pro-assad-conspiracist/ |archivedate=21 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nHe says that, with Corbyn as leader, the party has \"a common-sense socialist\" who does not place MPs in the situation of risking being in conflict with the party whips. Williamson said he is \"not one for undermining the leadership publicly\", explaining the difference between his history in the [[Division of the assembly|division lobbies]] and Corbyn's earlier frequent parliamentary vote rebellions as Corbyn expressing the opinions of party members.<ref name=\"Casalicchio\"/>\n\nWilliamson supports a mandatory reselection process for all Labour MPs and, in 2018, toured the country to promote this change from the existing procedure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/09/labour-mp-chris-williamson-democracy-roadshow-mandatory-reselection|title=Labour MP Chris Williamson launches 'democracy' roadshow|last=Crerar|first=Pippa|date=9 July 2018|accessdate=6 August 2019|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806073650/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/09/labour-mp-chris-williamson-democracy-roadshow-mandatory-reselection|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Views on handling of antisemitism allegations===\nIn 2017, Williamson said that attacks on Corbyn's handling of alleged [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism within the Labour Party]] were \"proxy wars and bullshit\" and that \"I'm not saying it never ever happens but it is a really dirty, lowdown trick, particularly the antisemitism smears. Many people in the Jewish community are appalled by what they see as the weaponisation of antisemitism for political ends.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/aug/28/make-labour-leadership-rules-more-democratic-urges-shadow-minister|title=MPs should have no say over who leads Labour, argues shadow minister|work=The Guardian|date=28 August 2017|accessdate=2 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002215225/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/aug/28/make-labour-leadership-rules-more-democratic-urges-shadow-minister|archivedate=2 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Marie van der Zyl]], the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews|Board of Deputies]] vice-president, said that Williamson should \"show solidarity with those suffering racism within his own party rather than blaming the victims\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-chris-williamson-dismisses-jew-hate-allegations-1.443446|title=Anger as 'deplorable' Labour MP dismisses antisemitism allegations as 'smears'|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=29 August 2017|accessdate=2 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002215617/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-chris-williamson-dismisses-jew-hate-allegations-1.443446|archivedate=2 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Williamson described antisemitism as being \"utterly repugnant and a scourge on society, which is why I stand in absolute solidarity with anyone who is subjected to antisemitic abuse\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-chris-williamson-dismisses-jew-hate-allegations-1.443446|title=Anger as 'deplorable' Labour MP dismisses antisemitism allegations as 'smears'|work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=29 August 2017|accessdate=2 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002215617/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-chris-williamson-dismisses-jew-hate-allegations-1.443446|archivedate=2 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He added that his critics' \"accusations of anti-Semitism (against him) were positively sinister\" and \"highly offensive and hurtful\" in suggesting \"that I was an anti-Semite myself, yet I have fought racism all my adult life\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Williamson|first=Chris|url=http://www.tribunemagazine.org/2017/09/agenda-setting-8/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170924121639/http://www.tribunemagazine.org/2017/09/agenda-setting-8/|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 September 2017|title=Agenda setting|work=Tribune|date=9 September 2017|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Williamson referenced [[Ken Livingstone]]: \"We've got these ridiculous suspensions and expulsions from the party\" made \"in the most grotesque and unfair way\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/chris-williamson-condemned-by-board-of-deputies-after-calling-for-ken-livingstone-to-be-reinstated-by-labour-party-1.460999|title=Board of Deputies condemns Labour MP's comments backing Ken Livingstone|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=19 March 2018|accessdate=18 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419053413/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/chris-williamson-condemned-by-board-of-deputies-after-calling-for-ken-livingstone-to-be-reinstated-by-labour-party-1.460999|archivedate=19 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Supporting [[Len McCluskey]], who had accused some Labour MPs of using the issue of antisemitism in campaigning against Corbyn, he described some of his colleagues as \"malcontents\" who were \"completely out of step with party members\" and voters,<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Lucy|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sir-keir-starmer-hits-back-at-union-leader-len-mccluskey-in-antisemitism-row-7gg0chqdc|title=Sir Keir Starmer hits back at Union leader Len McCluskey in antisemitism row|work=The Times|date=26 April 2018|accessdate=28 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427183755/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sir-keir-starmer-hits-back-at-union-leader-len-mccluskey-in-antisemitism-row-7gg0chqdc|archivedate=27 April 2018|url-status=live }}{{subscription required}}</ref> but that deselection of MPs was \"a matter for Labour Party members in each constituency and not a matter for me or indeed Len\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Matt|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/94697/chris-williamson-blasts-malcontent-labour-mps-amid|title=Chris Williamson blasts 'malcontent' Labour MPs amid bitter anti-Semitism row|work=Politics Home|date=26 April 2018|accessdate=28 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428183909/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/94697/chris-williamson-blasts-malcontent-labour-mps-amid|archivedate=28 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, during a visit to Derbyshire, [[Jeremy Corbyn]] defended Williamson, saying that \"Chris Williamson is a very good, very effective Labour MP. He's a very strong anti-racist campaigner. He is not anti-semitic in any way.\"<ref>\"Jeremy Corbyn defends ally Chris Williamson against anti-semitism claims\" 1 February 2019, https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/101537/jeremy-corbyn-defends-ally-chris-williamson {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626172218/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/101537/jeremy-corbyn-defends-ally-chris-williamson |date=26 June 2019 }}</ref>\n\n====Formal investigation and suspension====\nIn February 2019, Williamson was criticised for booking a room in the [[Houses of Parliament]] for a screening of ''[[Witch Hunt (2019 film)|Witch Hunt]]'', a film about suspended party member [[Jackie Walker (activist)|Jackie Walker]], to be hosted by [[Jewish Voice for Labour]].<ref name=\"set for clash\">{{cite news|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-mp-chris-williamson-party-too-apologetic-over-antisemitism-complaints|title=Corbyn set for clash with Watson over MP's antisemitism remarks|last=Mason|first=Rowena|work=The Guardian|date=27 February 2019|accessdate=28 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228012452/https://amp.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-mp-chris-williamson-party-too-apologetic-over-antisemitism-complaints|archivedate=28 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref> At the same time, a video was published by ''[[The Yorkshire Post]]'' of him telling a [[Momentum]] meeting in [[Sheffield]] that the party was being \"demonised as a racist, bigoted party\", partly because, in response to criticism, the party had \"given too much ground (and) been too apologetic\", going on to say \"We've done more to address the scourge of anti-Semitism than any other political party.\"<ref name=\"Bates 2019\">{{cite web | last=Bates | first=Elizabeth | title=Chris Williamson: Labour has been too apologetic about anti-Semitism | website=Yorkshire Post | date=26 February 2019 | url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/chris-williamson-labour-has-been-too-apologetic-about-anti-semitism-1-9618191 | accessdate=6 March 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303073859/https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/chris-williamson-labour-has-been-too-apologetic-about-anti-semitism-1-9618191 | archivedate=3 March 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=suspended/> [[Deputy Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Labour Deputy Leader]] [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] said that Williamson should have the Labour whip removed for his comments and a group of 38 Labour MPs had written to the party's General Secretary to ask that he be suspended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/mp-chris-williamson-suspended-from-labour-party-amid-antisemitism-storm-a4078386.html|title=Labour MP suspended over anti-Semitism remarks|date=27 February 2019|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=27 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228010127/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/mp-chris-williamson-suspended-from-labour-party-amid-antisemitism-storm-a4078386.html|archivedate=28 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref> There was also pressure from London mayor [[Sadiq Khan]], [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]] leader Tim Roache, anti-racism charity [[HOPE not hate]], the [[Jewish Labour Movement]] and the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2019/02/chris-williamson-suspended-from-the-labour-party/|title=Chris Williamson suspended from the Labour Party|date=27 February 2019|website=[[LabourList]]|accessdate=27 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228010216/https://labourlist.org/2019/02/chris-williamson-suspended-from-the-labour-party/|archivedate=28 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"splits exposed\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-suspends-chris-williamson-over-antisemitism-remarks|title=Labour splits exposed as MP is suspended over antisemitism remarks|work=[[The Guardian]]|first1=Heather|last1=Stewart|first2=Peter|last2=Walker|date=27 February 2019|accessdate=27 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227174126/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-suspends-chris-williamson-over-antisemitism-remarks|archivedate=27 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/mp-chris-williamson-accused-trolling-jewish-community-by-hosting-jackie-walker-film-parliament-1.480691|title=MP Chris Williamson accused of 'trolling Jewish community' by hosting Jackie Walker film in Parliament|last=Doherty|first=Rosa|date=26 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227060330/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/mp-chris-williamson-accused-trolling-jewish-community-by-hosting-jackie-walker-film-parliament-1.480691|archivedate=27 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref> Jewish Voice for Labour defended Williamson, as did the \"[[Labour Against the Witchhunt]]\" pressure group and the Sheffield Hallam constituency branch of the Labour Party who voted 40 to 0 in favour of a motion stating Williamson's comments had been taken out of context.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/01/local-labour-parties-drawn-into-row-over-antisemitism-claims |title=Local Labour parties drawn into row over antisemitism claims |accessdate=4 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304042847/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/01/local-labour-parties-drawn-into-row-over-antisemitism-claims |archivedate=4 March 2019 |url-status=live |newspaper=The Guardian |date=March 2019 |last1=Sabbagh |first1=Dan }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/labour-suspension-of-chris-williamson-branded-madness|title=Labour suspension of Chris Williamson branded 'madness'|first1=Lamiat|last1=Sabin|date=27 February 2019|website=Morning Star|accessdate=3 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306044446/https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/labour-suspension-of-chris-williamson-branded-madness|archivedate=6 March 2019|url-status=live }}</ref> Williamson apologised for his comments saying: \"I deeply regret, and apologise for, my recent choice of words when speaking about how the Labour Party has responded to the ongoing fight against antisemitism inside of our party. I was trying to stress how much the party has done to tackle anti-Semitism\".<ref name=\"to be investigated\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47385108|title=MP to be investigated in anti-Semitism row|date=27 February 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=27 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228133322/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47385108|archivedate=28 February 2019|url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-mp-chris-williamson-party-too-apologetic-over-antisemitism-complaints |title=Corbyn set for clash with Watson over MP's antisemitism remarks |work=[[The Guardian]] |first1=Rowena |last1=Mason |first2=Peter |last2=Walker |first3=Jessica |last3=Elgot |date=27 February 2019 |accessdate=27 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227103438/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/27/labour-mp-chris-williamson-party-too-apologetic-over-antisemitism-complaints |archivedate=27 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 27 February 2019, he was put under formal notice of investigation,<ref name=\"to be investigated\"/><ref name=\"set for clash\"/> and later that day suspended from the party.<ref name=suspended/><ref name=\"splits exposed\"/>\n\n====Formal warning, resuspension and further charges====\nLabour readmitted Williamson on 26 June 2019 after a [[National Executive Committee]] panel considered his case and issued him with a formal warning. A party source said: \"An NEC panel, advised by an independent barrister, found Chris Williamson had breached the party's rules and gave him a formal sanction. He could face further, more severe, action if he repeats any similar comments or behaviour.\"<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">BBC. \"Labour anti-Semitism row: Chris Williamson allowed back into party\". 26 July 2019, https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48778129 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626171709/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48778129 |date=26 June 2019 }}</ref> It was suggested that the decision for readmission was made in order to enable Williamson to enter the Labour MP reselection process then underway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/26/chris-williamson-back-in-labour-party-after-antisemitism-remarks|title=Chris Williamson back in Labour party after antisemitism remarks|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626185149/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/26/chris-williamson-back-in-labour-party-after-antisemitism-remarks|archive-date=26 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The decision to readmit Williamson was criticised by Labour parliamentarians and parliamentary staff<ref name=LAW>'''Statement on Chris Williamson''', 27 June 2019: \nWe cannot overstate the depth and breadth of hurt and anger felt about the readmission of Chris Williamson into the Labour Party and the questions that arise about the fairness of the process.<br>\nThe offficer recommendation - that Mr. Williamson should be referred to the National Constitutional Committee for action - was ignored by the members of the NEC panel. That the composition of that panel was changed at short notice seems highly irregular.<br>Justice needs to be seen to be done and this process has not done that.<br>Given that the Labour Party is being investigated by the EHRC over allegations of institutional antisemitism this case is particularly important.<br>It is clear to us that the Labour Party's disciplinary process remains mired by the appearance of political interference. This must stop. We need a truly independent process.<br>We call on Jeremy Corbyn to show leadership by asking for this inappropriate, offensive and reputationally damaging decision to be overturned and reviewed.<br>Ultimately, it is for Jeremy Corbyn to decide whether Chris Willamson retains the Labour whip. He must remove it immediately if we are to stand any hope of persuading anyone that the Labour Party is taking antisemitism seriously.<br>'''Signed'''\n{|\n|-\n|\n[[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]<br>[[Molly Lynch]]<br>[[Stella Creasy]]<br>[[Anna Turley]]<br>[[Rosie Duffield]]<br>[[Louise Ellman]]<br>[[Ruth Smeeth]]<br>[[Jenny Chapman]]<br>[[Roberta Blackman-Woods]]<br>[[Stephen Doughty]]<br>[[Karin Smyth]]<br>[[Baroness Thornton]]<br>[[Iain McNicol|Lord McNicol]]<br>[[Baroness Morgan of Huyton]]<br>[[Lord Turnberg]]<br>[[Gloria De Piero]]<br>[[Baroness Royall of Blaisdon]]<br>[[Yvette Cooper]]<br>[[Baroness Massey of Darwen]]<br>[[Baroness Kingsmill]]<br>[[Lord Soley]]<br>[[Madeleine Moon]]\n|\n[[Kate Green]]<br>[[Ruth Cadbury]]<br>[[Owen Smith]]<br>[[Seema Malhotra]]<br>[[Liz Kendall]]<br>[[Chris Matheson (politician)|Chris Matheson]]<br>[[Margaret Hodge]]<br>[[Stephen Kinnock]]<br>[[Jeff Smith (British politician)|Jeff Smith]]<br>[[Chris Bryant]]<br>[[Wes Streeting]]<br>[[Julie Elliott]]<br>[[Lord Levy]]<br>[[Lord Knight of Weymouth]]<br>[[Lord Harris of Haringey]]<br>[[Ali McGovern]]<br>[[James Frith]]<br>[[Lucy Powell]]<br>[[Bridget Phillipson]]<br>[[Pat McFadden]]<br>[[Baroness McIntosh of Hudnall]]<br>[[Lord Triesman]]<br>[[Lord Dubs]]<br>[[Ian Murray (Scottish politician)|Ian Murray]]\n|\n[[Darren Jones (politician)|Darren Jones]]<br>[[Alex Sobel]]<br>[[Karen Buck]]<br>[[Neil Coyle]]<br>[[Lord Mandelson]]<br>[[Anna McMorrin]]<br>[[Chi Onwurah]]<br>[[Baroness Taylor of Bolton]]<br>[[Lord Willie Bach]]<br>[[Susan Elan Jones]]<br>[[Ged Killen]]<br>[[Baroness Ramsay of Cartvale]]<br>[[Lord Livermore]]<br>[[Kevin Barron]]<br>[[Dan Jarvis]]<br>[[Jess Phillips]]<br>[[Martin Whitfield]]<br>[[Rachel Reeves]]<br>[[Peter Kyle]]<br>[[Baroness Armstrong of Hill Top]]<br>[[Lord Young of Norwood Green]]<br>[[Ellie Reeves]]\n|\n[[Baroness Maggie Jones]]<br>[[Rushanara Ali]]<br>[[Debbie Abrahams]]<br>[[Daniel Zeichner]]<br>[[Lilian Greenwood]]<br>[[Graham Jones (politician)|Graham Jones]]<br>[[Toby Perkins]]<br>[[George Robertson, Baron Robertson of Port Ellen|Lord George Robertson]]<br>[[Baroness Mary Goudie]]<br>[[Barry Sheerman]]<br>[[Tonia Antoniazzi]]<br>[[Ian Lucas]]<br>[[Lord George Foulkes]]<br>[[Lord Wood of Anfield]]<br>[[Cat McKinnell]]<br>[[Ben Bradshaw]]<br>[[Lord Haskell]]<br>[[Lisa Nandy]]<br>[[Gareth Thomas (English politician)|Gareth Thomas]]<br>[[Clive Brooke, Baron Brooke of Alverthorpe|Lord Brooke]]<br>[[Sharon Hodgson]]<br>[[Lord Kennedy of Southwark]]\n\n|}\n''from'' http://www.labouragainstthewitchhunt.org/, ''also see'' https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/tom-watson-and-labour-mps-demand-jeremy-corbyn-overturn-chris-williamson-decision_uk_5d14c696e4b0d0a2c0ad0c03</ref> and by Jewish communal bodies.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>Mathilde Frot. \"Labour MP Chris Williamson let back in with \u2018formal warning\u2019. Jewish News. 26 June 2019.https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/labour-mp-chris-williamson-let-back-in-with-formal-warning-after-suspension</ref> Two days later, he was resuspended after the Labour Party decided to review the decision.<ref name=\"Kentish\"/>\n\nAdditional allegations of misconduct resulting in a separate suspension was imposed on 3 September. Williamson's barrister, who called these allegations \"similar in nature\" to the first set, said \"It appears from the timing ... that the purpose of the decision to raise these allegations now, and to impose a second suspension on the claimant, is to seek to ensure that he will remain suspended even if this claim is successful and that he will therefore remain disqualified from selection in the forthcoming general election.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/derby-north-mp-chris-williamsons-3314988|title=Derby North MP Chris Williamson's legal fight is heard in the High Court|last=Hawley|first=Zena|date=13 September 2019|accessdate=10 October 2019|work=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927020550/https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/derby-north-mp-chris-williamsons-3314988|archive-date=27 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Reaction to resuspension====\nIn July 2019, the [[Labour Party in Northern Ireland]] (LPNI) released a statement opposing the resuspension of Williamson on the grounds that it was \"arbitrary and unreasonable\" and \"the Labour Party does not have any form of particular problem with anti-semitism\".<ref name=\"LPNIstat\">{{cite web|title=Statement on Chris Williamson MP, and on the allegation that the Labour Party is anti-semitic.|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1yXdpUPy67TmkfkURHkJicaIKE02jeS3j/view|publisher=[[Labour Party in Northern Ireland]]|accessdate=5 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705224721/https://drive.google.com/file/d/1yXdpUPy67TmkfkURHkJicaIKE02jeS3j/view|archive-date=5 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the same month, in a survey of LabourList readers with over 10,000 responses, over two thirds of those expressing a view supported Williamson's readmission.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://labourlist.org/2019/07/readmit-williamson-and-adopt-an-independent-complaints-process-say-labourlist-readers/|title=Readmit Williamson and adopt an independent complaints process, say LabourList readers|last=Rodgers|first=Sienna|date=2 July 2019|accessdate=5 July 2019|work=Labour List|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703140455/https://labourlist.org/2019/07/readmit-williamson-and-adopt-an-independent-complaints-process-say-labourlist-readers/|archive-date=3 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The leading Jewish scholar and activist [[Noam Chomsky]] stated that there was \"nothing even remotely antisemitic\" in Williamson's comments at Sheffield, and remarked that the way accusations were being used in cases such as Williamson was \"not only a disgrace, but also \u2013 to put it simply \u2013 an insult to the memory of the victims of the Holocaust.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cowles |first1=Ben |title=Chomsky speaks out against the attacks on Chris Williamson |url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/chomsky-speaks-out-against-the-attacks-on-chris-williamson |accessdate=25 September 2019 |work=Morning Star |publisher=The People\u2019s Press Society |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716002915/https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/chomsky-speaks-out-against-the-attacks-on-chris-williamson |url-status=live |archive-date=16 July 2019 |date=5 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"JVL Suspending Williamson\">{{cite web |title=Suspending Chris Williamson \u2013 The Fury And The Fakery |url=https://www.jewishvoiceforlabour.org.uk/article/suspending-chris-williamson-the-fury-and-the-fakery/ |publisher=Jewish Voice for Labour |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925150229/https://www.jewishvoiceforlabour.org.uk/article/suspending-chris-williamson-the-fury-and-the-fakery/ |archive-date=25 September 2019 |url-status=live |date=5 July 2019 |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thecanary.co/trending/2019/07/05/noam-chomsky-backs-chris-williamson-and-calls-the-antisemitism-smear-campaign-an-insult-to-the-memory-of-holocaust-victims/|title=Noam Chomsky backs Chris Williamson, and calls the antisemitism smear campaign 'an insult to the memory' of Holocaust victims|last=Mendoza|first=Kerry-anne|date=5 July 2019|accessdate=6 July 2019|work=The Canary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706053103/https://www.thecanary.co/trending/2019/07/05/noam-chomsky-backs-chris-williamson-and-calls-the-antisemitism-smear-campaign-an-insult-to-the-memory-of-holocaust-victims/|archive-date=6 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Campaign for Chris Williamson, established to support him, includes Israeli and British academics, film directors [[Mike Leigh]] and [[Ken Loach]], musicians [[Brian Eno]] and [[Roger Waters]], journalist [[John Pilger]], actor [[Miriam Margolyes]] and comedian [[Alexei Sayle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/derby-north-mp-chris-williamsons-3314988|title=Derby North MP Chris Williamson's legal fight is heard in the High Court|last=Hawley|first=Zena|date=13 September 2019|accessdate=16 September 2019|work=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918030434/https://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/news/derby-news/derby-north-mp-chris-williamsons-3314988|archive-date=18 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, more than one hundred signatories, describing themselves as \"all Jews\", including Noam Chomsky<ref name=\"Board complains\"/> signed a letter of support for Williamson.<ref>[https://archive.today/20190708173939/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2019/jul/08/jewish-support-for-chris-williamson 'Jewish support for Chris Williamson'], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 8 July 2019. Quote: \"We the undersigned, all Jews, are writing in support of Chris Williamson and to register our dismay at the recent letter organised by Tom Watson, and signed by parliamentary Labour party and House of Lords members, calling for his suspension\"</ref> The letter was later removed from the Guardian website, after questions were raised about the listed affiliation of some individuals on the list of signatories. [[Hope not Hate]] said that the person who used the organisation's name had not been authorised to do so and the Board of Deputies of British Jews said that two of the signatories had promoted 9/11 conspiracy theories.<ref name=\"York 2019\">{{cite web | author= Chris York | title= 'Misleading And Inaccurate' Letter Supporting MP Chris Williamson Removed By The Guardian | website=HuffPost  | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/chris-williamson-guardian-letter_uk_5d249fefe4b07e698c412ab5 | access-date=2019-07-31| date= 9 July 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Board complains\">{{cite web |author=Daniel Sugarman| title= Board of Deputies complains to Guardian about letter from 'prominent' Jews supporting Chris Williamson | website=Jewish Chronicle | url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/board-of-deputies-complains-to-guardian-about-letter-from-prominent-jews-supporting-chris-williams-1.4862605 | date= July 9, 2019 | access-date=2019-07-31}}{{dead link |date=August 2019}}</ref>\n\nPolitical opponents have sought to prevent him speaking, such as in Hull<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/hull-east-yorkshire-news/chris-williamson-mp-suspended-hull-3133754|title=Row erupts as suspended MP Chris Williamson in Hull to speak to trades union activists|last=Young|first=Angus|date=25 July 2019|accessdate=6 August 2019|work=Hull Live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806172416/https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/hull-east-yorkshire-news/chris-williamson-mp-suspended-hull-3133754|archive-date=6 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and Hebden Bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/uk/yorkshire-town-hall-meeting-featuring-mp-chris-williamson-cancelled-over-fears-it-might-affect-wedding-at-the-same-venue-1-9912110|title=Yorkshire town hall meeting featuring MP Chris Williamson cancelled over fears it might affect wedding at the same venue|last=Greenwood|first=John|date=2 August 2019|accessdate=6 August 2019|work=Yorkshire Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802124112/https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/uk/yorkshire-town-hall-meeting-featuring-mp-chris-williamson-cancelled-over-fears-it-might-affect-wedding-at-the-same-venue-1-9912110|archive-date=2 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Similarly, an event due to be hosted by Williamson at the Brighthelm Centre in [[Brighton]] was cancelled after local MP [[Peter Kyle]] contacted the venue to express his concerns over Williamson's alleged antisemitism. A second venue withdrew when staff were threatened in person and abused in phone calls and on their personal social media accounts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/brighton-holiday-inn-cancels-chris-williamson-event-after-complaints-1.487218|title=Brighton Holiday Inn cancels event with suspended Labour MP Chris Williamson after complaints|last=Harpin|first=Lee|date=7 August 2019|accessdate=7 August 2019|work=Jewish Chronicle|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807112525/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/brighton-holiday-inn-cancels-chris-williamson-event-after-complaints-1.487218|archive-date=7 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Board of Deputies of British Jews and the [[Jewish Leadership Council]] called a protest against Chris Williamson speaking, with a third venue then cancelling the booking after threats of violence were received.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/news-features/after-dropping-chris-williamson-event-quakers-take-time-to-reflect-on-hosting-speakers-accused-of-1.487569|title=After dropping Chris Williamson event, Quakers 'take time to reflect' on hosting speakers accused of antisemitism|last=Weich|first=Ben|date=16 August 2019|accessdate=18 August 2019|work=Jewish Chronicle|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818181721/https://www.thejc.com/news/news-features/after-dropping-chris-williamson-event-quakers-take-time-to-reflect-on-hosting-speakers-accused-of-1.487569|archive-date=18 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\nSupporters of the MP talked of the importance of protecting freedom of speech.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/chris-williamson-event-brighton-labour-antisemitism-board-of-deputies-jlc-protest-1.487301|title=Quakers cancel Chris Williamson Brighton event as Jewish groups planned protest|last=Weich|first=|date=8 August 2019|accessdate=8 August 2019|work=Jewish Chronicle|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808154356/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/chris-williamson-event-brighton-labour-antisemitism-board-of-deputies-jlc-protest-1.487301|archive-date=8 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In response, Williamson said: \"The grotesque slurs that Peter Kyle and others have levelled against me are truly despicable. I have a long and proud record of fighting racism, which has always involved standing up for every oppressed and marginalised group in society, including Jewish people. When Peter Kyle was still in nappies, I was an active member of the Anti-Nazi League, physically confronting foul racists and anti-Semites in the National Front.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/17792339.chris-williamson-event-cancelled-venue-mp-39-s-intervention|work=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]]|title=Chris Williamson event CANCELLED by venue after MP's intervention|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=24 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724165131/https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/17792339.chris-williamson-event-cancelled-venue-mp-39-s-intervention/|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}{{better source|date=July 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, the [[Union of Jewish Students]] and the Nottingham Jewish Society demanded that the [[University of Nottingham]] cancel a planned lecture by Williamson.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jewish-students-call-for-nottingham-university-to-cancel-chris-williamson-invitation-1.489683|title=Jewish students call for the University of Nottingham to cancel Chris Williamson invitation|last=Sugarman|first=Daniel|date=4 October 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=The Jewish Chronicle|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005141505/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jewish-students-call-for-nottingham-university-to-cancel-chris-williamson-invitation-1.489683|archive-date=5 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The demand was supported by the Jewish Labour Movement and the Board of Deputies of British Jews. The university said \u201cWhile the university is committed to supporting the well-being of all students within our community, we also have a legal duty to ensure that lawful free speech should not be prevented on campus.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-groups-furious-after-mp-chris-williamson-invited-to-deliver-lecture/|title=University of Nottingham defends invitation to Chris Williamson despite concern|last=Frot|first=Mathilde|date=4 October 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019|work=Jewish News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191007193714/https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-groups-furious-after-mp-chris-williamson-invited-to-deliver-lecture/|archive-date=7 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\nA similar venue denial campaign was mounted by Jewish groups against [[Jackie Walker (activist)|Jackie Walker]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/389750/controversial-momentum-figure-jackie-walker-to-address-dundee-university-audience-despite-anti-semitic-allegations/|title=Controversial Momentum figure Jackie Walker to address Dundee University audience despite anti-semitic allegations|last=Sneddon|first=Ciaran|work=\u201dThe Courier\u201d|date=19 March 2017|accessdate=1 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302024514/https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/389750/controversial-momentum-figure-jackie-walker-to-address-dundee-university-audience-despite-anti-semitic-allegations/|archive-date=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/396453/jackie-walker-lecture-dundee-university-goes-ahead-despite-hate-speech-claims/|title=Jackie Walker lecture at Dundee University goes ahead despite \"hate speech\" claims|last=Vidinova|first=Nadia|work=\u201dThe Courier\u201d|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=1 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302024541/https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/dundee/396453/jackie-walker-lecture-dundee-university-goes-ahead-despite-hate-speech-claims/|archive-date=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jackie-walker-claims-board-attempting-to-shut-down-show-1.442444|title=Jackie Walker claims Board of Deputies tried to shut down her Edinburgh show|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=4 August 2017|accessdate=1 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701031021/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jackie-walker-claims-board-attempting-to-shut-down-show-1.442444|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Williamson lodged legal papers with the High Court to challenge Labour's right to take away the whip two days after he was allowed to return as a member.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/13/chris-williamson-sues-labour-over-his-suspension-from-party|title=Chris Williamson sues Labour over his suspension from party|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|date=2019-08-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815090208/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/13/chris-williamson-sues-labour-over-his-suspension-from-party|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49340347|title=MP sues Labour over anti-Semitism suspension|date=2019-08-14|access-date=2019-08-15|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815100540/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49340347|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 October 2019, the judge ruled that reopening the case was unfair, but upheld the legality of a further suspension on 3 September on other charges.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/breaking-chris-williamson-mp-loses-20554102|title=Chris Williamson MP loses bid to be reinstated to Labour party after anti-semitism suspension|last=Tobin|first=Sam|date=10 October 2019|accessdate=10 October 2019|work=Daily Mirror|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191010155944/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/breaking-chris-williamson-mp-loses-20554102|archive-date=10 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, a Methodist Church in [[Downham]] cancelled the booking for a meeting he was due to speak at after \"its understanding\" of Williamson increased, having not known anything about him at the time of the booking.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lynnnews.co.uk/news/labour-party-distances-itself-from-downham-market-chris-williamson-meeting-9085834/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=12 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012014448/https://www.lynnnews.co.uk/news/labour-party-distances-itself-from-downham-market-chris-williamson-meeting-9085834/ |archive-date=12 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2019 General Election===\nWilliamson was prevented from standing as the Labour Candidate in his Derby North constituency in the 2019 General Election as a result of his active suspension. As a result he resigned from the Labour Party and stood instead as an independent candidate. He won only 635 votes losing his deposit and coming bottom of the poll.<ref name=\"UK Parliament\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=chris-williamson/3976 |publicwhip=Chris_Williamson |theywork=chris_williamson}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bob Laxton]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = Member of Parliament for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]]\n | years = [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Amanda Solloway]] }}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Amanda Solloway]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]]|years=[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=Amanda Solloway}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{East Midlands Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williamson, Chris}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Leicester Polytechnic]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:English social workers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for constituencies in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:People from Normanton, Derby]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: As a result \u2192 As a result,, a Methodist Church \u2192 a Methodist church", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Williamson_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Ibn Tumart", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]\n|honorific_prefix =al-Imam al-Mahdi\n|name             =Muhamed Ibn Tumart\n|image            = Abu Yaqub Yusef Coin.png\n|caption          = Coin minted during the reign of [[Abu Yaqub Yusuf]], the last line of the inner inscription on the right reads: ''al-Mahdi Imam al-Umma''<ref>Full inscription in Arabic: {{lang|ar|\u0628\u0633\u0645 \u0627\u0627\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u062d\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u062d\u064a\u0645 \u0644\u0627 \u0625\u0644\u0647 \u0625\u0644\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0631\u0633\u0648\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a \u0625\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0629}}</ref>\n|title            =Imam al-Umma<br />{{lang|ar|\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0629}}\n|birth_name       = \n|birth_date       =1080\n|birth_place      =Igiliz, [[Sous]], [[Almoravid empire]]\n|death_date       =c. 1128\u20131130\n|death_place      =[[Tinmel]], [[High Atlas]], [[Almohad Empire]]\n|death_cause      =\n|resting_place    =Tinmel Mosque<ref>his shrine was destroyed by a [[Marinid]] lieutenant</ref> \n|other_names      =\n|nationality      =\n|ethnicity        =[[Berbers|Berber]]\n|era              =\n|region           =\n|occupation       =\n|denomination     =[[Sunni Islam|Sunni]]\n|jurisprudence    = [[Zahiri]]\n|creed            = [[Ash'ari]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Spevack|first=Aaron|title=The Archetypal Sunni Scholar: Law, Theology, and Mysticism in the Synthesis of Al-Bajuri |origyear=2010|publisher=State University of New York Press|date=2014|isbn=143845371X|page=44}}</ref>\n\n|movement         = Almohad\n|main_interests   = \n|notable_ideas    =\n|notable_works    =\n|alma_mater       = \n|Sufi_order       =\n|disciple_of      =[[At-Turtushi]]\n|awards           =\n|influences       = [[Ibn Hazm]], [[at-Turtushi]], [[al-Ghazali]]\n|influenced       = [[Hafsid]]s\n|module           = \n|website          =\n|signature        =\n}}\n{{History of Morocco}}\n\n'''Abu Abd Allah Muhammad Ibn Tumart''' ([[Berber language|Berber]]: ''Amghar ibn Tumert'', {{lang-ar|\u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u062a\u0648\u0645\u0631\u062a}}, ca. 1080\u20131130 or 1128<ref>{{cite book |script-title=ar: \u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u062e\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0646: \u062f\u064a\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0628\u062a\u062f\u0623 \u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0628\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628 \u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u0628\u0631 \u0648 \u0645\u0646 \u0639\u0627\u0635\u0631\u0647\u0645 \u0645\u0646 \u0630\u0648\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0623\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0643\u0628\u0631\n|last= Ibn Khaldun\n|first=Abderahman\n|authorlink=Ibn Khaldun\n|year=1377\n|publisher= {{lang|ar|\u062f\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0643\u0631}}\n| volume=6\n|page=305\n}}</ref>), a Moroccan Muslim [[Berber people|Berber]] [[religion|religious]] scholar, teacher and political leader, from the Sous region in southern [[Morocco]]. He founded and served as the spiritual and first military leader of the [[Almohad dynasty|Almohad]] movement, a puritanical reform movement launched among the [[Masmuda]] [[Berber people|Berbers]] of the [[Atlas Mountains]]. Ibn Tumart launched an open revolt against the ruling [[Almoravid dynasty|Almoravids]] during the 1120s. After his death his followers, the Almohads, went on to conquer much of North Africa and part of Spain.\n\n==Biography==\n\n=== Early life ===\n\nMany of the details of Ibn Tumart's life were recorded by [[hagiography|hagiographers]], whose accounts probably mix legendary elements from the [[Almohad]] doctrine of their founding figure and spiritual leader.<ref>A French translation of the relation of the Almohad hagiographer [[Mohammed al-Baydhaq]], can be found in  L\u00e9vi-Proven\u00e7al (1928). A Spanish translation of the arguably most reliable Almohad chronicle ''[[al-Bayan al-Mughrib]]'' of [[Ibn Idhari|Ibn Idhari al-Marrakushi]], can be found in Huici Miranda (1951).  Ibn Idhari was a principal source for the account, ''Kitab al-'Ibar'', of [[Ibn Khaldun]].  [[Ibn Khallikan]]'s entry on Ibn Tumart can be found in English translation in ''Biographical Dictionary'', 1843 M. de Slane trans., Paris, vol. 3, [https://books.google.com/books?id=eeE80B81GfgC&pg=PA205#v=onepage&q&f=false p.205])</ref> Ibn Tumart was born sometime between 1078 and 1082 in the small village of [[Igiliz]] (exact location uncertain<ref>Fromherz (2005: p.177) identifies Igiliz (and Ibn Tumart's nearby cave) with the modern small village of Igli, some 30 km east of [[Taroudannt]] in the [[Sous]] valley</ref>) in the [[Sous]] valley of southern [[Morocco]].<ref name = kennedy>H. Kennedy (1996)</ref> He was a member of the Hargha, a [[Berbers|Berber]] tribe of the [[Anti-Atlas]] range, part of the [[Masmuda]] ([[Berber languages|Berber]]: ''imesmuden'') tribal confederation.<ref name=\"EI2\">{{Cite encyclopedia|title=Ibn T\u016bmart|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of Islam|publisher=[[Brill Publishers]]|url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/ibn-tumart-SIM_3395|last=Hopkins|first=J.F.P.|date=|edition=2nd|page=958}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NFfJAwAAQBAJ|title=Muslim Spain and Portugal: A Political History of Al-Andalus|last=Kennedy|first=Hugh|date=|publisher=Routledge|year=2014|isbn=9781317870418|location=|pages=197|language=en|quote=|via=}}</ref> His father belonged to the Hargha and his mother to the Masakkala, both of which are divisions of the Masmuda tribal confederation.<ref name=\"EI2\" />\n\nHis name is given alternatively as Muhammad ibn Abdallah or Muhammad ibn Tumart. [[Al-Baydhaq]] reported that \"Tumart\" was actually his father Abdallah's nickname (\"Tumart\" or \"Tunart\" comes from the [[Berber language]] and means \"good fortune\", \"delight\" or \"happiness\", and makes it an equivalent of the Arabic name \"[[Saad]]\". As it was noted by [[Ahmed Toufiq]] in his research about [[Ibn al-Zayyat al-Tadili]]'s famous book ''at-Tashawof'', many early Sufi saints held this name in Morocco).<ref>{{cite book|title=at-Tashawof|origyear=1220|date=1997|author=[[Ibn al-Zayyat al-Tadili]]|author2=[[Ahmed Toufiq]] }}</ref><ref>[http://i-cias.com/e.o/i_tumart.htm ''Encyclopaedia of the Orient'' - Ibn Tumart]</ref> Ibn Khaldun reports that Muhammad ibn Tumart himself was very pious as a child, and that he was nicknamed ''Asafu'' (Berber for \"firebrand\" or \"lover of light\") for his habit of lighting candles at mosques.<ref>Dramani Issifou (1988) \"Islam as a social system in Africa since the seventh century\", in M. Elfasi, editor, ''General History of Africa, Africa from the Seventh to the Eleventh Century'', ch.4, p. 99</ref>\n\nIbn Tumart came from a humble family and his father was a lamp-lighter at the mosque.<ref>History of [[Ibn Khaldun]]</ref> By his own declaration and that of his followers, he claimed to be descendant of [[Idriss I]], a descendant of Hassan, the grandson of the Prophet [[Muhammad]], who took refuge in Morocco in the 8th-century.<ref>For an attempt to trace this professed Sharifian lineage, see Ibn Khallikan's entry.</ref> However, and despite being supported by [[Ibn Khaldun]], this ascendency is today largely disputed.<ref name=\"EI2\" /> At the time, it was common for Berber leaders and tribes to claim a [[Sharif]] lineage in order to gain religious authority.<ref>Even today the claim of Shariffian lineage of Morocco's current ruling dynasty, the [[Alaouite dynasty|Alaouites]], is largely disputed</ref>\n\nAt the time, Morocco, [[al-Andalus]] and large parts of [[Maghreb]], were ruled by the [[Almoravids]], a [[Maliki]] puritanical [[Sanhaja|Saharan Sanhaja]] Berber movements, who founded the city of [[Marrakesh]] and are credited with spreading Islam to much of [[West Africa]]. To pursue his education, Ibn Tumart went as a young man (c.&nbsp;1106) to [[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain|Qortoba]], which was at the time the biggest centre of learning in the Almoravids dominion, where he was a disciple of [[at-Turtushi]]. Thereafter, Ibn Tumart went east to deepen his studies where he came under the influence [[al-Ghazali]]'s ideas (Almohad historians support that he met and studied under al-Ghazali, but modern historians maintain that it is unknown whether this encounter actually happened).<ref>Julian, p. 93; Ibn Khallikan, p.206</ref> He appears in [[Baghdad]] soon after, and there he attached himself to the [[Ash'ari]]te school of theology and the [[Zahiri]]te school of jurisprudence, but with the creed of [[Ibn Hazm]] which differed significantly from early Zahirites in its rejection of [[Taqlid]] and reliance on reason.<ref>De Lacy O'leary, ''Arabic Thought and Its Place in History'', p. 249. Courier Dover Publications, 1939. {{ISBN|9780486149554}}</ref>\n\n=== Doctrines ===\n\nIt was probably while in Baghdad that Ibn Tumart began to develop a system of his own by combining the teachings of his Ash'arite masters with parts of the doctrines of others, with a touch of [[Sufism|Sufi]] mysticism imbibed from the great teacher [[al-Ghazali]].<ref name=kojiro>[[Kojiro Nakamura]], \"Ibn Mada's Criticism of Arab Grammarians.\" ''Orient'', v. 10, pp. 89\u2013113. 1974</ref> Hagiographers report that Ibn Tumart was in al-Ghazali's presence when news arrived that the Almoravids had proscribed and publicly burned his recent great work, ''Ihya' Ulum al-Din'', upon which al-Ghazali is said to have turned to Ibn Tumart and charged him, as a native of those lands, with the mission of setting the Almoravids right.<ref name = kennedy/>\n\nIbn Tumart's main principle was a rigid unitarianism (''[[tawhid]]'') which denied the existence of the [[God in Islam#Other attributes|attributes of God]] as incompatible with his unity and therefore [[Shirk (Islam)|a polytheistic idea]].<ref name=kojiro/> Ibn Tumart represented a revolt against what he perceived as [[anthropomorphism]] in the Muslim orthodoxy, but he was a rigid predestinarian and a strict observer of the law. He laid the blame for the \"theological flaws\" of the nation upon the ruling dynasty of the Almoravids. Ibn Thumart strongly opposed their sponsorship of the [[Maliki]] school of jurisprudence, whom he accused of neglecting the [[Sunnah]] and [[Hadith]] (traditions and sayings of the Prophet and his companions) and relying too much on ''[[ijma]]'' (consensus of jurists) and other sources, an anathema to the stricter [[Zahiri]]sm favored by Ibn Tumart. Ibn Tumart condemned the subtle reasoning of Maliki scholars as \"innovations\" (''[[bid\u2018ah]]''), obscurantist, perverse and possibly heretical (a charge previously made by Ibn Hazm and al-Ghazali, and the main reason why their works were proscribed by Almoravid authorities.).<ref name=kojiro/> Ibn Tumart also blamed the Almoravid governance for the latitude he found in Maghrebi society, notably the public sale of wine and pork in the markets, something the [[Qur'an]] forbids. Another reform was the destruction or hiding of any type of religious art in mosques. His rule and the rule of the Almohads after were [[Almohad reforms|full of reforms]] that attempted to turn the area under his control into a place where his doctrines held sway.\n\nIbn Tumart's followers took up the name \"''al-Muwwahidun''\", meaning those who affirm the unity of God. Spanish authors wrote that down as \"''Almohades''\", by which \"Almohads\" entered other languages.\n\n=== Return to the Maghreb ===\n\nAfter his studies in Baghdad, Ibn Tumart is claimed in one account to have proceeded on pilgrimage to [[Mecca]] (''[[hajj]]''), but was so bubbling with Ash'arite doctrines and a one-minded zeal to 'correct' the mores of the people he came across that he quickly made a nuisance of himself and was expelled from the city.<ref>Ibn Khallikan, p. 206</ref> He proceeded to [[Cairo]], and thereon to [[Alexandria]], where he took a ship back to the [[Maghreb]] in 1117/18. The journey was not without incident - Ibn Tumart took it upon himself to toss the ship's flasks of wine overboard and set about lecturing (or harassing) the sailors to ensure they adhered to correct prayer times and number of genuflections; in some reports, the sailors got fed up and threw Ibn Tumart overboard, only to find him still bobbing a half-day later and fished him back (he is also reported in different chronicles of having either caused or calmed a storm at sea).<ref>Wasserstein (2003)</ref>\n\nAfter touching at [[Tripoli]], Ibn Tumart landed in [[Mahdia]] and proceed on to [[Tunis]] and then [[B\u00e9ja\u00efa|Bejaia]], preaching a puritan, simplistic Islam along the way. Waving his puritan's staff among crowds of listeners, Ibn Tumart complained of the mixing of sexes in public, the production of wine and music, and the fashion of veiling men unveiling women (a custom among the [[Sanhaja]] Berbers of the [[Sahara Desert]], that had spread to urban centers with the Almoravids). Setting himself up on the steps of mosques and schools, Ibn Tumart challenged everyone who came close to debate \u2013 unwary Maliki jurists and scholars frequently got an earful.\n\nHis antics and fiery preaching prompted fed-up authorities to hustle him along from town to town. After being expelled from [[Bejaia]], Ibn Tumart set himself up c.1119 at an encampment in [[Mellala]] (a few miles south of the city), where he began receiving his first followers and adherents. Among these were al-Bashir (a scholar, who would become his chief strategist), [[Abd al-Mu'min]] (a [[Zenata]] Berber who would become his eventual successor) and [[Mohammed al-Baydhaq|Abu Bakr Muhammad al-Baydhaq]] (who would later write the ''Kitab al-Ansab'', the chronicle of the Almohads.) It was at Mellala that Ibn Tumart and his close companions began forging a plan of political action.\n\nIn 1120, Ibn Tumart and his small band of followers headed west into [[Morocco]]. He stopped by [[Fes, Morocco|Fez]], the intellectual capital of Morocco, and engaged in polemical debates with the leading Malikite scholars of the city. Having exhausted them, the ''[[ulama]]'' of Fez decided they had enough and expelled him from the city. He proceeded south, hurried along from town to town like a vagabond (reportedly, he and his companions had to swim across the [[Bou Regreg]], as they could not afford the ferry passage). Shortly after his arrival in [[Marrakesh]], Ibn Tumart is said to have successfully sought out the Almoravid ruler [[Ali ibn Yusuf]] at a local mosque. In the famous encounter, when ordered to acknowledge the presence of the emir, Ibn Tumart reportedly replied \"Where is the emir? I see only women here!\" - an insulting reference to the [[tagelmust]] veil worn by the Almoravid ruling class.<ref>Messier (2010: p. 141)</ref> (According to one source, Ibn Tumart attacked the emir's own sister for going unveiled).\n\nCharged with fomenting rebellion, Ibn Tumart defended himself before the emir and his leading advisors. Presenting himself as a mere scholar, a voice for reform, Ibn Tumart set about lecturing the emir and his leading advisors about the dangers of innovations and the centrality of the Sunnah. When the emir's own scholars reminded him the Almoravids too embraced puritanical ideals, and were committed to the Sunnah, Ibn Tumart pointed out that the Almoravids professed puritanism had been clouded and deviated by \"obscurantists\", drawing attention to the ample evidence of laxity and impiety that prevailed in their dominions. When countered that at least on points of doctrine, there was little difference between them, Ibn Tumart brought out more emphasis on his own peculiar doctrines on the ''tawhid'' and the attributes. After a lengthy examination, the Almoravid jurists of Marrakesh concluded Ibn Tumart, however learned, was blasphemous and dangerous, insinuating he was probably a [[Kharijite]] agitator, and recommended he should be executed or imprisoned. The Almoravid emir, however, decided to merely expel him from the city, after a [[flogging]] of fourteen lashes.<ref name = kennedy/>  \n  \nIbn Tumart proceeded to [[Aghmat]] and immediately resumed his old behavior - destroying every jug of wine in sight, haranguing passers-by for impious behavior or dress, engaging locals in controversial debate. The ulama of Aghmat complained to the emir, who changed his mind and decided to have Ibn Tumart arrested after all. He was saved by the timely intervention of Abu Ibrahim Ismail Ibn Yasallali al-Hazraji (\"Ismail Igig\"), a prominent chieftain of the Hazraja tribe of the Masmuda, who helped him escape the city. Ibn Tumart took the road towards the Sous valley, to hide among his own people, the Haghra.\n\n=== Cave of Igiliz ===\n\nBefore the end of 1120, Ibn Tumart arrived at his home village of Igiliz in the Sous valley (exact location uncertain).<ref>See Fromherz (2005).</ref> Almost immediately, Ibn Tumart set himself up in a nearby mountain cave (a conscious echo of the Prophet Muhammad's withdraw to the cave of [[Cave of Hira|Hira]]). His bizarre retreat, his ascetic lifestyle, probably combined with rumors of his being a [[faith healer]] and small miracle-worker, gave the local people the initial impression that he was a [[Wali|holy man]] with supernatural powers (a point de-emphasized by later hagiographers).<ref name = kennedy/> But he soon set about spreading his principal message of puritanical reform. He preached in vernacular [[Berber languages|Berber]]. His oratory skill and crowd-moving eloquence are frequently referred to in the chronicles.\n\nTowards the end of [[Ramadan]] in late 1121, in a particularly moving sermon, Ibn Tumart reviewed his failure to persuade the Almoravids to reform by argument. After the sermon, having already claimed to be a [[sayyid|descendant]] of [[Muhammad]], Ibn Tumart suddenly 'revealed' himself as the true [[Mahdi]], the expected divinely guided justicer. He was promptly recognized as such by his audience. This was effectively a declaration of war on the Almoravid state. For to reject or resist the Mahdi's interpretations was equivalent to resisting God, and thus punishable with death as [[apostasy]].<ref name = kennedy/>\n\n(Notions of ''mahdism'' were not unfamiliar in this part of Morocco - not long before, the Sous valley had been a hotbed of [[Waqifite Shia|Waqafite Shi'iism]], a remnant of [[Fatimid]] influence, and descendance from the Prophet had been the principle recommendation of the fondly remembered [[Idrisid]]s).\n\nAt some point he was visited by [[Abu Hafs Umar ibn Yahya al-Hintati]] (\"Umar Hintati\"), a prominent [[Hintata]] chieftain (and stem of the future [[Hafsid]]s). Omar Hintati was immediately impressed and invited Ibn Tumart to take refuge among the [[Masmuda]] tribes of the [[High Atlas]], where he would be better protected from the Almoravid authorities. In 1122, Ibn Tumart abandoned his cave and climbed up the High Atlas.<ref name = kennedy/>\n\nIn later years, Ibn Tumart's path from the cave of Igiliz to mountain fort of Tinmel - another conscious echo of the Prophet's life (the ''[[Hijra (Islam)|hijra]]'' from Mecca to Medina) - would become a popular pilgrimage route for the Almohad faithful. The cave itself was preserved as a shrine for many years, where apparently Almohad partisans, regardless of their origin or background, would ceremonially reject their past affiliations and be \"adopted\" into Ibn Tumart's Hargha tribe).<ref>Fromherz (2005: p. 181)</ref>\n\n=== Tinmel and the Almohad rebellion ===\n[[image:Tinmel mosque.jpg|thumb|Mosque erected in 1156 in honor of Ibn Tumart at [[Tinmel]], once part of a large fortified complex, the first headquarters of the [[Almohads]].]]\n\nIbn Tumart urged his followers to arms in open revolt against the [[Almoravid]]s, to fulfill the mission of purifying the Almoravid state. In 1122, or shortly thereafter (c. 1124<ref>Messier (2010:148)</ref>) he founded a [[ribat]] at [[Tinmel]] (or 'Tin Mal', meaning \"(she who is) white\"), in a small valley of the Nfis in the middle of the High Atlas. Tinmel was an impregnable fortified complex, which would serve both as spiritual center and military headquarters of the Almohad rebellion. It is during this period that he wrote a series of monographs on various doctrines for the instruction of his men. These disparate works were later collected and compiled in 1183\u201384, on the order of the Almohad caliph Yusuf ibn Abd al-Ma'mun (later translated in French in 1903, under the title ''Livre d'Ibn Toumert''.)\n\nSix principal [[Masmuda]] tribes adhered to the Almohad rebellion: Ibn Tumart's own Hargha tribe (from the [[Anti-Atlas]]) and the Ganfisa, the Gadmiwa, the Hintata, the Haskura and the Hazraja (roughly from west to east, along the [[High Atlas]] range).<ref>Julien, p.99</ref>\n\n[[image:Almohad_Masmuda_tribes.png|thumb|400px|Approximate locations of the main Masmuda tribes that adhered to the Almohads]]\nFor the next eight years, the Almohad revolt was largely confined to an irresolute guerilla war through the ravines and peaks of the Atlas range. The principal damage done by the Almohads at this stage was the disruption of Almoravid tax-collection, and rendering insecure (or altogether impassable) the roads and mountain passes south of Marrakesh. The [[Sous]] valley, surrounded on three sides by Almohadist Masmuda mountaineers, was nearly cut off and isolated. Of more particular concern to the Almoravids was their threat to the [[Ourika River|Ourika]] and [[Tizi n'Tichka]] passes, that connected Marrakesh to the [[Draa River|Draa]] valley on the other side of the High Atlas. These were the principal routes to the all-important city of [[Sijilmassa]], gateway of the [[trans-Saharan trade]], by which gold came from west Africa to Morocco. But the Almoravids were unable to send enough manpower through the narrow passes to dislodge the Almohad rebels from their easily defended mountain strongpoints. The Almoravid authorities reconciled themselves to setting up strongpoints to confine them (most famously the fortress of [[Tasghimout]] that protected the approach to [[Aghmat]]), while exploring alternative routes through more easterly passes.<ref name = kennedy/><ref>Messier, 2010: p.153-54)</ref>\n\nIbn Tumart's closest companion and chief strategist, al-Bashir, took upon himself the role of political commissar, enforcing doctrinal discipline among the Masmuda tribesmen, often with a heavy head. This culminated in an infamous purge (''tamyiz'') conducted by al-Bashir in the winter of 1129\u201330, with mass executions of disloyal partisans, which has been characterized as a brief \"reign of terror\".<ref name = kennedy/><ref>Messier (2010: p. 149) reports 15,000 men of Tinmel area were killed, and their wives and belongings distributed among the Almohad warriors.</ref>\n\n=== Battle of al-Buhayra ===\n\nIn early 1130, the Almohads finally descended from the mountains for their first sizeable attack on the Almoravids in the lowlands. It was a disaster. Al-Bashir (others report Abd al-Mu'min<ref>Messier (2010: p. 150\u201351)</ref>) led the Almohad armies first against [[Aghmat]]. They quickly defeated the Almoravid force that came out the meet them, and then chased their fleeing remnant back to [[Marrakesh]]. The Almohads set up a siege camp before Marrakesh, the first recorded siege of the Almoravid capital, whose walls had only recently been erected. The Almoravid emir Ali ibn Yusuf immediately called upon reinforcements from other parts of Morocco. After forty days of siege, in May (others date April 14, 1130<ref>Messier (2010: p. 151)</ref>), heartened by news of the approach of a relief column from Sijilmassa, the Almoravids sallied from Marrakesh in force and crushed the Almohads in the bloody [[Battle of al-Buhayra]] (named after a large garden east of the city). The Almohads were routed, suffering huge human losses - 12,000 men from the Hargha alone. Al-Bashir and several other leading figures were killed in action.<ref>''Encyclopedia of Islam'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=tPsUAAAAIAAJ&lpg=PA592&ots=tDnAHS-glP&dq=battle%20of%20al-Buhayra&pg=PA592#v=onepage&q&f=false p.592]</ref> If not for a sudden torrential rain that broke up the fighting and allowed the remnant to escape back to the mountains, the Almohads might have been finished off then and there.\n\nIn a bizarre and chilling footnote in the aftermath, it is said that Ibn Tumart returned to the battlefield at night with some of his followers, and ordered them to bury themselves in the field with a small straw to breathe by. Then, to invigorate the rest of the demoralized Almohads, he challenged those who doubted the righteousness of their cause, to go to the battlefield and ask the dead themselves if they were enjoying the blisses of heaven after falling in the fight for God's cause. When they heard the positive reply from the buried men, they were assuaged. To prevent the ruse from being revealed, it is said Ibn Thumart left them buried there, filling their straws so they would suffocate.<ref>[[James Edward Budgett-Meakin]], (1899) ''The Moorish Empire: a historical epitome'', London: Sonnenschein, [https://archive.org/details/ldpd_6769876_000/page/n94 p.69]</ref>\n\n== Almohads after Ibn Tumart ==\n\nIbn Tumart died in August 1130, only a few months after the disastrous defeat at al-Buhayra.<ref name = kennedy/> That the Almohad movement did not immediately collapse by the combined blows of the crushing defeat and large losses at the walls of Marrakesh, and the deaths of not only their spiritual leader, but also their chief military commanders, is testament to the careful organization that Ibn Tumart had built up at Tinmel.\n\nIbn Tumart had set up the Almohad commune as a minutely detailed pyramidical hierarchy with fourteen grades. At the top was the ''Ahl ad-Dar'' (the Mahdi's family), supplemented by a privy council known as the Council of Ten (''Ahl al-jam\u0101\u02bf\u0101'') which included the Ifriqiyan migrants who had first joined Ibn Tumart in Mellala. There was also a wider consultative \"Council of Fifty\", composed of the ''[[sheikh]]s'' of the major [[Masmuda]] Berber tribes - the Hargha (Ibn Tumart's tribe, which had primacy in the hierarchy among the tribes), the Ganfisa, the Gadmiwa, the Hintata, the Haskura and the Hazraja.<ref name = kennedy/> The Almohad military had been organized as arranged \"units\" named by tribe, with sub-units and internal hierarchies carefully and exactly spelled out. There were also organized groups of ''Talba'' and ''Huffaz'', the preachers that had been the original missionaries and spreaders of Ibn Tumart's message.\n\n===The Council of Ten===\n\nIbn Tumart organized the inner 'Council of Ten' (''Ahl al-jam\u0101\u02bf\u0101''), composed of the ten who had first borne witness to Ibn Tumart as ''Mahdi''. Several of them were drawn from the core of followers that Ibn Tumart had picked up in Ifriqiya (esp. while holding camp at [[Mallala, Algeria|Mallala]], outside of Bejaia, in 1119-20); others were local leaders drawn from the local Masmuda Berbers who had proven early adherents. Although the list has some variations and there is some dispute in names, the Council of Ten is frequently identified as follows:<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aOeLAi38h4YC|title=The Almohads: The Rise of an Islamic Empire|last=Fromherz|first=Allen J.|date=|publisher=I.B.Tauris|year=2012|isbn=9781780764054|location=|pages=123\u2013124|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{|align=\"left\" class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+\n! width=\"200\" | Name || Notes\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|[[Abd al-Mu'min]] ibn Ali||align=\"left\"|originally from Tagra (near [[Tlemcen]], modern Algeria), Abd al-Mu'min was a Berber of the Kumiya tribe of the [[Zenata]] confederation.<ref>Julien, p.93</ref> Abd al-Mu'min adhered at Mellala, and was given the appellation of \"Lamp of the Almohads\" (''Siraj al-Muwahhidin''). He became Almohad emir and the first Almohad caliph after Ibn Tumart's death in 1130.\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Omar ibn Ali al-Sanhaji (known as \"Omar Asanag\")|| align=\"left\" | a [[Sanhaja]] Berber, prob. adhered at Mellala Died c. 1142 of natural causes. Sometimes said to be the brother of the Almohad chronicler [[Mohammed al-Baydhaq|al-Baydhaq]].\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Abu al-Rabi' Sulayman ibn Makhluf al-Hadrami (known as \"Ibn al-Baqqal\") || align=\"left\" | from the people of Aghmat. His name was Arabized, he was known to the Berbers as bn al-Baqq\u0101l and Ibn T\u0101\u02bf\u1e0damiy\u012bt.\nKilled at battle of al-Buhayra in 1130.\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Abu Ibrahim Ismail Ibn Yasallali al-Hazraji (known as \"Ismail Igig\" or \"Ismail al-Hazraji\")|| align=\"left\" | chieftain of Hazraja tribe of the Masmuda, who spirited Ibn Tumart from Aghmat to the High Atlas in 1120. Later appointed to lead Ibn Tumart's own Hargha tribe.\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Abu 'Imran Musa ibn Tammara al-Gadmiwi|| align=\"left\" | chieftain of the Gadmiwa tribe of the Masmuda of the High Atlas. Killed at 1130 battle of al-Buhayra\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Abu Yahya Abu Bakr ibn Yiggit|| align=\"left\" | from the Hintata tribe. He was killed in the 1130 battle of al-Buhayra. His son would briefly serve as Almohad governor of Cordova.\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Abu Abd Allah Muhammad ibn Sula\u012bman|| align=\"left\" | originally from the Massakala tribe. He came from \u0100ns\u0101, an oasis in south of the Anti-Atlas.\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Abd Allah ibn Ya'la (known as \"Ibn Malwiya\") ||align=\"left\"|\nprob. adhered at Mellala, later appointed as ''sheikh'' of the Ganfisa tribe of the Masmuda. He disputed the succession with Abd al-Mu'min, but was defeated and executed in 1132.\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Abd Allah ibn Muhsin al-Wansharisi (known as \"al-Bashir\")|| align=\"left\" | A scholar from [[Oran]], prob. adhered at Mellala. He became Ibn Tumart's early right-hand-man and chief strategist and enforcer. Known as \"the Herald\" (''al-Bashir''), he was killed in the 1130 battle of al-Buhayra.\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Abu Hafs Umar ibn Yahya al-Hintati]] (known as \"Omar Hintata\" or \"Omar Inti\")|| align=\"left\" | chieftain of the [[Hintata]] tribe of the Masmuda of the High Atlas. Omar Hintata became the father-in-law and principal ally of [[Abd al-Mu'min]]. A major military leader, he is the stem of the later [[Hafsid dynasty]] of [[Ifriqiya]].\n|-\n|}\n\nOf the Council of Ten, five were killed at al-Buhayra in 1130, two died in subsequent years, and only three survived well into the height of the Almohad empire - [[Abd al-Mu'min]], Omar Hintata and Ismail al-Hazraji.\n\n=== Succession ===\n\nThe Almohad hagiographer al-Baydhaq claims that Ibn Tumart had already designated Abd al-Mu'min as his successor back in Bejaia. But it seems more probable (although passed over in the chronicles) that there was an intense power struggle for succession in the aftermath of Ibn Tumart's death.<ref name = kennedy/> With half the Council of Ten killed at al-Buhayra, Abd al-Mu'min laid claim as the \"successor\" of the Ibn Tumart (the term \"[[caliph]]\", as \"successor\" of the Mahdi emerged only later, in conscious imitation of the term's original use for the \"successors\" of the [[Prophet Muhammad]].) Abd al-Mu'min's claim was challenged by Ibn Malwiya (another survivor of the Ten) as well as by the Ahl al-Dar (Ibn Tumart's brothers).\n\nExactly how Abd al-Mu'min imposed himself is uncertain. As a [[Zenata]] Berber, Abd al-Mu'min was an alien among the Masmuda. But that foreignness itself might have recommended him as a neutral choice to the Masmuda ''sheikhs'', as it would avoid the appearance of favoritism towards any particular tribe. Nonetheless it is reported that the more easterly Masmuda tribes, the Haskura and the Harzaja, rejected Abd al-Mu'min's leadership and broke away from the Almohad coalition at this stage.<ref>Messier (2010: p. 153)</ref> Abd al-Mu'min would have to force them back to the fold. (Ibn Khaldun reports (improbably) that Abd al-Ma'mun managed to conceal the death of Ibn Tumart for nearly two years, in order to gather allies and marry the daughter of Omar Hintati, who would become his principal ally.) His principal rival Ibn Malwiya was captured, condemned and executed by 1132, and Ibn Tumart's own family soon disappears from significance, their roles eclipsed by Abd al-Mu'min's own family, the future dynasty of Almohad caliphs. Whatever doubts lingered about Abd al-Mu'min's leadership certainly dissipated a decade later, when Abd al-Mu'min led the renewed Almohads down from the mountains on a seven-year campaign of conquest of Morocco, culminating in the fall of Marrakesh in 1147.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Written by Ibn Tumart===\n* {{in lang|ar}} ''Le livre de Mohammed Ibn Toumert, mahdi des Almohades'', 1903 edition, [[Ign\u00e1c Goldziher]], editor, [[Algiers]]: P. Fontana. [https://books.google.com/books?id=J24XAAAAIAAJ&pg=PT607#v=onepage&q&f=false full text online]; [http://www.ghazali.org/books/goldziher-1903.pdf introduction (Fr)]\n*  {{in lang|ar|fr}} [[\u00c9variste L\u00e9vi-Proven\u00e7al]] (1928), editor, ''Documents in\u00e9dits d'histoire almohade: fragments manuscrits du \"Legajo\" 1919 du fonds arabe de l'Escurial''. [[Paris]]: Geuthner.\n\n===Written about Ibn Tumart===\n\n* {{in lang|fr}} Bourouiba, Rachid (1966) \"A propos de la date de naissance d\u2019Ibn Tumart\", ''Revue d'Histoire et de Civilisation du Maghreb'', January, pp.&nbsp;19\u2013 25.\n* [[Vincent Cornell|Cornell, Vincent J.]] (1987) \"Understanding Is the Mother of Ability: Responsibility and action in the do